}}\n{{s-sports}}\n{{succession box| before=[[Ulrich Vinzents]]| title=[[Malm\u00f6 FF]]<br />[[List of Malm\u00f6 FF players#Club captains|Captain]]| years=2013| after=[[Guillermo Molins]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hamad, Jiloan}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Baku]]\n[[Category:Iraqi footballers]]\n[[Category:Iraq international footballers]]\n[[Category:Swedish footballers]]\n[[Category:Sweden youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Sweden under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Sweden international footballers]]\n[[Category:Swedish people of Iraqi descent]]\n[[Category:Swedish people of Kurdish descent]]\n[[Category:BK Forward players]]\n[[Category:Malm\u00f6 FF players]]\n[[Category:TSG 1899 Hoffenheim players]]\n[[Category:Standard Li\u00e8ge players]]\n[[Category:Hammarby Fotboll players]]\n[[Category:Incheon United FC players]]\n[[Category:HNK Gorica players]]\n[[Category:Allsvenskan players]]\n[[Category:Bundesliga players]]\n[[Category:K League 1 players]]\n[[Category:Belgian First Division A players]]\n[[Category:Croatian First Football League players]]\n[[Category:Kurdish sportspeople]]\n[[Category:Swedish expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Swedish expatriate sportspeople in Germany]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Germany]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Croatia]]\n[[Category:Association football wingers]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo/generalfixes, replaced: anfootballer\u2192 afootballer, clubs campaign \u2192 club's campaign, teams matches \u2192 team's matches", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jiloan_Hamad"}
{"title_page": "African sacred ibis", "text_new": "{{Speciesbox\n|name=African sacred ibis\n|status=LC\n|status_system=IUCN3.1\n|status_ref=<ref name=iucn>{{cite iucn |author=[[BirdLife International]] |year=2018 |title=''Threskiornis aethiopicus'' |volume=2018 |page=e.T22697510A132068562 |doi=10.2305/IUCN.UK.2018-2.RLTS.T22697510A132068562.en }}</ref>\n|image=Threskiornis aethiopicus -Mida Creek mud flats, Kenya-8.jpg\n|image_caption=Foraging in Mida Creek mud flats, Kenya\n|taxon=Threskiornis aethiopicus\n|authority=([[John Latham (ornithologist)|Latham]], 1790)\n|synonyms=''Tantalus aethiopicus'' <small>Latham, 1790</small>\n|range_map=ThreskiornisAethiopicusIUCNver2018 2.png\n|range_map_caption=Native and introduced ranges''\n}}\n[[File:Helig Ibis - Ystad 26 dec 2015.ogv|thumb|African sacred ibis in [[Ystad]], [[Sweden]]]]\nThe '''African sacred ibis''' (''Threskiornis aethiopicus'') is a species of [[ibis]], a wading [[bird]] of the family [[Threskiornithidae]]. It is native to Africa and the Middle East. It is especially known for its role in the religion of the [[Ancient Egypt]]ians, where it was linked to the god [[Thoth]].\n\n== Taxonomy ==\nIt is very closely related to the [[black-headed ibis]] and the [[Australian white ibis]], with which it forms a [[Species complex|superspecies complex]], so much so that the three species are considered [[Biological specificity#Conspecific|conspecific]] by some [[Ornithology|ornithologists]].<ref name=CABI>{{cite web |url=https://www.cabi.org/isc/datasheet/62201 |title=''Threskiornis aethiopicus'' (sacred ibis) |last=Clergeau |first=Philippe |date=14 July 2009 |publisher=Invasive Species Compendium - CAB International |location=Wallingford, UK |access-date=9 April 2018}}</ref> In mixed flocks these ibises often hybridise.<ref>{{cite book |last=McCarthy |first=Eugene M. |date=2006 |title=Handbook of Avian Hybrids of the World |location=Oxford |publisher=Oxford University Press |page=193 |isbn=978-0195183238}}</ref> The Australian white ibis is often called the sacred ibis colloquially.<ref name=Klemann>{{cite web |url=http://www.michelklemann.nl/ibis/restoftheworld.html |title=Heilige Ibis (''Threskiornis aethiopicus'') |last=Klemann |first=Michel |date=n.d. |language=nl, en |access-date=7 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nAlthough known to the ancient civilisations of Greece, Rome and especially Africa, ibises were unfamiliar to western Europeans from the fall of Rome until the 19th century, and mentions of this bird in the ancient works of these civilisations were supposed to describe some type of [[curlew]] or other bird, and were thus translated as such.<ref name=Buffon>{{cite book |last=Leclerc Comte de Buffon |first=Georges-Louis |translator-last=Smellie |translator-first=William |date=1812 |title=Histoire Naturelle, g\u00e9n\u00e9rale et particuli\u00e8re, avec la description du Cabinet du Roi vol. 19 |trans-title=Natural History, General and Particular |edition=2nd |location=London |publisher=T. Cadell and W. Davies |pages=1\u201316}}</ref> In 1758, [[Carl Linnaeus|Linnaeus]] was convinced that the ancient authors were describing a [[cattle egret]] (''Bubulcus ibis''), which he thus described as ''Ardea ibis''.<ref>{{cite book |last=Linnaeus |first=Carolus |date=1758 |title=Systema naturae per regna tria naturae :secundum classes, ordines, genera, species, cum characteribus, differentiis, synonymis, locis |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/10277#page/159/mode/1up |language=Latin |volume=1 |edition=10 |location=Stockholm |publisher=Laurentii Salvii (Impensis Direct) |pages=140, 141, 144 |doi=10.5962/bhl.title.542|hdl=2027/hvd.32044106464480 }}</ref> Following the work of [[Mathurin Jacques Brisson]], who calls it ''Ibis candida'' in 1760, in the 12th edition of his [[Systema Naturae]] of 1766 Linnaeus classifies it as ''Tantalus ibis''.<ref>{{cite book |last=Brisson |first=Mathurin Jacques |date=1760 |title=Ornithologie, ou, M\u00e9thode contenant la division des oiseaux en ordres, sections, genres, especes & leurs vari\u00e9t\u00e9s |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/111922#page/467/mode/1up |language=Latin, French |volume=5 |location=Paris |publisher=Cl. Joannem-Baptistam Bauche |pages=349\u2013350 |doi=10.5962/bhl.title.51902}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Linnaeus |first=Carolus |date=1766 |title=Systema naturae per regna tria naturae :secundum classes, ordines, genera, species, cum characteribus, differentiis, synonymis, locis |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/137337#page/245/mode/1up |language=Latin |volume=1 |issue=1 |edition=12 |location=Stockholm |publisher=Laurentii Salvii (Impensis Direct) |page=241 |doi=10.5962/bhl.title.68927|hdl=2027/hvd.32044106464431 }}</ref> These were also unfamiliar birds that did not occur in Europe at the time, in English in these times called the 'Egyptian ibis' by [[John Latham (ornithologist)|Latham]], and the 'emseesy' or 'ox-bird' by [[George Shaw]].<ref name=Latham>{{cite book |last=Latham |first=John |date=1790 |title=Index ornithologicus, sive, Systema ornithologiae |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/226469#page/246/mode/1up |language=Latin |volume=2 |location=London |publisher=Sumptibus authoris (self published) |pages=706, 709 |doi=10.5962/bhl.title.131313}}</ref>\n\nIn 1790, [[John Latham (ornithologist)|John Latham]] provided the first unambiguous modern scientific description of the sacred ibis as ''Tantalus aethiopicus'', mentioning [[James Bruce|James Bruce of Kinnaird]] who called it 'abou hannes' in his writings describing his travels in Sudan and Ethiopia, and also described ''Tantalus melanocephalus'' of India.<ref name=Latham/>\n\n[[Georges Cuvier]] named it ''Ibis religiosus'' in his ''[[Le R\u00e8gne Animal]]'' of 1817.\n\nIn 1842, [[George Robert Gray]] reclassified the bird under the new genus ''Threskiornis'', because the type of the genus ''Tantalus'' was designated as to be the [[Wood stork#Taxonomy and etymology|wood stork]], also formerly known as the wood ibis or wood pelican, and Gray decided these birds could not be classified in the same genus.<ref>{{cite book |last=Gray |first=George Robert |date=1842 |title=Appendix to A List of the Genera of Birds |url=https://archive.org/stream/appendixtolistof00gray#page/13/mode/1up |location=London |publisher=Richard and John E. Taylor |page=13 |doi=10.5962/bhl.title.119636}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.zoonomen.net/cit/RI/Genera/T/t00113a.jpg |title=Images of the cards in the Richmond Index |last=Richmond |first=Charles W. |date=n.d. |location=Washington D.C. |publisher=Bird Division, National Museum of Natural History |access-date=19 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn a comprehensive review of plumage patterns by Holyoak in 1970, it was noted that the three taxons were extremely similar and that the Australian birds resembled ''Threskiornis aethiopicus'' in adult plumage and ''T. melanocephalus'' in juvenile plumage, he thus proposed they all be considered part of a single species ''T. aethiopicus''. At the time this was generally accepted by the scientific community, however in 'The Birds of the Western Palearctic' compendium of 1977, Roselaar advocated splitting the group into 4 species, recognising [[Malagasy sacred ibis|''T. bernieri'']], based again on the then known geographical morphological differences.<ref name=Lowe&Richards>{{cite journal |last=Lowe |first=K. W. |last2=Richards |first2=G. C. |date=1991 |title=Morphological Variation in the Sacred Ibis ''Threskiornis aethiopicus'' Superspecies Complex |url=http://cescos.fau.edu/gawliklab/papers/LoweRichards1991_SAIB.pdf |journal=Emu |volume=91 |issue=1 |pages=41\u201345 |doi=10.1071/MU9910041 |access-date=18 April 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180418225850/http://cescos.fau.edu/gawliklab/papers/LoweRichards1991_SAIB.pdf |archive-date=18 April 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn 1990, Sibley & Monroe, in the general reference 'Distribution and Taxonomy of Birds of the World' followed Roselaar in recognising 4 species, which they repeated in 'A World Checklist of Birds' of 1993.<ref name=iucn/>\n\nThis taxon being split from ''T. melanocephalus'' and ''T. molucca'' was further advocated by another morphological study by Lowe and Richards in 1991, where, like Holyoak, they looked at plumage again but used much more skins, but unlike him concluded that the differences were such to merit separate species status for the three taxons, especially as they could find no intergradation in morphological characters in possible contact zones in SE Asia. They also cite purported differences in courtship displays between the Australian and Asian birds. Based on these characteristics they recommended the Malagasy birds be considered a subspecies of ''T. aethiopicus''.<ref name=Lowe&Richards/>\n\nIn 2003, Birdlife International elected to adopt the narrow taxonomic concept as advocated in Sibley & Monroe 1993.<ref name=iucn/>\n\n== Description ==\n[[File:Threskiornis aethiopicus - Durban -South Africa-8.jpg|thumb|Flying in South Africa]]\nAn adult individual is {{convert|68|cm|in|abbr=on}} long with all-white body [[plumage]] apart from dark plumes on the rump. Wingspan is {{convert|112|to|124|cm|in|abbr=on}} and body weight {{convert|1.35|to|1.5|kg|lb|abbr=on}}.<ref name=adw>{{cite web|last=Ramsey|first=C.|title=''Threskiornis aethiopicus''|url=http://animaldiversity.org/accounts/Threskiornis_aethiopicus/|work=University of Michigan Museum of Zoology|publisher=Animal Diversity Web}}</ref><ref name=anc>{{cite web|title=''Sacred Ibis Bird''|url=https://animalcorner.co.uk/animals/sacred-ibis-bird/|publisher=Animal Corner}}</ref> Males are generally slightly larger than females.<ref>{{cite web|title=African sacred ibis|url=https://www.sa-venues.com/wildlife/birds_sacred_ibis.htm|publisher=sa-venues}}</ref>\n\nThe bald head and neck, thick curved bill and legs are black. The white wings show a black rear border in flight. The eyes are brown with a dark red [[orbital ring]].<ref name=adw/> Sexes are similar, but juveniles have dirty white plumage, a smaller bill and some feathering on the neck, greenish-brown scapulars and more black on the primary coverts.<ref name=adw/>\n\nThis bird is usually silent, but occasionally makes some croaking noises, unlike its vocal relative, the [[hadada ibis]].\n\n== Distribution ==\n=== Native ===\nThe sacred ibis breeds in [[Sub-Saharan Africa]] and southeastern [[Iraq]]. A number of populations are migrant with the rains; some of the South African birds migrate 1,500&nbsp;km as far north as Zambia, the African birds north of the equator migrate in the opposite direction. The Iraqi population usually migrates to southwestern Iran, but wandering vagrants have been seen as far south as Oman (rare, but regular) and as far north as the Caspian coasts of Kazakhstan and Russia (before 1945).<ref name=AEWA1999>{{cite report |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=March 1999 |title=Report on the Conservation Status of Migratory Waterbirds in the Agreement Area|url=http://www.unep-aewa.org/sites/default/files/publication/ts1_conservation_status_report_wi_0.pdf|publisher=Wetlands International, for the Agreement on the Conservation of African-Eurasian Migratory Waterbirds Secretariat |pages= 20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unep-aewa.org/en/species/threskiornis-aethiopicus-0|title=''Threskiornis aethiopicus''|publisher=United Nations Environment Programme (UNEP), Agreement on the Conservation of African-Eurasian Migratory Waterbirds (AEWA)|access-date= 29 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite report |last=Watson |first=Mike |date=2014 |title=BirdQuest Tour Report: Oman & Bahrain 2014 |url=http://www.birdquest-tours.com/pdfs/report/OMAN%20-%20BAHRAIN%20REP%2014-ebook.pdf |publisher=Birdquest Tours |pages=20, 26}}</ref><ref name=Y\u00e9sou>{{cite journal |last= Y\u00e9sou|first= Pierre|last2= Clergeau|first2=Philippe |date=2005 |title= Sacred Ibis: a new invasive species in Europe|url=http://www.birdingworld.co.uk/images/SacredIbises.pdf |journal=Birding World |volume=18 |issue=12 |pages=517\u2013526 |access-date=9 January 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==== Africa ====\nIt was formerly found in [[Egypt]], where it was commonly venerated and mummified as a votive offering to the god [[Thoth]]. For many centuries until the Roman period the main temples buried a few dozen of thousands of birds a year, and to sustain sufficient numbers for the demand for sacrifices by pilgrims from all over Egypt, dozens of ibis breeding farms (called ''ibiotropheia'' by [[Herodotus]]) were established, initially throughout Egypt, but later centralised around the main temples, each producing around a thousand mummies annually.<ref name=Wasef>Wasef, Sally A. (2016); \"Ancient Egyptian Sacred Ibis Mummies: Evolutionary Mitogenomics Resolves the History of Ancient Farming\". Thesis (PhD Doctorate); Griffith University; Brisbane</ref> [[Aristotle]] mentions in c. 350 BC that many sacred ibises are found all over Egypt.<ref>{{cite book |author=Aristotle (c. 350 BC) |translator-last=Thompson |translator-first=D'Arcy Wentworth |title=\u03a4\u1ff6\u03bd \u03c0\u03b5\u03c1\u1f76 \u03c4\u1f70 \u03b6\u1ff7\u03b1 \u1f31\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03c1\u03b9\u1ff6\u03bd |trans-title=History of Animals |url=http://classics.mit.edu/Aristotle/history_anim.9.ix.html |volume=Book IX, prt 27}}</ref> [[Strabo]], writing around 20 AD, mentions large amounts of the birds in the streets of [[Alexandria]], where he was living at the time; picking through the trash, attacking provisions, and defiling everything with their dung.<ref name=Buffon/> [[Pierre Belon]] notes the many ibises in Egypt during his travels there in the late 1540s (he thought they were an odd type of stork).<ref name=Buffon/> [[Beno\u00eet de Maillet]], in his ''Description de l'Egypte'' (1735) relates that at the turn of the 17th century, when the great caravans travelled yearly to Mecca, great clouds of ibises would follow them from Egypt for over a hundred leagues into the desert to feed on the dung left at the encampments.<ref name=Buffon/> By 1850, however, the species had disappeared from Egypt both as a breeding and migrant population, with the last, albeit questionable, sighting in 1864.<ref name=Wasef/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chn-france.org/eorc/eorc.php?id_content=4/|title=''Updated Checklist of the Birds of Egypt''|publisher=Comit\u00e9 d'Homologation National for the Egyptian Ornithological Rarities Committee|access-date= 29 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe species did not breed in southern Africa before the beginning of the 20th century, but it has benefited from irrigation, dams, and commercial agricultural practices such as dung heaps, carrion and refuse tips. It began to breed in the early 20th century, and in the 1970s the first colonies of ibises were recorded in Zimbabwe and South Africa. Its population for example expanded 2-3-fold during the period between 1972\u20131995 in [[Orange Free State]]. It is now found throughout southern Africa.<ref name=Marion>{{cite journal | last1 = Marion | first1 = L. | year = 2013| title = Is the Sacred ibis a real threat to biodiversity? Long-term study of its diet in non-native areas compared to native areas. | url = | journal = Comptes Rendus Biologies | volume = 336 | issue = | pages = 207\u2013220 | doi = 10.1016/j.crvi.2013.05.001 | pmid = 23849724 }}</ref><ref name=Kopij1999>{{cite journal |last=Kopij |first=Grzegorz |date=1999 |title=Breeding ecology of the Sacred Ibis ''Threskiornis aethiopicus'' in the Free State, South Africa |url=http://cescos.fau.edu/gawliklab/papers/KopijG1999.pdf |journal=South African Journal Wildlife Research |volume=29 |issue=1 |pages=25\u201330 |issn=0379-4369 |access-date=10 April 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180330080216/http://cescos.fau.edu/gawliklab/papers/KopijG1999.pdf |archive-date=30 March 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The species is a common resident in most parts of South Africa. Local numbers are swollen in summer by individuals migrating southwards from the equator.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://dewetswild.com/2016/11/25/african-sacred-ibis/ |title=African Sacred Ibis - de Wets Wild |last=de Wets |first=Dries |date=November 25, 2016 |access-date=29 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nElsewhere in Africa it occurs throughout the continent south of the Sahara, but it is largely absent in the deserts of southwestern Africa (i.e. the [[Namib]], the [[Karoo]], the [[Kalahari]]) and probably the rainforests of the Congo. In west Africa it is fairly uncommon across the [[Sahel]], except for the major floodplain systems. It can commonly found breeding along the Niger, in the Inner Niger Delta of Mali, the [[Logone River|Logone]] of C.A.R., [[Lake Fitri|Lac Fitri]] in Chad, the [[Saloum Delta]] of Senegal, and other localities in relatively small numbers such as in The Gambia. It is common across eastern Africa and southern Africa. Large numbers can be found in the [[Sudd]] swamps and [[Lake Kundi]] in Sudan in the dry season. It is fairly widespread along the upper Nile River, and is quite common around Mogadishu, Somalia. In Tanzania there are a number of sites with 500 to 1,000+ birds, totalling some 20,000 birds.<ref>{{cite report |last=Dodman |first=Tim |date=September 2014 |title=Status, Estimates and Trends of Waterbird Populations in Africa: AEWA-listed African populations |url=https://www.wetlands.org/publications/1304/ |publisher=Wetlands International |pages=23\u201324}}</ref>\n\n==== Asia ====\nThe bird is also native to Yemen; in 2003 it bred in large numbers on small islands near [[Haramous]] and along the Red Sea coast near [[Hodeidah]] and [[Aden]], where it was often found at waste-water treatment plants. It has been recorded nesting on a shipwreck in the Red Sea.<ref>{{cite book |last=Shobrak |first=Mohammed|last2=Al Suhaibany |first2=Abdullah |last3=Al-Sagheir |first3=Omer |date=November 2003 |title=Status of Breeding Seabirds in the Red Sea and Gulf of Aden - PERSGA Technical Series No. 8 |url=http://www.persga.org/Files/Common/Sea_Birds/Reginal_Status_of_Seabirds.pdf |location=Jeddah, Saudi Arabia |publisher=The Regional Organization for the Conservation of the Environment of the Red Sea and Gulf of Aden (PERSGA)}}</ref> It is also seen as a vagrant on [[Socotra]].<ref name=MiddleEast >{{cite book |last=Porter |first=Richard |last2=Aspinall |first2=Simon |date=10 Dec 2016 |title=Birds of the Middle East |edition=3rd |location=London |publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing |page=58 |isbn=9781472946003}}</ref>\nWith the current war and famine, there have been no new census reports on the species in Yemen,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://iwc.wetlands.org/index.php/spectotals |title=Country count totals by species for the period 2013 - 2017 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |publisher=International Waterbird Census |access-date=31 March 2018}}</ref> however an estimate of approximately 30 mature individuals was given in 2015.<ref>{{cite book |last=Symes |first=A.|last2=Taylor |first2=J. |last3=Mallon |first3=D. |last4=Porter |first4=R. |last5=Simms |first5=C. |last6=Budd |first6=K. |date=2015 |title=The Conservation Status and Distribution of the Breeding Birds of the Arabian Peninsula |url=https://portals.iucn.org/library/sites/library/files/documents/RL-53-004.pdf |location=Sharjah, U.A.E. |publisher=IUCN, Gland, Switzerland and Cambridge, UK and the Environment and Protected Areas Authority, Government of Sharjah |page=21 |isbn=978-2-8317-1751-7 |doi=10.2305/IUCN.CH.2015.MRA.5.en }}</ref>\n\nThe species was fairly common in Iraq in the first half of the 20th century, but by the late 1960s it had become very scarce, with the population thought to number no more than 200 birds. The population was thought to have suffered greatly during the draining of the [[Mesopotamian Marshes]] of southeastern Iraq starting in the late 1980s, and feared to have disappeared entirely, but it has continuously been observed breeding in a colony in the [[Hawizeh Marshes]] (a part of the Mesopotamian Marshes) as of 2008, numbering up to 27 adults.<ref name=AEWA1999/><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Salim|first=Mudhafar|last2=Porter|first2=Richard|last3=Rubec|first3=Clayton|year=2009|title=A summary of birds recorded in the marshes of southern Iraq, 2005\u20132008 (in: Environment, Biodiversity and Conservation in the Middle East. Proceedings of the First Middle Eastern Biodiversity Congress, Aqaba, Jordan, 20\u201323 October 2008)|url=https://biorisk.pensoft.net/article/1840/download/pdf/|journal=BioRisk|volume=3|issue=1|pages=205\u2013219|doi=10.3897/biorisk.3.14}}</ref> It is also native to [[Kuwait]], where it occurs as an extremely rare migrant, with only two known sightings, the last being a flock of 17 in 2007.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kuwaitbirds.org/birds/african-sacred-ibis|title=African Sacred Ibis - KuwaitBirds.org|date= 2012|publisher=Birds of Kuwait by Biodiversity East sponsored by Kuwait Foreign Petroleum Exploration Company (KUFPEC)|access-date= 29 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nThere are no records of the bird in Iran before the 1970s, however small numbers were found overwintering in [[Khuzestan]] in 1970. Since the 1990s numbers appear to have slowly increased to a few dozen.<ref name=Iran>{{Cite journal|last=Khaleghizadeh|first=A.|last2=Scott|first2=D. A.|last3=Tohidifar|first3=M.|last4=Babak|first4=S.|last5=Musavi|first5=M. G.|last6=Sehhatisabet|first6=M. E.|last7=Ashoori|first7=A.|last8=Khani|first8=A.|last9=Bakhtiari|first9=P.|last10=Amini|first10=H.|last11=Rooselaar|first11=C.|last12=Ay\u00e9|first12=R.|last13=Ullman|first13=M.|last14=Nezami|first14=B.|last15=Eskandari|first15=F.|year=2011|title=Rare birds in Iran in 1980\u2212 2010|url=http://www.osme.org/tripreports/PODOCES%206_1_%20Rare%20Birds%20in%20Iran%20in%201980-2010.pdf|journal=Podoces|volume=6|issue=1|pages=1\u201348|issn=1735-6725|access-date=2018-03-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130201165126/http://www.osme.org/tripreports/PODOCES%206_1_%20Rare%20Birds%20in%20Iran%20in%201980-2010.pdf|archive-date=2013-02-01|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n=== Introduced ===\nThe first African sacred ibises brought to Europe were two imported from Egypt to France in the mid-1700s.<ref name=Buffon/> In the 1800s the first escapes were sighted in Europe (in Austria, Italy). In the 1970s it became fashionable for many zoos in Europe and elsewhere to keep their birds in free-flying colonies, which were allowed to forage in the area but would return to roost in the zoo every day. As such feral populations were established in [[Italy]], [[France]], [[Spain]], the Netherlands, the Canary Islands, Florida, [[Taiwan]], the United Arab Emirates and possibly Bahrain.<ref name=iucn/><ref name=Y\u00e9sou/><ref name=WildEast>{{cite news |last=Charlier |first=Phillip |date=25 April 2016 |title=The Sacred Ibis Runs Rampant in Taiwan |url=http://news.thewildeast.net/the-sacred-ibis-runs-rampant-in-taiwan/ |newspaper=The Wild East Magazine|access-date= 9 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nSome studies indicate that the introduced populations in Europe have significant economic and ecological impacts,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Kumschick|first1=S.|last2=Nentwig|first2=W.|year=2010|title=Some alien birds have as severe an impact as the most effectual alien mammals in Europe|journal=Biological Conservation|volume=143|issue=11|pages=2757\u20132762|doi=10.1016/j.biocon.2010.07.023}}</ref> while others suggest that they constitute no substantial threat to native European bird species.<ref name=Marion/>\n\n==== Europe ====\nIn France the African sacred ibises have become established along its Atlantic coast following the feral breeding of birds which were the offspring of a large free-flying population originating from the Branf\u00e9r\u00e9 Zoological Gardens in southern [[Brittany]]. The first successful breeding was in 1993 at two sites, the [[Golfe du Morbihan]] and [[Lac de Grand-Lieu]], {{cvt|25|km}} and {{cvt|70|km}} respectively from Branf\u00e9r\u00e9. By 2005 the Atlantic French breeding population was estimated at 1,100 pairs and winter censuses led to an estimated total population of up to 3,000 birds. A separate population originated from a zoo at [[Sigean]] on the Mediterranean coast of France and by 2005 the colony at the [[Etang de Bages-et Sigean]] was estimated at 250 pairs.<ref name=Y\u00e9sou/> A cull was begun and by 2011 the population had fallen to 560\u2013600 pairs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oncfs.gouv.fr/IMG/pdf/Bilan_nidification_ibis_sacre_2011.pdf |title=Nidification de l'ibis sacr\u00e9 dans l'ouest de la France en 2011 |language=French |accessdate=5 January 2018 |author=Pierre Y\u00e9sou |date=23 November 2011 |publisher=Office National de la Chasse et de la Faune Sauvage}}</ref> By January 2017 the eradication programme had lowered the number of birds in roosts in western France to 300\u2013500 birds and the Lac de Grand-Lieu was the only regular breeding site in the region; as the programme has progressed the birds have become warier and the reduced numbers mean the effort and cost per bird has increased and complete eradication may never be achieved. The population near Sigean was eradicated by killing and capturing the birds with only a few remaining in the [[Camargue]].<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Pierre Y\u00e9sou |author2= Philippe Clergeau |author3=Suzanne Bastian |author4=S\u00e9bastien Reeber |author5=Jean-Fran\u00e7ois Maillard |last-author-amp=yes |year=2017 |title=The Sacred Ibis in Europe: ecology and management |journal=British Birds |volume=110 |issue=April 2017 |pages=197\u2013212}}</ref>\n\nThis species is not considered established in mainland Spain. The Barcelona Zoo kept a small free-flying population which bred in the zoo and at least once in 1974 in the surrounding city park. Between 1983 and 1985 they had increased to 18 birds, but these subsequently declined to 4\u20136 pairs in the 1990s and the birds were permanently caged by the end of the 1990s (the zoo still has some). In 2001 the remaining birds in the surroundings were culled, thus ending the occurrence of the species in the 'wild' in the area. However, in the early 2000s vagrants from most probably France were recorded in northern Catalonia, and sporadic observations throughout the year have been recorded since then along the Mediterranean and Cantabrian coasts. There were a total of about twenty approved records of sightings between 1994 and 2004.<ref name=Y\u00e9sou/><ref name=DAISIE>{{cite report |last=Clergeau |first=Philippe |last2=Y\u00e9sou |first2=Pierre |date=12 October 2006 |title=''Threskiornis aethiopicus'' |url=http://www.europe-aliens.org/speciesFactsheet.do?speciesId=50480# |publisher=Delivering Alien Invasive Species Inventories for Europe (DAISIE) |access-date=9 April 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161126003457/http://www.europe-aliens.org/speciesFactsheet.do?speciesId=50480 |archivedate=26 November 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=Cat\u00e1logoEspa\u00f1ol>{{cite report |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=September 2013 |title=Cat\u00e1logo Espa\u00f1ol de Especies Ex\u00f3ticas Invasoras - ''Threskiornis aethiopicus'' |url=http://www.mapama.gob.es/es/biodiversidad/temas/conservacion-de-especies/Threskiornis_aethiopicus_2013_tcm30-69957.pdf |language=Spanish |publisher=Ministerio de Agricultura y Pesca, Alimentaci\u00f3n y Medio Ambiente}}</ref><ref name=SEO>{{cite web |url=https://www.seo.org/ave/ibis-sagrado/ |title=Ibis sagrado SEOBirdLife |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=2008 |language=Spanish |publisher=Sociedad Espa\u00f1ola de Ornitolog\u00eda |access-date=7 April 2018 |quote=}}</ref> As of 2009, birds entering Spain from France are shot.<ref name=CABI/>\n \nThe population in Italy may have been introduced from the zoo [[Faunistic Park Le Cornelle|Le Cornelle]] which has kept a free-flying group since the early 1980s, or possibly from Brittany, but this is unclear. The first pair was seen breeding in the nearby heronry at Oldenico, in Lame del Sesia Regional Park in [[Novara]], NW Italy, in 1989. By 1998 there was a colony of 9 pairs and 48 birds there; by 2000 there were 24\u201326 pairs, and by 2003 there were 25\u201330 breeding pairs. A second colony appeared in 2004 at another nearby heronry at Casalbeltrame. These birds would mostly feed in the rice fields in the area, but would also migrate elsewhere during the summer, with the population at the roosts increasing in the winter. In 2008, the number of breeding ibis was estimated at 80\u2013100 pairs, and at least 300 birds. That same year, six individuals, consisting of three pairs, were observed roosting at a heronry in [[Casaleggio Novara|Casaleggio]]. By 2009 they were said to be one of the most characteristic animals of the rice-growing area of Novara and [[Vercellese]]. In 2010 the species was reported attempting to breed in the [[Po (river)|Po]] Delta, northeast Italy. By 2014 reports of individuals and small flocks were recorded in various areas from the Po Valley down to [[Tuscany]]. Outside the Piedmont Region, cases of possible nesting are reported in [[Emilia-Romagna]], [[Veneto]] and [[Lombardy]]. As of 2017 there do not seem to be coordinated control efforts in Italy.<ref name=Quaderni>{{cite magazine |last=Usai |first=Alessio |last2=Billington |first2=Richard |last3=Re |first3=Alessandro |last4=Rigamonti |first4=Ettore |last5=Festari |first5=Igor |date=2009 |title=L'Ibis sacro in Provincia di Novara |url=http://www.ebnitalia.it/QB/QB021/index.htm |magazine=Quaderni di Birdwatching |language=Italian |location=Verona |publisher=EBN Italia |volume=21 |issue=XI |access-date=17 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite newsgroup |title=Italy wild-occurring hybrid African spoonbill X Sacred ibis (photos) |author=italianbirder |date=4 March 2010 |newsgroup=www.surfbirds.com |url=http://www.surfbirds.com/forum/forum/rare-bird-information/european-rare-birds/5385-italy-wild-occurring-hybrid-african-spoonbill-x-sacred-ibis-photos |access-date=16 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tenutasanguido.com/pdf/BOLGHERI%20OASI/IbisSacro%20Eng.pdf |title=Oasi di Bolgheri - The African sacred ibis (''Threskiornis aethiopicus'') - A new species for the Bolgheri Bird Sanctuary |last=Politi |first=Paolo Maria |date=23 November 2014 |publisher=WWF OASI |access-date=17 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.parcodelmincio.it/infonatura-dettaglio.php?id=42880 |title=Lo strano caso dell'ibis sacro\u2026 |last=Pavesi |first=Alessandro |date=14 July 2017 |language=Italian |location=Mantua |publisher=Gruppo Ricerche Avifauna Mantova (GRAM) for Parco del Mincio |access-date=17 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the Netherlands, sacred ibises were introduced from three sources; primarily from the free-flying flock at the [[aviary]] zoo [[Vogelpark Avifauna|Avifauna]], and another group of 11 birds which escaped from a private bird trader in [[Weert]] when a tree fell on their enclosure sometime between 1998 and 2000 which would all return to their cage each winter. Furthermore, in 2000 a group of sacred ibises escaped from a zoo near [[Munster]], some of which apparently crossed the border into [[Overijssel]], as the colours of their [[Bird ringing|rings]] closely matched. The free-flying Avifauna flock numbered 12 in 2001, 30 in 2003, and an estimated maximum of 41 birds escaped the zoo eventually. There had been sightings throughout the country for many years, but in 2002 successful breeding was first reported in a nature reserve some 40&nbsp;km from Avifauna. \nBy 2007 the feral population in the Netherlands had increased to 15 pairs breeding at three locations, including in a tree just outside the zoo. Pairs would regularly move from the zoo to the nature reserve in the summer and vice versa. The next year, in 2008, the tree outside the zoo was cut down, and free-flying birds were recaptured, clipped and caged. 2008/2009 was also a cold winter and many birds died. By 2009 37 birds had been recaptured and by 2010 there were no more birds breeding in the wild. The birds in Weert were halved in number after the 2008\u20132009 winter and had disappeared somewhere between 2011 and 2015. As of 2016 a few birds survive, some still attempting to breed in Overijssel, and handful sightings of less than three reported. Possible vagrants from France have also been noted (by their rings) after 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.michelklemann.nl/ibis/index.htm |title=Heilige Ibis ''Threskiornis aethiopicus'' Sacred Ibis |last=Klemann |first=Michel |date=n.d. |language=Dutch |access-date=9 April 2018}}</ref><ref name=Waardenburg>{{cite report |last=Smits |first=R.R. |last2=van Horssen |first2=P. |last3=van der Winden |first3=J. |date=26 February 2010 |title=A risk analysis of the sacred ibis in The Netherlands |url=https://www.buwa.nl/fileadmin/buwa_upload/Bureau_Waardenburg_rapporten/09-556_Risk_analysis_sacred_ibis.pdf |publisher=Bureau Waardenburg B.V. |docket=Report nr 10-005}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sovon.nl/nl/soort/1420 |title=Heilige Ibis Sovon.nl |author=<!--Not stated--> |language=Dutch |publisher= Sovon Vogelonderzoek Nederland |date=n.d.|access-date=9 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==== Elsewhere ====\nThe sacred ibis is not considered invasive on the Canary Islands.<ref name=Cat\u00e1logoEspa\u00f1ol/> It is kept in zoos on Tenerife, Gran Canaria, Lanzarote and Fuerteventura, two of which kept their collections free-flying. In 1989, the first ibis was seen in the wild. In 1997, the first pair was seen breeding outside a zoo, the population reached a maximum of 5 pairs between then and 2005, and 30 pairs is given by Clergeau & Y\u00e9sou in 2006 (though this last number is untrustworthy). The birds are divided between the islands Lanzarote (near [[Arrecife]] in an old heron colony) and Fuerteventura (in the zoo near La Lajita but free-flying). On both islands, these birds have remained very near to the zoos. The breeding is 'controlled'. There is disagreement regarding the origin of other records, especially during the migratory period. Ibises have been seen on all four of the islands where there are zoos that keep them.<ref name=Y\u00e9sou/><ref name=DAISIE/><ref name=Cat\u00e1logoEspa\u00f1ol/><ref name=SEO/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://blog.birdingcanarias.com/2009/02/ibis-sagrado-en-tenerife.html |title=Birding Canarias - Ibis Sagrado en Tenerife |last=Ramos |first=Juan Jos\u00e9 |date=12 February 2009 |language=Spanish |access-date=6 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nIntroduced sacred ibises bred in the [[United Arab Emirates]] in the wildlife reserve on [[Sir Bani Yas]] Island, where 6 were introduced in the early 1980s, and which did not leave the island. There was only one left in 1989 and it died that year. [[Al Ain Zoo]] has had a flock since 1976, which had increased to some 70 birds by 1991. There are records of ibises showing up in [[Dubai]] since the 1980s. Birds in Al Ain initially stayed at the zoo, but began to fly from the zoo to the sewage treatment plant and a shallow wet area in the former public park, now luxury villa park, Ain Al Fayda, where their numbers increased slowly up to 32 in 1997 and they had bred by 1998. They were not numerous outside these locations in 2002, but by 2001 1-5 ibises would show up regularly in Dubai in such places as the golf course, the sewage treatment plant, and the construction site of the now completed [[Dubai International City]]. Breeding has since occurred in Dubai. The Dubai birds especially may be partially vagrants arrived from the Iraqi marshes, as they often show up during the migrating season.<ref name=Y\u00e9sou/><ref name=MiddleEast/><ref name=CABI/><ref name=Klemann/><ref>{{cite report |last=Pedersen |first=T. |last2=Aspinall |first2=S.J. |last3=Campbell |first3=O.J. |last4=Smiles |first4=M.C. |date=2017 |title=EBRC Annotated Checklist of the birds of the United Arab Emirates |url=http://www.uaebirding.com/uaechecklist.html |publisher=Emirates Bird Records Committee |page=125 |access-date=11 April 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180412082728/http://www.uaebirding.com/uaechecklist.html |archivedate=12 April 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> On the other hand, a bird showing up in Iran is suspected to be from the introduced U.A.E. population.<ref name=Iran/> As of 2010 the population in Al Ain numbers over 75 birds, and the free-flying zoo birds roost in two subcolonies on top of their aviary. Birds regularly show up throughout the city and surrounding villages and can often be seen in the early morning in parks and roundabouts picking up scraps left by people the night before.<ref>{{cite newsgroup |title=Sacred ibis in Green Mubazzara |author=Rezak Khan |date=30 April 2010 |url=http://www.uaebirding.com/forum/showthread.php?2645-sacred-ibis-in-Green-Mubazzara |access-date=11 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nA breeding population was listed as introduced on [[Bahrain]] since at least 2006,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hawar-islands.com/checklist.html |title=Bahrain Check List |last=King |first=Howard |date=n.d. |access-date=10 April 2018}}</ref> but it is also said to be a vagrant on the island.<ref name=MiddleEast/>\n\nIn Taiwan, as elsewhere, the founding population escaped from a zoo, in this case before 1984, at which time the first wild birds were seen at [[Guandu Nature Park|Guandu]] in [[Taipei]]. In 1998 it was estimated that some 200 birds roamed freely, primarily in northern Taiwan. In 2010 it was first added to the Checklist of Birds of Taiwan with the status of 'uncommon' (as opposed to 'rare'). By 2010 \nthe birds were also occasionally sighted on the [[Matsu Islands]], which are only 19&nbsp;km off the coast of [[Fujian]] province in mainland China (and only a few kilometres from other coastal Chinese islands), but 190&nbsp;km from Taiwan. In 2012 the population was estimated to be 500\u2013600 individuals, and had spread to the west of Taiwan. The first attempts at culling were performed in 2012 using the [[Cormorant culling|egg-oiling method]] (unsuccessful), and by killing chicks from nests (successful). By 2016 the number was estimated at 1000 individuals, of whom around 500 inhabited a wetland in [[Changhua County]].<ref name=WildEast/><ref name=Klemann/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bird.org.tw/index.php/works/lists |title=\u53f0\u7063\u9ce5\u985e\u540d\u9304 The Checklist of Birds of Taiwan |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=26 April 2017 |publisher=\u4e2d\u83ef\u6c11\u570b\u91ce\u9ce5\u5b78\u6703 The Republic of China Wild Bird Society |language=Chinese |access-date=8 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bird.org.tw/index.php/news/cwbf/1011-2015-03-05-01-40-10 |title=\u5916\u4f86\u5165\u4fb5\u9ce5\u7a2e\u57c3\u53ca\u8056\u9e6e\u9632\u6cbb |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=5 March 2015 |publisher=\u4e2d\u83ef\u6c11\u570b\u91ce\u9ce5\u5b78\u6703 The Republic of China Wild Bird Society |language=Chinese |access-date=8 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn Florida five individuals of the species are thought to have escaped Miami Metro Zoo, and perhaps more from private collections, after [[Hurricane Andrew]] in 1992. These birds lived in the surroundings but would return to roost at the zoo at night, and the population slowly increased to 30 or 40 by 2005. That same year two pairs were found nesting in the [[Everglades]]. Two or three years later the decision was made to remove the species. By 2009 75 birds were removed from Florida, and the birds are believed to be eradicated.<ref name=Y\u00e9sou/><ref>{{cite report |last=Johnson |first=Steve A. |last2=McGarrity |first2=Monica |date=October 2009 |title=Florida's Introduced Birds: Sacred Ibis (''Threskiornis aethiopicus'') |url=http://ufdcimages.uflib.ufl.edu/IR/00/00/34/25/00001/UW31200.pdf |publisher=Wildlife Ecology and Conservation Department, Florida Cooperative Extension Service, Institute of Food and Agricultural Sciences, University of Florida}}</ref>\n\n== Ecology ==\n=== Habitat ===\nThe African sacred ibis occurs in marshy wetlands and mud flats, both inland and on the coast. It preferably nests on trees in or near water. It feeds wading in very shallow wetlands or slowly stomping in wet pastures with soft soil. It will also visit cultivation and [[rubbish dumps]].<ref name=Kopij1999/><ref name=Waardenburg/>\n\n=== Diet ===\nThe species are predators which feed primarily by day, generally in flocks. The diet consists of mainly insects, worms, crustaceans, molluscs and other invertebrates, as well as various fish, frogs, reptiles, small mammals and carrion.<ref name=adw/><ref name=Waardenburg/><ref name=biex>{{cite web|title=''Threskiornis aethiopicus'' (African sacred ibis, Sacred ibis) |url=http://www.biodiversityexplorer.org/birds/threskiornithidae/threskiornis_aethiopicus.htm|publisher=Biodiversity Explorer}}</ref> It may also probe into the soil with its long beak for invertebrates such as earthworms.<ref name=biex/> It does even feed on seeds.<ref>{{cite iucn |url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22697510/0 |title=Threskiornis aethiopicus (African Sacred Ibis, Sacred Ibis)}}</ref>\n\nSacred ibises were observed to occasionally feed on the contents of pelican eggs broken by [[Egyptian vulture]]s in the mixed colonies of the ibises, [[Great cormorant|cormorants]], [[Great white pelican|pelicans]] and [[Abdim's stork]]s at Lake Shala in Ethiopia.<ref name=Urban>{{cite journal |last=Urban |first=Emil K. |date=July 1974 |title=Breeding of Sacred ibis ''Threskiornis aethiopica'' at lake Shala, Ethiopia |journal=Ibis |volume=116 |issue=3 |pages=263\u2013277 |doi=10.1111/j.1474-919X.1974.tb00124.x }}</ref> On [[Central Island]] in [[Lake Turkana]] sacred ibises were noted to incidentally eat [[Nile crocodile]] eggs excavated by [[Varanus salvator|Nile monitors]].<ref name=Marion/> Most recently, in 2006, observations were reported from a large mixed colony on [[Bird Island Nature Reserve (South Africa)|Bird Island]] (called Penguin Island in the article) in South Africa, where 10,000 pairs of [[Morus capensis|gannets]] nested, together with 4800 pairs of [[Cape cormorant]] and other species such as gulls and [[Spheniscus demersus|jackass penguin]]. Within a period of 3 years, a few specialized sacred ibis individuals out of the 400 that roosted on the island had fed on at least 152 eggs of the cormorant (other species were even more ovivorous).<ref>{{cite journal |last=Williams |first=Anthony J. |last2=Ward |first2=V. L. |date=September 2006 |title=Sacred Ibis and Gray Heron Predation of Cape Cormorant Eggs and Chicks; and a Review of Ciconiiform Birds as Seabird Predators |url=http://cescos.fau.edu/gawliklab/papers/WilliamsAJandVLWard2006.pdf |journal=Waterbirds |volume=29 |issue=3 |pages=321\u2013327 |doi=10.1675/1524-4695(2006)29[321:SIAGHP]2.0.CO;2 |access-date=12 April 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180418161140/http://cescos.fau.edu/gawliklab/papers/WilliamsAJandVLWard2006.pdf |archive-date=18 April 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn a study of [[Pellet (ornithology)|pellets]] and stomachs contents of nestlings in the Free State, South Africa, food is mostly reported to consist of frogs (mainly ''[[Angola river frog|Amietia angolensis]]'' and ''[[Xenopus laevis]]''), ''[[Potamonautes|Potamonautes warreni]]'' crabs, [[Calliphoridae|blow fly]] maggots, [[Sphingidae]] caterpillars, and adult beetles. During the first 10 days of life nestlings fed mainly on crabs and beetles, and later mainly on Sphingidae caterpillars and more beetles. The breeding colony collected different (proportions of) prey the subsequent year.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Kopij |first=Grzegorz |last2=Kok |first2=Ordino B. |last3=Roos |first3=Zennon N. |date=1996 |title=Food of Sacred Ibis Threskiornis aethiopicus nestlings in the Free State province, South Africa |journal=Ostrich |volume=67 |issue=3\u20134 |pages=138\u2013143 |doi=10.1080/00306525.1996.9639698 }}</ref>  The food of one one\u2010month old nestlings at [[Lake Shala]], Ethiopia, consisted of beetle larvae, caterpillars and beetles.<ref name=Urban/> In France, adult ibises fed largely on the invasive crayfish ''[[Procambarus clarkii]]'', for nestlings larvae of ''[[Eristalis]]'' species are important.<ref name=Marion/><ref name=Waardenburg/>\n\nIn France, they sometimes supplement their diet by feeding at rubbish tips in the winter.<ref name=Marion/>\n\n=== Predators ===\nThe most important predator of nestlings of the sacred ibis in Kenya is the [[African fish eagle]], which preferentially searches for the largest (sub-)colonies to attack, but in Ethiopia and South Africa it poses less of a threat.<ref name=Kopij1999/>\n\n=== Diseases ===\nThis species was reported to be susceptible to avian botulism in a list of dead animals found around a man-made lake in South Africa which tested positive for the pathogen in the late 1960s and early 1970s.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Van Heerden |first=J. |date=1974 |title=Botulism in the Orange Free State goldfields |journal=Ostrich |volume=45 |issue=3 |pages=182\u2013184 |doi=10.1080/00306525.1974.9634055 }}</ref> During a large scale mortality of [[Cape cormorant]]s from [[Fowl cholera|avian cholera]] in 1991 in western South Africa, small numbers of sacred ibis were killed.<ref name=Waardenburg/> The new species ''[[Chlamydia (genus)|Chlamydia ibidis]]'' was isolated from feral sacred ibis in France in 2013; it infected 6-7 of the 70 birds tested.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Vorimore |first=Fabien |last2=Hsia |first2=Ru-ching |last3=Huot-Creasy |first3=Heather |last4=Bastian |first4=Suzanne |last5=Deruyter |first5=Lucie |last6=Passet |first6=Anne  |last7=Sachse |first7=Konrad |last8=Bavoil |first8=Patrik |last9=Myers |first9=Garry |last10=Laroucau |first10=Karine |date=20 September 2013 |title=Isolation of a New ''Chlamydia'' species from the Feral Sacred Ibis (''Threskiornis aethiopicus'')- ''Chlamydia ibidis'' |journal=PLoS ONE |volume=8 |issue=9 |at=e74823 |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0074823 |pmid=24073223 |pmc=3779242 |bibcode=2013PLoSO...874823V }}</ref>\n\nIn 1887, the Italian scientist Corrado Parona reported a 3&nbsp;cm ''[[Physaloptera]]'' species of [[nematode]] in the orbital cavity of a sacred ibis collected in [[Metemma]], Abyssinia (now Ethiopia) in 1882. He thought it was perhaps a new species, as it differed morphologically from earlier seen worms. A single adult female was recovered, and it has never been seen again. As the ''Physaloptera'' species infecting birds are generally parasites of the intestines of raptors; it might be an artefact, or perhaps a misidentification, or possibly a [[Host (biology)#Dead-end hosts|dead-end host]] infection.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Parona |first=Corrado |date=7\u201312 October 1885 |title=Di Alcuni Elminti Raccolti nel Sudan Orientale da O. Beccari e P. Magretti |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/35910#page/446/mode/1up |journal=Annali del Museo Civico di Storia Naturale di Genova |series=2 |language=Italian |volume=22 |pages=438\u2013439 |access-date=15 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Morgan |first=Banner Bill |date=1946 |title=Host-parasite Relationships and Geographical Distribution of the Physalopterinae (Nematoda) |url=http://images.library.wisc.edu/WI/EFacs/transactions/WT1946/reference/wi.wt1946.bbmorgan.pdf |journal=Transactions of the Wisconsin Academy of Sciences, Arts and Letters |volume=38 |issue= |pages=282 |issn=0084-0505 |access-date=15 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Ransom |first=B. H. |date=1904 |title=General Review of Nematodes Parasitic in the Eyes of Birds |url=https://archive.org/stream/mansonseyewormof00rommiala#page/43/mode/1up/search/Physaloptera |journal=Bulletin |issue=60 |pages=43 |doi= |access-date=15 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Cram |first=Eloise B. |date=1927 |title=Bird Parasites of the Nematode Suborders Strongylata, Ascaridata, and Spirurata |url=https://archive.org/stream/bulletinunitedst1401927unit#page/309/mode/1up/search/parona |journal=Bulletin of the United States National Museum |volume=140 |issue= |pages=309 |doi= |access-date=15 April 2018}}</ref> The [[digenea]]n [[Trematoda|trematode]] ''Patagifer bilobus'', a fluke, has been reported from sacred ibis in Sudan before 1949. It lives in the small intestine of this species, among numerous other ibises, spoonbills, and a few other waterfowl. It has a complicated life history involving three [[Host (biology)|hosts]]: the eggs hatch in fresh water where they infect a [[Planorbis planorbis|ram's horn snail]] in which they multiply and produce [[Trematode life cycle stages|cercariae]], which exit and encyst in a larger snail such as a ''[[Lymnaea]]'', waiting to be eaten by a bird.<ref>{{cite journal |last=McDonald |first=Malcolm Edwin |date=August 1969 |title=Catalogue of Helminths of Waterfowl (Anatidae) |url=https://archive.org/stream/specialscientifi126unit#page/155/mode/1up/search/patagifer |department=Bureau of Sport Fisheries and Wildlife |journal=Special Scientific Report--Wildlife |volume=126 |pages=156 |access-date=14 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Reproduction ==\n[[File:African Sacred Ibis colony in Montagu, Western Cape b.JPG|thumb|right|The breeding colony in [[Montagu, Western Cape|Montagu]], [[Western Cape]], South Africa]]\n[[File:Threskiornis aethiopicus MHNT.ZOO.2010.11.63.1.jpg|thumb| ''Threskiornis aethiopicus'' - [[MHNT]]]]\nThe species usually breeds once per year in the wet season. Breeding season is from March to August in Africa, from April to May in [[Iraq]].<ref name=adw/> It builds a stick nest, often in a [[Adansonia|baobab tree]]. The bird nests in tree colonies, often with other large wading birds such as [[stork]]s, [[heron]]s, [[African spoonbill]]s, [[African darter]]s, [[cormorant]]s. It may also form single-species groups on offshore islands or abandoned buildings. Large colonies consist of numerous subcolonies and can number 1000 birds.<ref name=Kopij1999/><ref name=biex/>\n\n[[File:Sacred ibis (Threskiornis aethiopicus) immature.jpg|thumb|immature, [[Uganda]]]]\nFemales lay 1-5 eggs per season, incubated by both parents for 21\u201329 days.<ref name=anc/> After hatching, one parent continuously stays at the nest for the first 7-days.<ref name=adw/> Chicks fledge after 35\u201340 days and are independent after 44\u201348 days, reaching sexual maturity 1\u20135 years after hatching.<ref name=anc/>\n\n== Conservation ==\nThe African sacred ibis is classified as \"[[Least Concern]]\" by the [[IUCN]]. The global population is estimated at 200,000\u2013450,000 individuals but appears to be decreasing.<ref name=iucn/> It is covered by the ''Agreement on the Conservation of African-Eurasian Migratory Waterbirds'' ([[AEWA]]).<ref>{{cite web |title=Threskiornis aethiopicus |url=https://www.unep-aewa.org/en/species/threskiornis-aethiopicus |website=Agreement on the Conservation of African-Eurasian Migratory Waterbirds |publisher=Agreement on the Conservation of African-Eurasian Migratory Waterbirds |accessdate=25 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n== In myth and legend ==\n[[File:IbisCopenhagenMuseum.jpg|thumb|Copenhagen Museum]]\nFor many centuries, sacred ibis, along with two other species in lesser numbers,<ref>{{Cite book |last=Wyatt |first=John |date=26 October 2012 |title=The Encyclopedia of Ancient History |doi=10.1002/9781444338386.wbeah15208 |chapter=Ibis |isbn=9781444338386 }}</ref> were commonly mummified by the [[Ancient Egypt]]ians as a votive offering to the god [[Thoth]]. Thoth, whose head is that of an ibis, is the Ancient Egyptian god of wisdom and reason, and thus of truth, knowledge, learning and study, and writing and mathematics. The sacred ibis was considered the living incarnation of Thoth on earth.\n\nProperly mummified birds enjoyed a path to the afterlife. Pilgrims from all over Egypt brought thousands of ibis offerings to four or more main temples, which at their peak mummified and buried thousands of birds a year in gigantic and ancient catacombs (one complex was in operation for 700 years). Eventually an estimated eight million birds were mummified and entombed by the Ancient Egyptians.\n\nTo sustain sufficient numbers for the large and sometimes growing demand for sacrifices by the people, dozens of ibis breeding farms (called ''ibiotropheia'' by Herodotus) were established, initially throughout the regions of Egypt, but later centralised around the main temples, each producing around a thousand birds for mummies annually. Wild birds were caught and added to the captive flocks. The mummified birds were often young and were usually killed by breaking their neck. The head and bill were often placed between the tail feathers, and a piece of food was often placed in the bill. The particulars of the mummification ritual often differed. The mummies could be stored in ceramic jars, wooden chests or stone sarcophagi. Not all mummies contain whole birds; some (cheaper ones) contain only a leg, an eggshell, or even dried grass from the nest. Birds were given different burials according to their status; as pets, offerings or holy individuals. Special sacred birds were afforded special mummification, transported from their cities to the temples long after normal offerings were sourced from temple farm flocks, and honoured with more luxurious burial. Different regions in Egypt observed slightly different practises regarding the ritual beliefs.<ref name=Wasef/>\n\nIbis mummification started by at least 1,100 BC and petered out by approximately 30 BC. Although the numbers of burials peaked at different times depending on the region and temple, the rituals were most popular from the Late Period to the Ptolemaic Period.<ref name=Wasef/><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wasef|first=S.|last2=Wood|first2=R.|last3=Merghani|first3=S. El|last4=Ikram|first4=S.|last5=Curtis|first5=C.|last6=Holland|first6=B.|last7=Willerslev|first7=E.|last8=Millar|first8=C.D.|last9=Lambert|first9=D.M.|title=Radiocarbon dating of Sacred Ibis mummies from ancient Egypt|journal=Journal of Archaeological Science: Reports|volume=4|pages=355\u2013361|doi=10.1016/j.jasrep.2015.09.020|year=2015}}</ref>\n\nMummified specimens of the African Sacred Ibis were brought back to Europe by Napoleon's army, where they became part of an early debate about evolution.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Curtis|first=Caitlin|last2=Millar|first2=Craig|last3=Lambert|first3=David|date=2018-09-27|title=The Sacred Ibis debate: The first test of evolution|journal=PLOS Biology|volume=16|issue=9|pages=e2005558|doi=10.1371/journal.pbio.2005558|pmid=30260949|pmc=6159855}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Herodotus]] and [[Pliny the Elder]] the ibis was invoked against incursions of winged serpents. Herodotus wrote:\n\n{{quote|There is a region moreover in Arabia, situated nearly over against the city of Buto, to which place I came to inquire about the winged serpents: and when I came thither I saw bones of serpents and spines in quantity so great that it is impossible to make report of the number, and there were heaps of spines, some heaps large and others less large and others smaller still than these, and these heaps were many in number.\nThe region in which the spines are scattered upon the ground is of the nature of an entrance from a narrow mountain pass to a great plain, which plain adjoins the plain of Egypt; and the story goes that at the beginning of spring winged serpents from Arabia fly towards Egypt, and the birds called ibises meet them at the entrance of this country and do not suffer the serpents to go by but kill them. On account of this deed it is (say the Arabians) that the ibis has come to be greatly honored by the Egyptians, and the Egyptians also agree that it is for this reason that they honor these birds.}}\n\n[[Josephus]] tells us that when Moses lead the Hebrews to make war upon the \u00c6thiopians, he brought a great number of the birds in cages of papyrus to oppose any serpents.<ref name=Buffon/>\n\nDue to perhaps a mistranslation of the Greek of Herodotus, before the early 18th century Europeans were convinced that these ibises had human feet.<ref name=Buffon/>\n\n[[Pliny the Elder]] tells us that it was said that the flies that brought pestilence died immediately upon propitiatory sacrifices of this bird.<ref name=Pliny>{{cite book |last=Pliny |title=Natural History |volume=Book X |chapter=Chapter 41 |chapterurl=http://www.masseiana.org/pliny.htm#BOOK%20X|title-link=Natural History (Pliny) }}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Claudius Aelianus]] in ''De Natura Animalium'', and [[Gaius Julius Solinus]], both quoting much earlier but now lost authors, the sacred ibis procreates with its bill, and thus the bird is always a virgin. [[Aristotle]], writing some 500 years earlier, also mentions this theory, but repudiates it. Picrius mentions how the venomous basilisk is hatched from the eggs of ibis, nurtured from the poisons of all the serpents the birds devour. These authors and many others also mention how crocodiles and snakes are rendered motionless after being touched by the feather of an ibis. Claudius Aelianus also says the ibis is consecrated to the moon.<ref name=Buffon/>\n\nPliny and [[Galen]] ascribe the invention of the [[clyster]] (enema) to the ibis, as according to them it gave such treatments to hippopotami. [[Plutarch]] assures us it uses only salt water for this purpose. 1600 years later this was still accepted science, as [[Claude Perrault]], in his anatomical descriptions of the bird, claimed to have found a hole in the bill which the bird used for that purpose.<ref name=Buffon/>\n\nIn the century before the time of Christ and for at least a century after, the worship of [[Isis#Spread|Isis]] had become quite popular in Rome, especially among women, and the ibis had become one of her associated symbols.<ref>{{cite book |last=Heyob |first=Sharon Kelly |date=1975 |title=The Cult of Isis Among Women in the Graeco-Roman World |editor-last=Vermaseren |editor-first=Maarten Jozef |series=\u00c9tudes pr\u00e9liminaires aux religions orientales dans l'Empire Romain - Tomus 51 |location=Leiden |publisher=Brill |pages=15\u201316 |doi=10.1163/9789004296374 |isbn=978-9004043688}}</ref> A number of [[fresco]]es and mosaics in the [[Patrician (ancient Rome)|patrician]] villas of [[Pompeii]] and [[Herculaneum]] of 50BC-79AD show these birds.<ref name=Quaderni/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.artoffresco.com/02-Portfolio/02.1-Birds/ibis.html |title=Ibis, Pompeii 50BC - 79AD, The Art of the Fresco |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=n.d. |access-date=17 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/28772513@N07/8610154333 |title=Landscape with Ibis. Roman fresco from the temple of Isis |author=saamiblog |date=1 April 2013 |access-date=17 April 2018}}</ref>\n \nAccording to some translations of the [[septuagint]], the ibis is one of the unclean birds which may not be eaten ([[Leviticus]] 11:17, [[Deuteronomy]] 14:16).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=Leviticus+11%3A17-19&version=ISV |title=Leviticus 11 17-19 ISV - owls, cormorants, the ibis, water-hens, - Bible Gateway |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=2014 |publisher=International Standard Version Foundation by permission of Davidson Press |access-date=17 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=Deuteronomy+14%3A16&version=DARBY |title=Deuteronomy 14 16 DARBY - the owl, and the ibis and the - Bible Gateway |last=Darby |first=John Nelson |date=1890 |access-date=17 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |title=A Field Guide to birds of The Gambia and Senegal |last1=Barlow |first1=Clive |last2=Wacher |first2=Tim |last3=Disley |first3=Tony |location=Robertsbridge |publisher=Pica Press |year=1997 |isbn=978-1-873403-32-7 }}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Threskiornis aethiopicus}}\n* [http://sabap2.adu.org.za/docs/sabap1/091.pdf Sacred Ibis] - ''[[Southern African Bird Atlas Project|The Atlas of Southern African Birds]]''\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20161126003457/http://www.europe-aliens.org/speciesFactsheet.do?speciesId=50480 Invasive Species Factsheet African sacred ibis] on DAISIE European Invasive Alien Species Gateway\n* {{VIREO|African+Sacred+Ibis}}\n\n{{Threskiornithidae}}\n{{Birds}}\n{{portalbar|Birds|Animals|Biology|Africa|Iraq|Egypt|Ancient Egypt}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q208763}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:ibis, sacred, African}}\n[[Category:Threskiornis|African sacred ibis]]\n[[Category:Birds of Africa|African sacred ibis]]\n[[Category:Birds of the Middle East]]\n[[Category:Birds of Sub-Saharan Africa|African sacred ibis]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1790|African sacred ibis]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Birds of East Africa]]\n[[Category:Birds in religion]]\n", "text_old": "{{Speciesbox\n|name=African sacred ibis\n|status=LC\n|status_system=IUCN3.1\n|status_ref=<ref name=iucn>{{cite iucn |author=[[BirdLife International]] |year=2018 |title=''Threskiornis aethiopicus'' |volume=2018 |page=e.T22697510A132068562 |doi=10.2305/IUCN.UK.2018-2.RLTS.T22697510A132068562.en }}</ref>\n|image=Threskiornis aethiopicus -Mida Creek mud flats, Kenya-8.jpg\n|image_caption=Foraging in Mida Creek mud flats, Kenya\n|taxon=Threskiornis aethiopicus\n|authority=([[John Latham (ornithologist)|Latham]], 1790)\n|synonyms=''Tantalus aethiopicus'' <small>Latham, 1790</small>\n|range_map=ThreskiornisAethiopicusIUCNver2018 2.png\n|range_map_caption=Native and introduced ranges''\n}}\n[[File:Helig Ibis - Ystad 26 dec 2015.ogv|thumb|African sacred ibis in [[Ystad]], [[Sweden]]]]\nThe '''African sacred ibis''' (''Threskiornis aethiopicus'') is a species of [[ibis]], a wading [[bird]] of the family [[Threskiornithidae]]. It is native to Africa and the Middle East. It is especially known for its role in the religion of the [[Ancient Egypt]]ians, where it was linked to the god [[Thoth]].\n\n== Taxonomy ==\nIt is very closely related to the [[black-headed ibis]] and the [[Australian white ibis]], with which it forms a [[Species complex|superspecies complex]], so much so that the three species are considered [[Biological specificity#Conspecific|conspecific]] by some [[Ornithology|ornithologists]].<ref name=CABI>{{cite web |url=https://www.cabi.org/isc/datasheet/62201 |title=''Threskiornis aethiopicus'' (sacred ibis) |last=Clergeau |first=Philippe |date=14 July 2009 |publisher=Invasive Species Compendium - CAB International |location=Wallingford, UK |access-date=9 April 2018}}</ref> In mixed flocks these ibises often hybridise.<ref>{{cite book |last=McCarthy |first=Eugene M. |date=2006 |title=Handbook of Avian Hybrids of the World |location=Oxford |publisher=Oxford University Press |page=193 |isbn=978-0195183238}}</ref> The Australian white ibis is often called the sacred ibis colloquially.<ref name=Klemann>{{cite web |url=http://www.michelklemann.nl/ibis/restoftheworld.html |title=Heilige Ibis (''Threskiornis aethiopicus'') |last=Klemann |first=Michel |date=n.d. |language=nl, en |access-date=7 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nAlthough known to the ancient civilisations of Greece, Rome and especially Africa, ibises were unfamiliar to western Europeans from the fall of Rome until the 19th century, and mentions of this bird in the ancient works of these civilisations were supposed to describe some type of [[curlew]] or other bird, and were thus translated as such.<ref name=Buffon>{{cite book |last=Leclerc Comte de Buffon |first=Georges-Louis |translator-last=Smellie |translator-first=William |date=1812 |title=Histoire Naturelle, g\u00e9n\u00e9rale et particuli\u00e8re, avec la description du Cabinet du Roi vol. 19 |trans-title=Natural History, General and Particular |edition=2nd |location=London |publisher=T. Cadell and W. Davies |pages=1\u201316}}</ref> In 1758, [[Carl Linnaeus|Linnaeus]] was convinced that the ancient authors were describing a [[cattle egret]] (''Bubulcus ibis''), which he thus described as ''Ardea ibis''.<ref>{{cite book |last=Linnaeus |first=Carolus |date=1758 |title=Systema naturae per regna tria naturae :secundum classes, ordines, genera, species, cum characteribus, differentiis, synonymis, locis |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/10277#page/159/mode/1up |language=Latin |volume=1 |edition=10 |location=Stockholm |publisher=Laurentii Salvii (Impensis Direct) |pages=140, 141, 144 |doi=10.5962/bhl.title.542|hdl=2027/hvd.32044106464480 }}</ref> Following the work of [[Mathurin Jacques Brisson]], who calls it ''Ibis candida'' in 1760, in the 12th edition of his [[Systema Naturae]] of 1766 Linnaeus classifies it as ''Tantalus ibis''.<ref>{{cite book |last=Brisson |first=Mathurin Jacques |date=1760 |title=Ornithologie, ou, M\u00e9thode contenant la division des oiseaux en ordres, sections, genres, especes & leurs vari\u00e9t\u00e9s |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/111922#page/467/mode/1up |language=Latin, French |volume=5 |location=Paris |publisher=Cl. Joannem-Baptistam Bauche |pages=349\u2013350 |doi=10.5962/bhl.title.51902}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Linnaeus |first=Carolus |date=1766 |title=Systema naturae per regna tria naturae :secundum classes, ordines, genera, species, cum characteribus, differentiis, synonymis, locis |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/137337#page/245/mode/1up |language=Latin |volume=1 |issue=1 |edition=12 |location=Stockholm |publisher=Laurentii Salvii (Impensis Direct) |page=241 |doi=10.5962/bhl.title.68927|hdl=2027/hvd.32044106464431 }}</ref> These were also unfamiliar birds that did not occur in Europe at the time, in English in these times called the 'Egyptian ibis' by [[John Latham (ornithologist)|Latham]], and the 'emseesy' or 'ox-bird' by [[George Shaw]].<ref name=Latham>{{cite book |last=Latham |first=John |date=1790 |title=Index ornithologicus, sive, Systema ornithologiae |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/226469#page/246/mode/1up |language=Latin |volume=2 |location=London |publisher=Sumptibus authoris (self published) |pages=706, 709 |doi=10.5962/bhl.title.131313}}</ref>\n\nIn 1790, [[John Latham (ornithologist)|John Latham]] provided the first unambiguous modern scientific description of the sacred ibis as ''Tantalus aethiopicus'', mentioning [[James Bruce|James Bruce of Kinnaird]] who called it 'abou hannes' in his writings describing his travels in Sudan and Ethiopia, and also described ''Tantalus melanocephalus'' of India.<ref name=Latham/>\n\n[[Georges Cuvier]] named it ''Ibis religiosus'' in his ''[[Le R\u00e8gne Animal]]'' of 1817.\n\nIn 1842, [[George Robert Gray]] reclassified the bird under the new genus ''Threskiornis'', because the type of the genus ''Tantalus'' was designated as to be the [[Wood stork#Taxonomy and etymology|wood stork]], also formerly known as the wood ibis or wood pelican, and Gray decided these birds could not be classified in the same genus.<ref>{{cite book |last=Gray |first=George Robert |date=1842 |title=Appendix to A List of the Genera of Birds |url=https://archive.org/stream/appendixtolistof00gray#page/13/mode/1up |location=London |publisher=Richard and John E. Taylor |page=13 |doi=10.5962/bhl.title.119636}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.zoonomen.net/cit/RI/Genera/T/t00113a.jpg |title=Images of the cards in the Richmond Index |last=Richmond |first=Charles W. |date=n.d. |location=Washington D.C. |publisher=Bird Division, National Museum of Natural History |access-date=19 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn a comprehensive review of plumage patterns by Holyoak in 1970, it was noted that the three taxons were extremely similar and that the Australian birds resembled ''Threskiornis aethiopicus'' in adult plumage and ''T. melanocephalus'' in juvenile plumage, he thus proposed they all be considered part of a single species ''T. aethiopicus''. At the time this was generally accepted by the scientific community, however in 'The Birds of the Western Palearctic' compendium of 1977, Roselaar advocated splitting the group into 4 species, recognising [[Malagasy sacred ibis|''T. bernieri'']], based again on the then known geographical morphological differences.<ref name=Lowe&Richards>{{cite journal |last=Lowe |first=K. W. |last2=Richards |first2=G. C. |date=1991 |title=Morphological Variation in the Sacred Ibis ''Threskiornis aethiopicus'' Superspecies Complex |url=http://cescos.fau.edu/gawliklab/papers/LoweRichards1991_SAIB.pdf |journal=Emu |volume=91 |issue=1 |pages=41\u201345 |doi=10.1071/MU9910041 |access-date=18 April 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180418225850/http://cescos.fau.edu/gawliklab/papers/LoweRichards1991_SAIB.pdf |archive-date=18 April 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn 1990, Sibley & Monroe, in the general reference 'Distribution and Taxonomy of Birds of the World' followed Roselaar in recognising 4 species, which they repeated in 'A World Checklist of Birds' of 1993.<ref name=iucn/>\n\nThis taxon being split from ''T. melanocephalus'' and ''T. molucca'' was further advocated by another morphological study by Lowe and Richards in 1991, where, like Holyoak, they looked at plumage again but used much more skins, but unlike him concluded that the differences were such to merit separate species status for the three taxons, especially as they could find no intergradation in morphological characters in possible contact zones in SE Asia. They also cite purported differences in courtship displays between the Australian and Asian birds. Based on these characteristics they recommended the Malagasy birds be considered a subspecies of ''T. aethiopicus''.<ref name=Lowe&Richards/>\n\nIn 2003, Birdlife International elected to adopt the narrow taxonomic concept as advocated in Sibley & Monroe 1993.<ref name=iucn/>\n\n== Description ==\n[[File:Threskiornis aethiopicus - Durban -South Africa-8.jpg|thumb|Flying in South Africa]]\nAn adult individual is {{convert|68|cm|in|abbr=on}} long with all-white body [[plumage]] apart from dark plumes on the rump. Wingspan is {{convert|112|to|124|cm|in|abbr=on}} and body weight {{convert|1.35|to|1.5|kg|lb|abbr=on}}.<ref name=adw>{{cite web|last=Ramsey|first=C.|title=''Threskiornis aethiopicus''|url=http://animaldiversity.org/accounts/Threskiornis_aethiopicus/|work=University of Michigan Museum of Zoology|publisher=Animal Diversity Web}}</ref><ref name=anc>{{cite web|title=''Sacred Ibis Bird''|url=https://animalcorner.co.uk/animals/sacred-ibis-bird/|publisher=Animal Corner}}</ref> Males are generally slightly larger than females.<ref>{{cite web|title=African sacred ibis|url=https://www.sa-venues.com/wildlife/birds_sacred_ibis.htm|publisher=sa-venues}}</ref>\n\nThe bald head and neck, thick curved bill and legs are black. The white wings show a black rear border in flight. The eyes are brown with a dark red [[orbital ring]].<ref name=adw/> Sexes are similar, but juveniles have dirty white plumage, a smaller bill and some feathering on the neck, greenish-brown scapulars and more black on the primary coverts.<ref name=adw/>\n\nThis bird is usually silent, but occasionally makes some croaking noises, unlike its vocal relative, the [[hadada ibis]].\n\n== Distribution ==\n=== Native ===\nThe sacred ibis breeds in [[Sub-Saharan Africa]] and southeastern [[Iraq]]. A number of populations are migrant with the rains; some of the South African birds migrate 1,500&nbsp;km as far north as Zambia, the African birds north of the equator migrate in the opposite direction. The Iraqi population usually migrates to southwestern Iran, but wandering vagrants have been seen as far south as Oman (rare, but regular) and as far north as the Caspian coasts of Kazakhstan and Russia (before 1945).<ref name=AEWA1999>{{cite report |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=March 1999 |title=Report on the Conservation Status of Migratory Waterbirds in the Agreement Area|url=http://www.unep-aewa.org/sites/default/files/publication/ts1_conservation_status_report_wi_0.pdf|publisher=Wetlands International, for the Agreement on the Conservation of African-Eurasian Migratory Waterbirds Secretariat |pages= 20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unep-aewa.org/en/species/threskiornis-aethiopicus-0|title=''Threskiornis aethiopicus''|publisher=United Nations Environment Programme (UNEP), Agreement on the Conservation of African-Eurasian Migratory Waterbirds (AEWA)|access-date= 29 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite report |last=Watson |first=Mike |date=2014 |title=BirdQuest Tour Report: Oman & Bahrain 2014 |url=http://www.birdquest-tours.com/pdfs/report/OMAN%20-%20BAHRAIN%20REP%2014-ebook.pdf |publisher=Birdquest Tours |pages=20, 26}}</ref><ref name=Y\u00e9sou>{{cite journal |last= Y\u00e9sou|first= Pierre|last2= Clergeau|first2=Philippe |date=2005 |title= Sacred Ibis: a new invasive species in Europe|url=http://www.birdingworld.co.uk/images/SacredIbises.pdf |journal=Birding World |volume=18 |issue=12 |pages=517\u2013526 |access-date=9 January 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==== Africa ====\nIt was formerly found in [[Egypt]], where it was commonly venerated and mummified as a votive offering to the god [[Thoth]]. For many centuries until the Roman period the main temples buried a few dozen of thousands of birds a year, and to sustain sufficient numbers for the demand for sacrifices by pilgrims from all over Egypt, dozens of ibis breeding farms (called ''ibiotropheia'' by [[Herodotus]]) were established, initially throughout Egypt, but later centralised around the main temples, each producing around a thousand mummies annually.<ref name=Wasef>Wasef, Sally A. (2016); \"Ancient Egyptian Sacred Ibis Mummies: Evolutionary Mitogenomics Resolves the History of Ancient Farming\". Thesis (PhD Doctorate); Griffith University; Brisbane</ref> [[Aristotle]] mentions in c. 350 BC that many sacred ibises are found all over Egypt.<ref>{{cite book |author=Aristotle (c. 350 BC) |translator-last=Thompson |translator-first=D'Arcy Wentworth |title=\u03a4\u1ff6\u03bd \u03c0\u03b5\u03c1\u1f76 \u03c4\u1f70 \u03b6\u1ff7\u03b1 \u1f31\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03c1\u03b9\u1ff6\u03bd |trans-title=History of Animals |url=http://classics.mit.edu/Aristotle/history_anim.9.ix.html |volume=Book IX, prt 27}}</ref> [[Strabo]], writing around 20 AD, mentions large amounts of the birds in the streets of [[Alexandria]], where he was living at the time; picking through the trash, attacking provisions, and defiling everything with their dung.<ref name=Buffon/> [[Pierre Belon]] notes the many ibises in Egypt during his travels there in the late 1540s (he thought they were an odd type of stork).<ref name=Buffon/> [[Beno\u00eet de Maillet]], in his ''Description de l'Egypte'' (1735) relates that at the turn of the 17th century, when the great caravans travelled yearly to Mecca, great clouds of ibises would follow them from Egypt for over a hundred leagues into the desert to feed on the dung left at the encampments.<ref name=Buffon/> By 1850, however, the species had disappeared from Egypt both as a breeding and migrant population, with the last, albeit questionable, sighting in 1864.<ref name=Wasef/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chn-france.org/eorc/eorc.php?id_content=4/|title=''Updated Checklist of the Birds of Egypt''|publisher=Comit\u00e9 d'Homologation National for the Egyptian Ornithological Rarities Committee|access-date= 29 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe species did not breed in southern Africa before the beginning of the 20th century, but it has benefited from irrigation, dams, and commercial agricultural practices such as dung heaps, carrion and refuse tips. It began to breed in the early 20th century, and in the 1970s the first colonies of ibises were recorded in Zimbabwe and South Africa. Its population for example expanded 2-3-fold during the period between 1972\u20131995 in [[Orange Free State]]. It is now found throughout southern Africa.<ref name=Marion>L. Marion: ''Is the Sacred ibis a real threat to biodiversity? Long-term study of its diet in non-native areas compared to native areas.'' In: ''Comptes Rendus Biologies.'' Volume 336, Number 4, April 2013, {{ISSN|1768-3238}}, S.&nbsp;207\u2013220, {{doi|10.1016/j.crvi.2013.05.001}}. {{PMID|23849724}}.</ref><ref name=Kopij1999>{{cite journal |last=Kopij |first=Grzegorz |date=1999 |title=Breeding ecology of the Sacred Ibis ''Threskiornis aethiopicus'' in the Free State, South Africa |url=http://cescos.fau.edu/gawliklab/papers/KopijG1999.pdf |journal=South African Journal Wildlife Research |volume=29 |issue=1 |pages=25\u201330 |issn=0379-4369 |access-date=10 April 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180330080216/http://cescos.fau.edu/gawliklab/papers/KopijG1999.pdf |archive-date=30 March 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The species is a common resident in most parts of South Africa. Local numbers are swollen in summer by individuals migrating southwards from the equator.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://dewetswild.com/2016/11/25/african-sacred-ibis/ |title=African Sacred Ibis - de Wets Wild |last=de Wets |first=Dries |date=November 25, 2016 |access-date=29 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nElsewhere in Africa it occurs throughout the continent south of the Sahara, but it is largely absent in the deserts of southwestern Africa (i.e. the [[Namib]], the [[Karoo]], the [[Kalahari]]) and probably the rainforests of the Congo. In west Africa it is fairly uncommon across the [[Sahel]], except for the major floodplain systems. It can commonly found breeding along the Niger, in the Inner Niger Delta of Mali, the [[Logone River|Logone]] of C.A.R., [[Lake Fitri|Lac Fitri]] in Chad, the [[Saloum Delta]] of Senegal, and other localities in relatively small numbers such as in The Gambia. It is common across eastern Africa and southern Africa. Large numbers can be found in the [[Sudd]] swamps and [[Lake Kundi]] in Sudan in the dry season. It is fairly widespread along the upper Nile River, and is quite common around Mogadishu, Somalia. In Tanzania there are a number of sites with 500 to 1,000+ birds, totalling some 20,000 birds.<ref>{{cite report |last=Dodman |first=Tim |date=September 2014 |title=Status, Estimates and Trends of Waterbird Populations in Africa: AEWA-listed African populations |url=https://www.wetlands.org/publications/1304/ |publisher=Wetlands International |pages=23\u201324}}</ref>\n\n==== Asia ====\nThe bird is also native to Yemen; in 2003 it bred in large numbers on small islands near [[Haramous]] and along the Red Sea coast near [[Hodeidah]] and [[Aden]], where it was often found at waste-water treatment plants. It has been recorded nesting on a shipwreck in the Red Sea.<ref>{{cite book |last=Shobrak |first=Mohammed|last2=Al Suhaibany |first2=Abdullah |last3=Al-Sagheir |first3=Omer |date=November 2003 |title=Status of Breeding Seabirds in the Red Sea and Gulf of Aden - PERSGA Technical Series No. 8 |url=http://www.persga.org/Files/Common/Sea_Birds/Reginal_Status_of_Seabirds.pdf |location=Jeddah, Saudi Arabia |publisher=The Regional Organization for the Conservation of the Environment of the Red Sea and Gulf of Aden (PERSGA)}}</ref> It is also seen as a vagrant on [[Socotra]].<ref name=MiddleEast >{{cite book |last=Porter |first=Richard |last2=Aspinall |first2=Simon |date=10 Dec 2016 |title=Birds of the Middle East |edition=3rd |location=London |publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing |page=58 |isbn=9781472946003}}</ref>\nWith the current war and famine, there have been no new census reports on the species in Yemen,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://iwc.wetlands.org/index.php/spectotals |title=Country count totals by species for the period 2013 - 2017 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |publisher=International Waterbird Census |access-date=31 March 2018}}</ref> however an estimate of approximately 30 mature individuals was given in 2015.<ref>{{cite book |last=Symes |first=A.|last2=Taylor |first2=J. |last3=Mallon |first3=D. |last4=Porter |first4=R. |last5=Simms |first5=C. |last6=Budd |first6=K. |date=2015 |title=The Conservation Status and Distribution of the Breeding Birds of the Arabian Peninsula |url=https://portals.iucn.org/library/sites/library/files/documents/RL-53-004.pdf |location=Sharjah, U.A.E. |publisher=IUCN, Gland, Switzerland and Cambridge, UK and the Environment and Protected Areas Authority, Government of Sharjah |page=21 |isbn=978-2-8317-1751-7 |doi=10.2305/IUCN.CH.2015.MRA.5.en }}</ref>\n\nThe species was fairly common in Iraq in the first half of the 20th century, but by the late 1960s it had become very scarce, with the population thought to number no more than 200 birds. The population was thought to have suffered greatly during the draining of the [[Mesopotamian Marshes]] of southeastern Iraq starting in the late 1980s, and feared to have disappeared entirely, but it has continuously been observed breeding in a colony in the [[Hawizeh Marshes]] (a part of the Mesopotamian Marshes) as of 2008, numbering up to 27 adults.<ref name=AEWA1999/><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Salim|first=Mudhafar|last2=Porter|first2=Richard|last3=Rubec|first3=Clayton|year=2009|title=A summary of birds recorded in the marshes of southern Iraq, 2005\u20132008 (in: Environment, Biodiversity and Conservation in the Middle East. Proceedings of the First Middle Eastern Biodiversity Congress, Aqaba, Jordan, 20\u201323 October 2008)|url=https://biorisk.pensoft.net/article/1840/download/pdf/|journal=BioRisk|volume=3|issue=1|pages=205\u2013219|doi=10.3897/biorisk.3.14}}</ref> It is also native to [[Kuwait]], where it occurs as an extremely rare migrant, with only two known sightings, the last being a flock of 17 in 2007.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kuwaitbirds.org/birds/african-sacred-ibis|title=African Sacred Ibis - KuwaitBirds.org|date= 2012|publisher=Birds of Kuwait by Biodiversity East sponsored by Kuwait Foreign Petroleum Exploration Company (KUFPEC)|access-date= 29 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nThere are no records of the bird in Iran before the 1970s, however small numbers were found overwintering in [[Khuzestan]] in 1970. Since the 1990s numbers appear to have slowly increased to a few dozen.<ref name=Iran>{{Cite journal|last=Khaleghizadeh|first=A.|last2=Scott|first2=D. A.|last3=Tohidifar|first3=M.|last4=Babak|first4=S.|last5=Musavi|first5=M. G.|last6=Sehhatisabet|first6=M. E.|last7=Ashoori|first7=A.|last8=Khani|first8=A.|last9=Bakhtiari|first9=P.|last10=Amini|first10=H.|last11=Rooselaar|first11=C.|last12=Ay\u00e9|first12=R.|last13=Ullman|first13=M.|last14=Nezami|first14=B.|last15=Eskandari|first15=F.|year=2011|title=Rare birds in Iran in 1980\u2212 2010|url=http://www.osme.org/tripreports/PODOCES%206_1_%20Rare%20Birds%20in%20Iran%20in%201980-2010.pdf|journal=Podoces|volume=6|issue=1|pages=1\u201348|issn=1735-6725|access-date=2018-03-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130201165126/http://www.osme.org/tripreports/PODOCES%206_1_%20Rare%20Birds%20in%20Iran%20in%201980-2010.pdf|archive-date=2013-02-01|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n=== Introduced ===\nThe first African sacred ibises brought to Europe were two imported from Egypt to France in the mid-1700s.<ref name=Buffon/> In the 1800s the first escapes were sighted in Europe (in Austria, Italy). In the 1970s it became fashionable for many zoos in Europe and elsewhere to keep their birds in free-flying colonies, which were allowed to forage in the area but would return to roost in the zoo every day. As such feral populations were established in [[Italy]], [[France]], [[Spain]], the Netherlands, the Canary Islands, Florida, [[Taiwan]], the United Arab Emirates and possibly Bahrain.<ref name=iucn/><ref name=Y\u00e9sou/><ref name=WildEast>{{cite news |last=Charlier |first=Phillip |date=25 April 2016 |title=The Sacred Ibis Runs Rampant in Taiwan |url=http://news.thewildeast.net/the-sacred-ibis-runs-rampant-in-taiwan/ |newspaper=The Wild East Magazine|access-date= 9 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nSome studies indicate that the introduced populations in Europe have significant economic and ecological impacts,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Kumschick|first1=S.|last2=Nentwig|first2=W.|year=2010|title=Some alien birds have as severe an impact as the most effectual alien mammals in Europe|journal=Biological Conservation|volume=143|issue=11|pages=2757\u20132762|doi=10.1016/j.biocon.2010.07.023}}</ref> while others suggest that they constitute no substantial threat to native European bird species.<ref name=Marion/>\n\n==== Europe ====\nIn France the African sacred ibises have become established along its Atlantic coast following the feral breeding of birds which were the offspring of a large free-flying population originating from the Branf\u00e9r\u00e9 Zoological Gardens in southern [[Brittany]]. The first successful breeding was in 1993 at two sites, the [[Golfe du Morbihan]] and [[Lac de Grand-Lieu]], {{cvt|25|km}} and {{cvt|70|km}} respectively from Branf\u00e9r\u00e9. By 2005 the Atlantic French breeding population was estimated at 1,100 pairs and winter censuses led to an estimated total population of up to 3,000 birds. A separate population originated from a zoo at [[Sigean]] on the Mediterranean coast of France and by 2005 the colony at the [[Etang de Bages-et Sigean]] was estimated at 250 pairs.<ref name=Y\u00e9sou/> A cull was begun and by 2011 the population had fallen to 560\u2013600 pairs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oncfs.gouv.fr/IMG/pdf/Bilan_nidification_ibis_sacre_2011.pdf |title=Nidification de l'ibis sacr\u00e9 dans l'ouest de la France en 2011 |language=French |accessdate=5 January 2018 |author=Pierre Y\u00e9sou |date=23 November 2011 |publisher=Office National de la Chasse et de la Faune Sauvage}}</ref> By January 2017 the eradication programme had lowered the number of birds in roosts in western France to 300\u2013500 birds and the Lac de Grand-Lieu was the only regular breeding site in the region; as the programme has progressed the birds have become warier and the reduced numbers mean the effort and cost per bird has increased and complete eradication may never be achieved. The population near Sigean was eradicated by killing and capturing the birds with only a few remaining in the [[Camargue]].<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Pierre Y\u00e9sou |author2= Philippe Clergeau |author3=Suzanne Bastian |author4=S\u00e9bastien Reeber |author5=Jean-Fran\u00e7ois Maillard |last-author-amp=yes |year=2017 |title=The Sacred Ibis in Europe: ecology and management |journal=British Birds |volume=110 |issue=April 2017 |pages=197\u2013212}}</ref>\n\nThis species is not considered established in mainland Spain. The Barcelona Zoo kept a small free-flying population which bred in the zoo and at least once in 1974 in the surrounding city park. Between 1983 and 1985 they had increased to 18 birds, but these subsequently declined to 4\u20136 pairs in the 1990s and the birds were permanently caged by the end of the 1990s (the zoo still has some). In 2001 the remaining birds in the surroundings were culled, thus ending the occurrence of the species in the 'wild' in the area. However, in the early 2000s vagrants from most probably France were recorded in northern Catalonia, and sporadic observations throughout the year have been recorded since then along the Mediterranean and Cantabrian coasts. There were a total of about twenty approved records of sightings between 1994 and 2004.<ref name=Y\u00e9sou/><ref name=DAISIE>{{cite report |last=Clergeau |first=Philippe |last2=Y\u00e9sou |first2=Pierre |date=12 October 2006 |title=''Threskiornis aethiopicus'' |url=http://www.europe-aliens.org/speciesFactsheet.do?speciesId=50480# |publisher=Delivering Alien Invasive Species Inventories for Europe (DAISIE) |access-date=9 April 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161126003457/http://www.europe-aliens.org/speciesFactsheet.do?speciesId=50480 |archivedate=26 November 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=Cat\u00e1logoEspa\u00f1ol>{{cite report |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=September 2013 |title=Cat\u00e1logo Espa\u00f1ol de Especies Ex\u00f3ticas Invasoras - ''Threskiornis aethiopicus'' |url=http://www.mapama.gob.es/es/biodiversidad/temas/conservacion-de-especies/Threskiornis_aethiopicus_2013_tcm30-69957.pdf |language=Spanish |publisher=Ministerio de Agricultura y Pesca, Alimentaci\u00f3n y Medio Ambiente}}</ref><ref name=SEO>{{cite web |url=https://www.seo.org/ave/ibis-sagrado/ |title=Ibis sagrado SEOBirdLife |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=2008 |language=Spanish |publisher=Sociedad Espa\u00f1ola de Ornitolog\u00eda |access-date=7 April 2018 |quote=}}</ref> As of 2009, birds entering Spain from France are shot.<ref name=CABI/>\n \nThe population in Italy may have been introduced from the zoo [[Faunistic Park Le Cornelle|Le Cornelle]] which has kept a free-flying group since the early 1980s, or possibly from Brittany, but this is unclear. The first pair was seen breeding in the nearby heronry at Oldenico, in Lame del Sesia Regional Park in [[Novara]], NW Italy, in 1989. By 1998 there was a colony of 9 pairs and 48 birds there; by 2000 there were 24\u201326 pairs, and by 2003 there were 25\u201330 breeding pairs. A second colony appeared in 2004 at another nearby heronry at Casalbeltrame. These birds would mostly feed in the rice fields in the area, but would also migrate elsewhere during the summer, with the population at the roosts increasing in the winter. In 2008, the number of breeding ibis was estimated at 80\u2013100 pairs, and at least 300 birds. That same year, six individuals, consisting of three pairs, were observed roosting at a heronry in [[Casaleggio Novara|Casaleggio]]. By 2009 they were said to be one of the most characteristic animals of the rice-growing area of Novara and [[Vercellese]]. In 2010 the species was reported attempting to breed in the [[Po (river)|Po]] Delta, northeast Italy. By 2014 reports of individuals and small flocks were recorded in various areas from the Po Valley down to [[Tuscany]]. Outside the Piedmont Region, cases of possible nesting are reported in [[Emilia-Romagna]], [[Veneto]] and [[Lombardy]]. As of 2017 there do not seem to be coordinated control efforts in Italy.<ref name=Quaderni>{{cite magazine |last=Usai |first=Alessio |last2=Billington |first2=Richard |last3=Re |first3=Alessandro |last4=Rigamonti |first4=Ettore |last5=Festari |first5=Igor |date=2009 |title=L'Ibis sacro in Provincia di Novara |url=http://www.ebnitalia.it/QB/QB021/index.htm |magazine=Quaderni di Birdwatching |language=Italian |location=Verona |publisher=EBN Italia |volume=21 |issue=XI |access-date=17 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite newsgroup |title=Italy wild-occurring hybrid African spoonbill X Sacred ibis (photos) |author=italianbirder |date=4 March 2010 |newsgroup=www.surfbirds.com |url=http://www.surfbirds.com/forum/forum/rare-bird-information/european-rare-birds/5385-italy-wild-occurring-hybrid-african-spoonbill-x-sacred-ibis-photos |access-date=16 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tenutasanguido.com/pdf/BOLGHERI%20OASI/IbisSacro%20Eng.pdf |title=Oasi di Bolgheri - The African sacred ibis (''Threskiornis aethiopicus'') - A new species for the Bolgheri Bird Sanctuary |last=Politi |first=Paolo Maria |date=23 November 2014 |publisher=WWF OASI |access-date=17 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.parcodelmincio.it/infonatura-dettaglio.php?id=42880 |title=Lo strano caso dell'ibis sacro\u2026 |last=Pavesi |first=Alessandro |date=14 July 2017 |language=Italian |location=Mantua |publisher=Gruppo Ricerche Avifauna Mantova (GRAM) for Parco del Mincio |access-date=17 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the Netherlands, sacred ibises were introduced from three sources; primarily from the free-flying flock at the [[aviary]] zoo [[Vogelpark Avifauna|Avifauna]], and another group of 11 birds which escaped from a private bird trader in [[Weert]] when a tree fell on their enclosure sometime between 1998 and 2000 which would all return to their cage each winter. Furthermore, in 2000 a group of sacred ibises escaped from a zoo near [[Munster]], some of which apparently crossed the border into [[Overijssel]], as the colours of their [[Bird ringing|rings]] closely matched. The free-flying Avifauna flock numbered 12 in 2001, 30 in 2003, and an estimated maximum of 41 birds escaped the zoo eventually. There had been sightings throughout the country for many years, but in 2002 successful breeding was first reported in a nature reserve some 40&nbsp;km from Avifauna. \nBy 2007 the feral population in the Netherlands had increased to 15 pairs breeding at three locations, including in a tree just outside the zoo. Pairs would regularly move from the zoo to the nature reserve in the summer and vice versa. The next year, in 2008, the tree outside the zoo was cut down, and free-flying birds were recaptured, clipped and caged. 2008/2009 was also a cold winter and many birds died. By 2009 37 birds had been recaptured and by 2010 there were no more birds breeding in the wild. The birds in Weert were halved in number after the 2008\u20132009 winter and had disappeared somewhere between 2011 and 2015. As of 2016 a few birds survive, some still attempting to breed in Overijssel, and handful sightings of less than three reported. Possible vagrants from France have also been noted (by their rings) after 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.michelklemann.nl/ibis/index.htm |title=Heilige Ibis ''Threskiornis aethiopicus'' Sacred Ibis |last=Klemann |first=Michel |date=n.d. |language=Dutch |access-date=9 April 2018}}</ref><ref name=Waardenburg>{{cite report |last=Smits |first=R.R. |last2=van Horssen |first2=P. |last3=van der Winden |first3=J. |date=26 February 2010 |title=A risk analysis of the sacred ibis in The Netherlands |url=https://www.buwa.nl/fileadmin/buwa_upload/Bureau_Waardenburg_rapporten/09-556_Risk_analysis_sacred_ibis.pdf |publisher=Bureau Waardenburg B.V. |docket=Report nr 10-005}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sovon.nl/nl/soort/1420 |title=Heilige Ibis Sovon.nl |author=<!--Not stated--> |language=Dutch |publisher= Sovon Vogelonderzoek Nederland |date=n.d.|access-date=9 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==== Elsewhere ====\nThe sacred ibis is not considered invasive on the Canary Islands.<ref name=Cat\u00e1logoEspa\u00f1ol/> It is kept in zoos on Tenerife, Gran Canaria, Lanzarote and Fuerteventura, two of which kept their collections free-flying. In 1989, the first ibis was seen in the wild. In 1997, the first pair was seen breeding outside a zoo, the population reached a maximum of 5 pairs between then and 2005, and 30 pairs is given by Clergeau & Y\u00e9sou in 2006 (though this last number is untrustworthy). The birds are divided between the islands Lanzarote (near [[Arrecife]] in an old heron colony) and Fuerteventura (in the zoo near La Lajita but free-flying). On both islands, these birds have remained very near to the zoos. The breeding is 'controlled'. There is disagreement regarding the origin of other records, especially during the migratory period. Ibises have been seen on all four of the islands where there are zoos that keep them.<ref name=Y\u00e9sou/><ref name=DAISIE/><ref name=Cat\u00e1logoEspa\u00f1ol/><ref name=SEO/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://blog.birdingcanarias.com/2009/02/ibis-sagrado-en-tenerife.html |title=Birding Canarias - Ibis Sagrado en Tenerife |last=Ramos |first=Juan Jos\u00e9 |date=12 February 2009 |language=Spanish |access-date=6 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nIntroduced sacred ibises bred in the [[United Arab Emirates]] in the wildlife reserve on [[Sir Bani Yas]] Island, where 6 were introduced in the early 1980s, and which did not leave the island. There was only one left in 1989 and it died that year. [[Al Ain Zoo]] has had a flock since 1976, which had increased to some 70 birds by 1991. There are records of ibises showing up in [[Dubai]] since the 1980s. Birds in Al Ain initially stayed at the zoo, but began to fly from the zoo to the sewage treatment plant and a shallow wet area in the former public park, now luxury villa park, Ain Al Fayda, where their numbers increased slowly up to 32 in 1997 and they had bred by 1998. They were not numerous outside these locations in 2002, but by 2001 1-5 ibises would show up regularly in Dubai in such places as the golf course, the sewage treatment plant, and the construction site of the now completed [[Dubai International City]]. Breeding has since occurred in Dubai. The Dubai birds especially may be partially vagrants arrived from the Iraqi marshes, as they often show up during the migrating season.<ref name=Y\u00e9sou/><ref name=MiddleEast/><ref name=CABI/><ref name=Klemann/><ref>{{cite report |last=Pedersen |first=T. |last2=Aspinall |first2=S.J. |last3=Campbell |first3=O.J. |last4=Smiles |first4=M.C. |date=2017 |title=EBRC Annotated Checklist of the birds of the United Arab Emirates |url=http://www.uaebirding.com/uaechecklist.html |publisher=Emirates Bird Records Committee |page=125 |access-date=11 April 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180412082728/http://www.uaebirding.com/uaechecklist.html |archivedate=12 April 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> On the other hand, a bird showing up in Iran is suspected to be from the introduced U.A.E. population.<ref name=Iran/> As of 2010 the population in Al Ain numbers over 75 birds, and the free-flying zoo birds roost in two subcolonies on top of their aviary. Birds regularly show up throughout the city and surrounding villages and can often be seen in the early morning in parks and roundabouts picking up scraps left by people the night before.<ref>{{cite newsgroup |title=Sacred ibis in Green Mubazzara |author=Rezak Khan |date=30 April 2010 |url=http://www.uaebirding.com/forum/showthread.php?2645-sacred-ibis-in-Green-Mubazzara |access-date=11 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nA breeding population was listed as introduced on [[Bahrain]] since at least 2006,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hawar-islands.com/checklist.html |title=Bahrain Check List |last=King |first=Howard |date=n.d. |access-date=10 April 2018}}</ref> but it is also said to be a vagrant on the island.<ref name=MiddleEast/>\n\nIn Taiwan, as elsewhere, the founding population escaped from a zoo, in this case before 1984, at which time the first wild birds were seen at [[Guandu Nature Park|Guandu]] in [[Taipei]]. In 1998 it was estimated that some 200 birds roamed freely, primarily in northern Taiwan. In 2010 it was first added to the Checklist of Birds of Taiwan with the status of 'uncommon' (as opposed to 'rare'). By 2010 \nthe birds were also occasionally sighted on the [[Matsu Islands]], which are only 19&nbsp;km off the coast of [[Fujian]] province in mainland China (and only a few kilometres from other coastal Chinese islands), but 190&nbsp;km from Taiwan. In 2012 the population was estimated to be 500\u2013600 individuals, and had spread to the west of Taiwan. The first attempts at culling were performed in 2012 using the [[Cormorant culling|egg-oiling method]] (unsuccessful), and by killing chicks from nests (successful). By 2016 the number was estimated at 1000 individuals, of whom around 500 inhabited a wetland in [[Changhua County]].<ref name=WildEast/><ref name=Klemann/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bird.org.tw/index.php/works/lists |title=\u53f0\u7063\u9ce5\u985e\u540d\u9304 The Checklist of Birds of Taiwan |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=26 April 2017 |publisher=\u4e2d\u83ef\u6c11\u570b\u91ce\u9ce5\u5b78\u6703 The Republic of China Wild Bird Society |language=Chinese |access-date=8 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bird.org.tw/index.php/news/cwbf/1011-2015-03-05-01-40-10 |title=\u5916\u4f86\u5165\u4fb5\u9ce5\u7a2e\u57c3\u53ca\u8056\u9e6e\u9632\u6cbb |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=5 March 2015 |publisher=\u4e2d\u83ef\u6c11\u570b\u91ce\u9ce5\u5b78\u6703 The Republic of China Wild Bird Society |language=Chinese |access-date=8 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn Florida five individuals of the species are thought to have escaped Miami Metro Zoo, and perhaps more from private collections, after [[Hurricane Andrew]] in 1992. These birds lived in the surroundings but would return to roost at the zoo at night, and the population slowly increased to 30 or 40 by 2005. That same year two pairs were found nesting in the [[Everglades]]. Two or three years later the decision was made to remove the species. By 2009 75 birds were removed from Florida, and the birds are believed to be eradicated.<ref name=Y\u00e9sou/><ref>{{cite report |last=Johnson |first=Steve A. |last2=McGarrity |first2=Monica |date=October 2009 |title=Florida's Introduced Birds: Sacred Ibis (''Threskiornis aethiopicus'') |url=http://ufdcimages.uflib.ufl.edu/IR/00/00/34/25/00001/UW31200.pdf |publisher=Wildlife Ecology and Conservation Department, Florida Cooperative Extension Service, Institute of Food and Agricultural Sciences, University of Florida}}</ref>\n\n== Ecology ==\n=== Habitat ===\nThe African sacred ibis occurs in marshy wetlands and mud flats, both inland and on the coast. It preferably nests on trees in or near water. It feeds wading in very shallow wetlands or slowly stomping in wet pastures with soft soil. It will also visit cultivation and [[rubbish dumps]].<ref name=Kopij1999/><ref name=Waardenburg/>\n\n=== Diet ===\nThe species are predators which feed primarily by day, generally in flocks. The diet consists of mainly insects, worms, crustaceans, molluscs and other invertebrates, as well as various fish, frogs, reptiles, small mammals and carrion.<ref name=adw/><ref name=Waardenburg/><ref name=biex>{{cite web|title=''Threskiornis aethiopicus'' (African sacred ibis, Sacred ibis) |url=http://www.biodiversityexplorer.org/birds/threskiornithidae/threskiornis_aethiopicus.htm|publisher=Biodiversity Explorer}}</ref> It may also probe into the soil with its long beak for invertebrates such as earthworms.<ref name=biex/> It does even feed on seeds.<ref>{{cite iucn |url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22697510/0 |title=Threskiornis aethiopicus (African Sacred Ibis, Sacred Ibis)}}</ref>\n\nSacred ibises were observed to occasionally feed on the contents of pelican eggs broken by [[Egyptian vulture]]s in the mixed colonies of the ibises, [[Great cormorant|cormorants]], [[Great white pelican|pelicans]] and [[Abdim's stork]]s at Lake Shala in Ethiopia.<ref name=Urban>{{cite journal |last=Urban |first=Emil K. |date=July 1974 |title=Breeding of Sacred ibis ''Threskiornis aethiopica'' at lake Shala, Ethiopia |journal=Ibis |volume=116 |issue=3 |pages=263\u2013277 |doi=10.1111/j.1474-919X.1974.tb00124.x }}</ref> On [[Central Island]] in [[Lake Turkana]] sacred ibises were noted to incidentally eat [[Nile crocodile]] eggs excavated by [[Varanus salvator|Nile monitors]].<ref name=Marion/> Most recently, in 2006, observations were reported from a large mixed colony on [[Bird Island Nature Reserve (South Africa)|Bird Island]] (called Penguin Island in the article) in South Africa, where 10,000 pairs of [[Morus capensis|gannets]] nested, together with 4800 pairs of [[Cape cormorant]] and other species such as gulls and [[Spheniscus demersus|jackass penguin]]. Within a period of 3 years, a few specialized sacred ibis individuals out of the 400 that roosted on the island had fed on at least 152 eggs of the cormorant (other species were even more ovivorous).<ref>{{cite journal |last=Williams |first=Anthony J. |last2=Ward |first2=V. L. |date=September 2006 |title=Sacred Ibis and Gray Heron Predation of Cape Cormorant Eggs and Chicks; and a Review of Ciconiiform Birds as Seabird Predators |url=http://cescos.fau.edu/gawliklab/papers/WilliamsAJandVLWard2006.pdf |journal=Waterbirds |volume=29 |issue=3 |pages=321\u2013327 |doi=10.1675/1524-4695(2006)29[321:SIAGHP]2.0.CO;2 |access-date=12 April 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180418161140/http://cescos.fau.edu/gawliklab/papers/WilliamsAJandVLWard2006.pdf |archive-date=18 April 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn a study of [[Pellet (ornithology)|pellets]] and stomachs contents of nestlings in the Free State, South Africa, food is mostly reported to consist of frogs (mainly ''[[Angola river frog|Amietia angolensis]]'' and ''[[Xenopus laevis]]''), ''[[Potamonautes|Potamonautes warreni]]'' crabs, [[Calliphoridae|blow fly]] maggots, [[Sphingidae]] caterpillars, and adult beetles. During the first 10 days of life nestlings fed mainly on crabs and beetles, and later mainly on Sphingidae caterpillars and more beetles. The breeding colony collected different (proportions of) prey the subsequent year.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Kopij |first=Grzegorz |last2=Kok |first2=Ordino B. |last3=Roos |first3=Zennon N. |date=1996 |title=Food of Sacred Ibis Threskiornis aethiopicus nestlings in the Free State province, South Africa |journal=Ostrich |volume=67 |issue=3\u20134 |pages=138\u2013143 |doi=10.1080/00306525.1996.9639698 }}</ref>  The food of one one\u2010month old nestlings at [[Lake Shala]], Ethiopia, consisted of beetle larvae, caterpillars and beetles.<ref name=Urban/> In France, adult ibises fed largely on the invasive crayfish ''[[Procambarus clarkii]]'', for nestlings larvae of ''[[Eristalis]]'' species are important.<ref name=Marion/><ref name=Waardenburg/>\n\nIn France, they sometimes supplement their diet by feeding at rubbish tips in the winter.<ref name=Marion/>\n\n=== Predators ===\nThe most important predator of nestlings of the sacred ibis in Kenya is the [[African fish eagle]], which preferentially searches for the largest (sub-)colonies to attack, but in Ethiopia and South Africa it poses less of a threat.<ref name=Kopij1999/>\n\n=== Diseases ===\nThis species was reported to be susceptible to avian botulism in a list of dead animals found around a man-made lake in South Africa which tested positive for the pathogen in the late 1960s and early 1970s.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Van Heerden |first=J. |date=1974 |title=Botulism in the Orange Free State goldfields |journal=Ostrich |volume=45 |issue=3 |pages=182\u2013184 |doi=10.1080/00306525.1974.9634055 }}</ref> During a large scale mortality of [[Cape cormorant]]s from [[Fowl cholera|avian cholera]] in 1991 in western South Africa, small numbers of sacred ibis were killed.<ref name=Waardenburg/> The new species ''[[Chlamydia (genus)|Chlamydia ibidis]]'' was isolated from feral sacred ibis in France in 2013; it infected 6-7 of the 70 birds tested.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Vorimore |first=Fabien |last2=Hsia |first2=Ru-ching |last3=Huot-Creasy |first3=Heather |last4=Bastian |first4=Suzanne |last5=Deruyter |first5=Lucie |last6=Passet |first6=Anne  |last7=Sachse |first7=Konrad |last8=Bavoil |first8=Patrik |last9=Myers |first9=Garry |last10=Laroucau |first10=Karine |date=20 September 2013 |title=Isolation of a New ''Chlamydia'' species from the Feral Sacred Ibis (''Threskiornis aethiopicus'')- ''Chlamydia ibidis'' |journal=PLoS ONE |volume=8 |issue=9 |at=e74823 |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0074823 |pmid=24073223 |pmc=3779242 |bibcode=2013PLoSO...874823V }}</ref>\n\nIn 1887, the Italian scientist Corrado Parona reported a 3&nbsp;cm ''[[Physaloptera]]'' species of [[nematode]] in the orbital cavity of a sacred ibis collected in [[Metemma]], Abyssinia (now Ethiopia) in 1882. He thought it was perhaps a new species, as it differed morphologically from earlier seen worms. A single adult female was recovered, and it has never been seen again. As the ''Physaloptera'' species infecting birds are generally parasites of the intestines of raptors; it might be an artefact, or perhaps a misidentification, or possibly a [[Host (biology)#Dead-end hosts|dead-end host]] infection.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Parona |first=Corrado |date=7\u201312 October 1885 |title=Di Alcuni Elminti Raccolti nel Sudan Orientale da O. Beccari e P. Magretti |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/35910#page/446/mode/1up |journal=Annali del Museo Civico di Storia Naturale di Genova |series=2 |language=Italian |volume=22 |pages=438\u2013439 |access-date=15 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Morgan |first=Banner Bill |date=1946 |title=Host-parasite Relationships and Geographical Distribution of the Physalopterinae (Nematoda) |url=http://images.library.wisc.edu/WI/EFacs/transactions/WT1946/reference/wi.wt1946.bbmorgan.pdf |journal=Transactions of the Wisconsin Academy of Sciences, Arts and Letters |volume=38 |issue= |pages=282 |issn=0084-0505 |access-date=15 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Ransom |first=B. H. |date=1904 |title=General Review of Nematodes Parasitic in the Eyes of Birds |url=https://archive.org/stream/mansonseyewormof00rommiala#page/43/mode/1up/search/Physaloptera |journal=Bulletin |issue=60 |pages=43 |doi= |access-date=15 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Cram |first=Eloise B. |date=1927 |title=Bird Parasites of the Nematode Suborders Strongylata, Ascaridata, and Spirurata |url=https://archive.org/stream/bulletinunitedst1401927unit#page/309/mode/1up/search/parona |journal=Bulletin of the United States National Museum |volume=140 |issue= |pages=309 |doi= |access-date=15 April 2018}}</ref> The [[digenea]]n [[Trematoda|trematode]] ''Patagifer bilobus'', a fluke, has been reported from sacred ibis in Sudan before 1949. It lives in the small intestine of this species, among numerous other ibises, spoonbills, and a few other waterfowl. It has a complicated life history involving three [[Host (biology)|hosts]]: the eggs hatch in fresh water where they infect a [[Planorbis planorbis|ram's horn snail]] in which they multiply and produce [[Trematode life cycle stages|cercariae]], which exit and encyst in a larger snail such as a ''[[Lymnaea]]'', waiting to be eaten by a bird.<ref>{{cite journal |last=McDonald |first=Malcolm Edwin |date=August 1969 |title=Catalogue of Helminths of Waterfowl (Anatidae) |url=https://archive.org/stream/specialscientifi126unit#page/155/mode/1up/search/patagifer |department=Bureau of Sport Fisheries and Wildlife |journal=Special Scientific Report--Wildlife |volume=126 |pages=156 |access-date=14 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Reproduction ==\n[[File:African Sacred Ibis colony in Montagu, Western Cape b.JPG|thumb|right|The breeding colony in [[Montagu, Western Cape|Montagu]], [[Western Cape]], South Africa]]\n[[File:Threskiornis aethiopicus MHNT.ZOO.2010.11.63.1.jpg|thumb| ''Threskiornis aethiopicus'' - [[MHNT]]]]\nThe species usually breeds once per year in the wet season. Breeding season is from March to August in Africa, from April to May in [[Iraq]].<ref name=adw/> It builds a stick nest, often in a [[Adansonia|baobab tree]]. The bird nests in tree colonies, often with other large wading birds such as [[stork]]s, [[heron]]s, [[African spoonbill]]s, [[African darter]]s, [[cormorant]]s. It may also form single-species groups on offshore islands or abandoned buildings. Large colonies consist of numerous subcolonies and can number 1000 birds.<ref name=Kopij1999/><ref name=biex/>\n\n[[File:Sacred ibis (Threskiornis aethiopicus) immature.jpg|thumb|immature, [[Uganda]]]]\nFemales lay 1-5 eggs per season, incubated by both parents for 21\u201329 days.<ref name=anc/> After hatching, one parent continuously stays at the nest for the first 7-days.<ref name=adw/> Chicks fledge after 35\u201340 days and are independent after 44\u201348 days, reaching sexual maturity 1\u20135 years after hatching.<ref name=anc/>\n\n== Conservation ==\nThe African sacred ibis is classified as \"[[Least Concern]]\" by the [[IUCN]]. The global population is estimated at 200,000\u2013450,000 individuals but appears to be decreasing.<ref name=iucn/> It is covered by the ''Agreement on the Conservation of African-Eurasian Migratory Waterbirds'' ([[AEWA]]).<ref>{{cite web |title=Threskiornis aethiopicus |url=https://www.unep-aewa.org/en/species/threskiornis-aethiopicus |website=Agreement on the Conservation of African-Eurasian Migratory Waterbirds |publisher=Agreement on the Conservation of African-Eurasian Migratory Waterbirds |accessdate=25 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n== In myth and legend ==\n[[File:IbisCopenhagenMuseum.jpg|thumb|Copenhagen Museum]]\nFor many centuries, sacred ibis, along with two other species in lesser numbers,<ref>{{Cite book |last=Wyatt |first=John |date=26 October 2012 |title=The Encyclopedia of Ancient History |doi=10.1002/9781444338386.wbeah15208 |chapter=Ibis |isbn=9781444338386 }}</ref> were commonly mummified by the [[Ancient Egypt]]ians as a votive offering to the god [[Thoth]]. Thoth, whose head is that of an ibis, is the Ancient Egyptian god of wisdom and reason, and thus of truth, knowledge, learning and study, and writing and mathematics. The sacred ibis was considered the living incarnation of Thoth on earth.\n\nProperly mummified birds enjoyed a path to the afterlife. Pilgrims from all over Egypt brought thousands of ibis offerings to four or more main temples, which at their peak mummified and buried thousands of birds a year in gigantic and ancient catacombs (one complex was in operation for 700 years). Eventually an estimated eight million birds were mummified and entombed by the Ancient Egyptians.\n\nTo sustain sufficient numbers for the large and sometimes growing demand for sacrifices by the people, dozens of ibis breeding farms (called ''ibiotropheia'' by Herodotus) were established, initially throughout the regions of Egypt, but later centralised around the main temples, each producing around a thousand birds for mummies annually. Wild birds were caught and added to the captive flocks. The mummified birds were often young and were usually killed by breaking their neck. The head and bill were often placed between the tail feathers, and a piece of food was often placed in the bill. The particulars of the mummification ritual often differed. The mummies could be stored in ceramic jars, wooden chests or stone sarcophagi. Not all mummies contain whole birds; some (cheaper ones) contain only a leg, an eggshell, or even dried grass from the nest. Birds were given different burials according to their status; as pets, offerings or holy individuals. Special sacred birds were afforded special mummification, transported from their cities to the temples long after normal offerings were sourced from temple farm flocks, and honoured with more luxurious burial. Different regions in Egypt observed slightly different practises regarding the ritual beliefs.<ref name=Wasef/>\n\nIbis mummification started by at least 1,100 BC and petered out by approximately 30 BC. Although the numbers of burials peaked at different times depending on the region and temple, the rituals were most popular from the Late Period to the Ptolemaic Period.<ref name=Wasef/><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wasef|first=S.|last2=Wood|first2=R.|last3=Merghani|first3=S. El|last4=Ikram|first4=S.|last5=Curtis|first5=C.|last6=Holland|first6=B.|last7=Willerslev|first7=E.|last8=Millar|first8=C.D.|last9=Lambert|first9=D.M.|title=Radiocarbon dating of Sacred Ibis mummies from ancient Egypt|journal=Journal of Archaeological Science: Reports|volume=4|pages=355\u2013361|doi=10.1016/j.jasrep.2015.09.020|year=2015}}</ref>\n\nMummified specimens of the African Sacred Ibis were brought back to Europe by Napoleon's army, where they became part of an early debate about evolution.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Curtis|first=Caitlin|last2=Millar|first2=Craig|last3=Lambert|first3=David|date=2018-09-27|title=The Sacred Ibis debate: The first test of evolution|journal=PLOS Biology|volume=16|issue=9|pages=e2005558|doi=10.1371/journal.pbio.2005558|pmid=30260949|pmc=6159855}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Herodotus]] and [[Pliny the Elder]] the ibis was invoked against incursions of winged serpents. Herodotus wrote:\n\n{{quote|There is a region moreover in Arabia, situated nearly over against the city of Buto, to which place I came to inquire about the winged serpents: and when I came thither I saw bones of serpents and spines in quantity so great that it is impossible to make report of the number, and there were heaps of spines, some heaps large and others less large and others smaller still than these, and these heaps were many in number.\nThe region in which the spines are scattered upon the ground is of the nature of an entrance from a narrow mountain pass to a great plain, which plain adjoins the plain of Egypt; and the story goes that at the beginning of spring winged serpents from Arabia fly towards Egypt, and the birds called ibises meet them at the entrance of this country and do not suffer the serpents to go by but kill them. On account of this deed it is (say the Arabians) that the ibis has come to be greatly honored by the Egyptians, and the Egyptians also agree that it is for this reason that they honor these birds.}}\n\n[[Josephus]] tells us that when Moses lead the Hebrews to make war upon the \u00c6thiopians, he brought a great number of the birds in cages of papyrus to oppose any serpents.<ref name=Buffon/>\n\nDue to perhaps a mistranslation of the Greek of Herodotus, before the early 18th century Europeans were convinced that these ibises had human feet.<ref name=Buffon/>\n\n[[Pliny the Elder]] tells us that it was said that the flies that brought pestilence died immediately upon propitiatory sacrifices of this bird.<ref name=Pliny>{{cite book |last=Pliny |title=Natural History |volume=Book X |chapter=Chapter 41 |chapterurl=http://www.masseiana.org/pliny.htm#BOOK%20X|title-link=Natural History (Pliny) }}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Claudius Aelianus]] in ''De Natura Animalium'', and [[Gaius Julius Solinus]], both quoting much earlier but now lost authors, the sacred ibis procreates with its bill, and thus the bird is always a virgin. [[Aristotle]], writing some 500 years earlier, also mentions this theory, but repudiates it. Picrius mentions how the venomous basilisk is hatched from the eggs of ibis, nurtured from the poisons of all the serpents the birds devour. These authors and many others also mention how crocodiles and snakes are rendered motionless after being touched by the feather of an ibis. Claudius Aelianus also says the ibis is consecrated to the moon.<ref name=Buffon/>\n\nPliny and [[Galen]] ascribe the invention of the [[clyster]] (enema) to the ibis, as according to them it gave such treatments to hippopotami. [[Plutarch]] assures us it uses only salt water for this purpose. 1600 years later this was still accepted science, as [[Claude Perrault]], in his anatomical descriptions of the bird, claimed to have found a hole in the bill which the bird used for that purpose.<ref name=Buffon/>\n\nIn the century before the time of Christ and for at least a century after, the worship of [[Isis#Spread|Isis]] had become quite popular in Rome, especially among women, and the ibis had become one of her associated symbols.<ref>{{cite book |last=Heyob |first=Sharon Kelly |date=1975 |title=The Cult of Isis Among Women in the Graeco-Roman World |editor-last=Vermaseren |editor-first=Maarten Jozef |series=\u00c9tudes pr\u00e9liminaires aux religions orientales dans l'Empire Romain - Tomus 51 |location=Leiden |publisher=Brill |pages=15\u201316 |doi=10.1163/9789004296374 |isbn=978-9004043688}}</ref> A number of [[fresco]]es and mosaics in the [[Patrician (ancient Rome)|patrician]] villas of [[Pompeii]] and [[Herculaneum]] of 50BC-79AD show these birds.<ref name=Quaderni/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.artoffresco.com/02-Portfolio/02.1-Birds/ibis.html |title=Ibis, Pompeii 50BC - 79AD, The Art of the Fresco |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=n.d. |access-date=17 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/28772513@N07/8610154333 |title=Landscape with Ibis. Roman fresco from the temple of Isis |author=saamiblog |date=1 April 2013 |access-date=17 April 2018}}</ref>\n \nAccording to some translations of the [[septuagint]], the ibis is one of the unclean birds which may not be eaten ([[Leviticus]] 11:17, [[Deuteronomy]] 14:16).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=Leviticus+11%3A17-19&version=ISV |title=Leviticus 11 17-19 ISV - owls, cormorants, the ibis, water-hens, - Bible Gateway |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=2014 |publisher=International Standard Version Foundation by permission of Davidson Press |access-date=17 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=Deuteronomy+14%3A16&version=DARBY |title=Deuteronomy 14 16 DARBY - the owl, and the ibis and the - Bible Gateway |last=Darby |first=John Nelson |date=1890 |access-date=17 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |title=A Field Guide to birds of The Gambia and Senegal |last1=Barlow |first1=Clive |last2=Wacher |first2=Tim |last3=Disley |first3=Tony |location=Robertsbridge |publisher=Pica Press |year=1997 |isbn=978-1-873403-32-7 }}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Threskiornis aethiopicus}}\n* [http://sabap2.adu.org.za/docs/sabap1/091.pdf Sacred Ibis] - ''[[Southern African Bird Atlas Project|The Atlas of Southern African Birds]]''\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20161126003457/http://www.europe-aliens.org/speciesFactsheet.do?speciesId=50480 Invasive Species Factsheet African sacred ibis] on DAISIE European Invasive Alien Species Gateway\n* {{VIREO|African+Sacred+Ibis}}\n\n{{Threskiornithidae}}\n{{Birds}}\n{{portalbar|Birds|Animals|Biology|Africa|Iraq|Egypt|Ancient Egypt}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q208763}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:ibis, sacred, African}}\n[[Category:Threskiornis|African sacred ibis]]\n[[Category:Birds of Africa|African sacred ibis]]\n[[Category:Birds of the Middle East]]\n[[Category:Birds of Sub-Saharan Africa|African sacred ibis]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1790|African sacred ibis]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Birds of East Africa]]\n[[Category:Birds in religion]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAfrica:Journal cites:,", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/African_sacred_ibis"}
{"title_page": "Andr\u00e9 Daina", "text_new": "{{short description|Swiss football referee}}\n{{Infobox football official\n| name = Andr\u00e9 Daina\n| image = \n| caption =\n| fullname =\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1940|7|8|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Esclepens]], [[Switzerland]]\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| role1 = Referee\n| league1 = [[Swiss Super League|Swiss Nationalliga A]]\n| years1 = 1974\u20131986\n| internationalyears1 = 1976\u20131986\n| confederation1 = [[FIFA International Referees List|FIFA]]-listed\n| internationalrole1 = Referee\n}}\n\n'''Andr\u00e9 Daina''' (born 8 July 1940) is a retired [[Switzerland|Swiss]] [[football (soccer)|football referee]]. He is known for having refereed one match in the [[1986 FIFA World Cup]] in [[Mexico]]. He also refereed one match in the [[1984 UEFA European Football Championship]] in [[France]]. He refereed a [[Liverpool vs Dinamo Bucharest, 1984 European Cup Semi-Final|European Cup semi-final]] leg in 1984 and the [[1985 European Cup Final|European Cup final]] in 1985.\n\n==References==\n* {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929120932/http://www.weltfussball.de/schiedsrichter_profil.php?id=13024 |title=Profile at weltfussball.de}} {{in lang|de}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{WorldReferee.com}}\n* {{WorldFootball.net referee}}\n* {{Soccerway referee|andre-daina/107459}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box|title=[[UEFA Champions League|European Cup Referees]] \n |before=[[1984 European Cup Final|European Cup Final 1984]]<br />{{flagicon|SWE}} [[Erik Fredriksson]] \n |after=[[1986 European Cup Final|European Cup Final 1986]]<br />{{flagicon|FRA}} [[Michel Vautrot]] \n |years='''[[1985 European Cup Final|Final 1985]]<br />{{flagicon|SUI}} Andr\u00e9 Daina'''}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{UEFA Euro 1984 referees}}\n{{Referees 1986 World Cup}}\n{{UEFA Champions League Final referees}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Daina, Andre}}\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:Swiss football referees]]\n[[Category:FIFA World Cup referees]]\n[[Category:1986 FIFA World Cup referees]]\n[[Category:Olympic football referees]]\n[[Category:Football referees at the 1980 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 1984 referees]]\n\n\n{{Switzerland-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Swiss football referee}}\n{{Infobox football official\n| name = Andr\u00e9 Daina\n| image = \n| caption =\n| fullname =\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1940|7|8|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Esclepens]], [[Switzerland]]\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| role1 = Referee\n| league1 = [[Swiss Super League|Swiss Nationalliga A]]\n| years1 = 1974\u20131986\n| internationalyears1 = 1976\u20131986\n| confederation1 = [[FIFA International Referees List|FIFA]]-listed\n| internationalrole1 = Referee\n}}\n'''Andr\u00e9 Daina''' (born 8 July 1940) is a retired [[Switzerland|Swiss]] [[football (soccer)|football referee]]. He is known for having refereed one match in the [[1986 FIFA World Cup]] in [[Mexico]]. He also refereed one match in the [[1984 UEFA European Football Championship]] in [[France]]. He refereed a [[Liverpool vs Dinamo Bucharest, 1984 European Cup Semi-Final|European Cup semi-final]] leg in 1984 and the [[1985 European Cup Final|European Cup final]] in 1985.\n\n==References==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070929120932/http://www.weltfussball.de/schiedsrichter_profil.php?id=13024 Profile]\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box|title=[[UEFA Champions League|European Cup Referees]] \n |before=[[1984 European Cup Final|European Cup Final 1984]]<br />{{flagicon|SWE}} [[Erik Fredriksson]] \n |after=[[1986 European Cup Final|European Cup Final 1986]]<br />{{flagicon|FRA}} [[Michel Vautrot]] \n |years='''[[1985 European Cup Final|Final 1985]]<br />{{flagicon|SUI}} Andr\u00e9 Daina'''}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{UEFA Euro 1984 referees}}\n{{Referees 1986 World Cup}}\n{{UEFA Champions League Final referees}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Daina, Andre}}\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:Swiss football referees]]\n[[Category:FIFA World Cup referees]]\n[[Category:1986 FIFA World Cup referees]]\n[[Category:Olympic football referees]]\n[[Category:Football referees at the 1980 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 1984 referees]]\n\n\n{{Switzerland-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "add referee link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andr%C3%A9_Daina"}
{"title_page": "Francis Landey Patton", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name        = Francis Landey Patton\n| image       = Francis Landey Patton.jpg\n| caption     =\n| order       = 12th\n| title       = [[President of Princeton University]]\n| term_start  = 1888\n| term_end    = 1902\n| predecessor = [[James McCosh]]\n| successor   = [[Woodrow Wilson]]\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1843|1|22}}\n| birth_place = [[Warwick Parish, Bermuda]]\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|1932|11|26|1843|2|22}}\n| death_place = [[Bermuda]]\n| order2       = 1st\n| title2       = [[President of Princeton Theological Seminary]]\n| term_start2  = 1902\n| term_end2    = 1913\n| predecessor2 = Position established <br> ''[[Benjamin Breckinridge Warfield]] as principal''\n| successor2   = [[J. Ross Stevenson]]\n}}\n'''Francis Landey Patton''' (January 22, 1843 \u2013 November 25, 1932) was a [[Bermuda]]n- educator, academic administrator, and [[theology|theologian]], and served as the twelfth president of [[Princeton University]].\n\n==Background, 1843\u20131871==\nPatton was born in [[Warwick Parish, Bermuda]], to a family of [[Scottish people|Scottish]] descent. He attended Warwick Academy. As a child, the family relocated to [[Canada]]. Patton received collegiate education at the [[University of Toronto]], followed by a theological education at [[Knox College, Toronto]]. He graduated from [[Princeton Theological Seminary]] in 1865; was ordained to the [[Presbyterian]] ministry in June 1865; was pastor of the [[West-Park Presbyterian Church|84th Street Presbyterian Church]], New York City, and in 1867\u20131870, of the South Church, [[Brooklyn, New York|Brooklyn]].{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=937}}\n\n==Years in Chicago, 1871\u20131881==\n\nIn 1871, Patton moved to Chicago to become minister of the [[Jefferson Park, Chicago|Jefferson Park]] Presbyterian Church, Chicago (1874\u20131881).  From 1872 to 1881, he was also a professor at [[McCormick Theological Seminary]], Chicago.  He wrote ''The Inspiration of the Scriptures'' (1869), and ''Summary of Christian Doctrine'' (1874).{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=937}}\n\nPatton was opposed to the spread of [[liberal Christianity]] in his [[Christian denomination|denomination]], the [[Presbyterian Church in the United States of America]].  As editor of a Presbyterian weekly entitled ''Interior'', he denounced the growth of liberalism in the Chicago [[Presbytery (church polity)#The Presbytery|Presbytery]].{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=937}}\n\nHe brought charges of [[heresy]] in 1874 against [[David Swing]] (a confidant of [[Abraham Lincoln]] and [[Mary Todd Lincoln]]), and was prosecuting attorney at Swing's trial.  He accused Swing of subscribing to a modern version of the [[Christian heresy|heresy]] of [[Sabellianism]] and of unduly countenancing [[Unitarianism]].  Patton lost his case and Chicago Presbytery acquitted Swing, but Patton had gained a new prominence in the denomination and this was partially responsible for his election as [[moderator of the General Assembly]] of the Presbyterian Church in 1878.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=937}}\n\n==Early years at the College of New Jersey, 1881\u20131888==\n\nIn 1881, he left Chicago and became Stuart professor \"of the relation of philosophy and science to the Christian religion\" (a chair founded for him) at [[Princeton Theological Seminary]].  He co-edited the ''Presbyterian Review'' with [[Charles Augustus Briggs|Dr Charles A Briggs]] 1880-1888. {{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=937}} At Princeton, Patton found like-minded theologians - proponents of the so-called [[Princeton theologians|Princeton theology]] - a conservative theological position that, within the Presbyterian church, was a competitor to the liberal \"Chicago school\".{{citation needed|date=January 2017}}\n\n==President of Princeton University, 1888\u20131902==\n{{unreferenced section|date=January 2017}}\nIn 1888, he was elected president of the College of New Jersey (which in 1896 became [[Princeton University]]), replacing out-going president [[James McCosh]].  His appointment was criticized by some alumni, who noted that Patton was not an American citizen, while some feared he would harangue students with [[John Knox]]-style sermons.  He won over a large number of the alumni with a speech given in New York in 1888, in which he remarked \"I am not prepared to say that it is better to have gone and loafed than never to have gone at all, but I do believe in the ''genius loci''; and I sympathize with Sir [[Joshua Reynolds]] when he says, 'that there is around every seminary of learning, an atmosphere of floating knowledge where every one can imbibe something peculiar to his own original conceptions.'\"  The phrase \"Better to have gone and loafed than never to have gone at all\" was often quoted by proponents of the so-called \"Gentleman's C.\"  Patton was a popular president, and his class in [[Ethics]] was one of the most popular on campus.\n\nDuring Patton's time as university president, Princeton more than doubled in size, growing from 600 students in 1888 to 1,300 students in 1902.  Patton appointed many prominent Princeton professors, including: [[Woodrow Wilson]], [[Bliss Perry]], [[John Grier Hibben]], [[Henry van Dyke]], [[Paul Van Dyke]], and [[Howard C. Warren]].  Patton announced the name change from \"the College of New Jersey\" to \"Princeton University\" in the midst of the ceremonies celebrating the College's [[Sesquicentennial]] in 1896.  Although Princeton founded a [[graduate school]] while Patton was president (in 1900), Patton played little role in the foundation of the graduate school.\n\nIn 1891, Dr [[Charles Augustus Briggs|Charles A. Briggs]], Patton's former co-editor at the ''Presbyterian Review'' was appointed the first-ever Professor of [[Biblical Theology]] by [[Union Theological Seminary (New York City)|Union Theological Seminary]].  In his inaugural lecture, Briggs praised [[higher criticism]], a component of liberal Christianity, and argued that the Scriptures as a whole are riddled with errors and that the doctrine of [[biblical inerrancy]] taught at Princeton Theological Seminary \"is a ghost of modern evangelicalism to frighten children.\"  Patton was outraged by this lecture and moved that the [[Presbyterian polity#The general assembly|General Assembly]], which had the authority to veto all appointments of professors of theology at Presbyterian [[seminaries]], should exercise this power and remove Briggs from the Union faculty.  On Patton's urging, the General Assembly voted to remove Briggs from his position.  The faculty of Union Theological Seminary voted to withdraw from the denomination rather than remove Briggs from his chair in order to defend the institution's [[academic freedom]].\n\nAlthough Patton was popular as an academic, a theologian, and a public speaker, he was not a gifted [[Academic administration|administrator]].  In the 1890s, clerical control over Princeton waned, and more and more businessmen and lawyers were elected as [[Trustees of Princeton University]].  Dissatisfied with Patton's management of the university, in 1902, the Trustees voted to replace Patton as president, naming [[Woodrow Wilson]] as his successor.\n\n==President of Princeton Theological Seminary, 1902\u20131913==\n\nPatton thus became president of [[Princeton Theological Seminary]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ptsem.edu/about/history |title=History of Princeton Theological Seminary |publisher=Princeton Theological Seminary |accessdate=27 August 2017}}</ref> In that capacity, he opposed [[Henry van Dyke]]'s proposal to revise the [[Westminster Confession of Faith]].{{citation needed|date=January 2017}}\n\n==Later years, 1913\u20131932==\n\nPatton retired in 1913, with a pension of $3,000 a year. He returned to his native [[Bermuda]].  He continued to speak out on controversies within the Presbyterian church, and during the [[Fundamentalist\u2013Modernist Controversy]], he supported the Fundamentalist side.  He published a book entitled ''Fundamental Christianity'', in which he wrote \"We cannot change Christianity.  We may reject it if we please, but its meaning is plain\".{{citation needed|date=January 2017}}\n\nHe died in Bermuda on November 25, 1932.{{citation needed|date=January 2017}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* {{EB1911|wstitle=Patton, Francis Landey |volume=20 |pages=937\u2013938}}\n\n==External links==\n{{NIE Poster|year=1905|Patton, Francis Landey|Francis Landey Patton}}\n* {{Gutenberg author | id=Patton,+Francis+Landey | name=Francis Landey Patton}}\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Francis Landey Patton}}\n*[http://etcweb.princeton.edu/CampusWWW/Companion/patton_francis.html Princeton biography]\n*[https://archive.org/details/addressesatindu00pattgoog Addresses commemorating Patton's appointment at McCormick Theological Seminary, 1873]\n*[http://quod.lib.umich.edu/cgi/t/text/text-idx?c=moa;idno=AGU9808 ''The world's edition of the great Presbyterian conflict: Patton vs. Swing.: Both sides of the question'', 1874]\n*[http://quod.lib.umich.edu/cgi/t/text/text-idx?c=moa;idno=AJK3103 ''Presbyterian Principles'' by Francis L. Patton, 1875]\n*[http://scdc.library.ptsem.edu/mets/mets.aspx?src=PresReviewIndex.txt ''The Presbyterian Review'', 1880-89, made available by Princeton Theological Seminary]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-rel}}\n{{succession box\n| before = The Rev. James Eells\n| title  = [[List of Moderators of the General Assembly of the Presbyterian Church in the United States of America|Moderator of the 90th General Assembly of the Presbyterian Church in the United States of America]]\n| years  = 1878\u20131879\n| after  = The Rev. [[Henry Harris Jessup]]\n}}\n{{s-aca}}\n{{s-bef |before=[[James McCosh]]}}\n{{s-ttl |title=[[President of Princeton University|President of the College of New Jersey]]|years=1888-1896}}\n{{s-non |reason=Name of institution changed}}\n{{s-new|reason=Name of institution changed}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[President of Princeton University]]|years=1896-1902}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Woodrow Wilson]]}}\n{{s-bef | before = [[Benjamin Breckinridge Warfield]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title  = President of [[Princeton Theological Seminary]] | years = 1902-1913}}\n{{s-aft | after  = [[J. Ross Stevenson]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Princeton presidents}}\n{{Princeton Theological Seminary|state=expanded}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Patton, Francis}}\n[[Category:American educational theorists]]\n[[Category:1843 births]]\n[[Category:1932 deaths]]\n[[Category:Bermudian Presbyterians]]\n[[Category:Princeton Theological Seminary alumni]]\n[[Category:19th-century Presbyterian ministers]]\n[[Category:Presidents of Calvinist and Reformed seminaries]]\n[[Category:Presbyterian Church in the United States of America ministers]]\n[[Category:British emigrants to the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name        = Francis Landey Patton\n| image       = Francis Landey Patton.jpg\n| caption     =\n| order       = 12th\n| title       = [[President of Princeton University]]\n| term_start  = 1888\n| term_end    = 1902\n| predecessor = [[James McCosh]]\n| successor   = [[Woodrow Wilson]]\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1843|1|22}}\n| birth_place = [[Warwick Parish, Bermuda]]\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|1932|11|26|1843|2|22}}\n| death_place = [[Bermuda]]\n| order2       = 1st\n| title2       = [[President of Princeton Theological Seminary]]\n| term_start2  = 1902\n| term_end2    = 1913\n| predecessor2 = Position established <br> ''[[Benjamin Breckinridge Warfield]] as principal''\n| successor2   = [[J. Ross Stevenson]]\n}}\n'''Francis Landey Patton''' (January 22, 1843 \u2013 November 25, 1932) was a [[Bermuda]]n- educator, academic administrator, and [[theology|theologian]], and served as the twelfth president of [[Princeton University]].\n\n==Background, 1843\u20131871==\nPatton was born in [[Warwick Parish, Bermuda]], to a family of [[Scottish]] descent. He attended Warwick Academy. As a child, the family relocated to [[Canada]]. Patton received collegiate education at the [[University of Toronto]], followed by a theological education at [[Knox College, Toronto]]. He graduated from [[Princeton Theological Seminary]] in 1865; was ordained to the [[Presbyterian]] ministry in June 1865; was pastor of the [[West-Park Presbyterian Church|84th Street Presbyterian Church]], New York City, and in 1867\u20131870, of the South Church, [[Brooklyn, New York|Brooklyn]].{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=937}}\n\n==Years in Chicago, 1871\u20131881==\n\nIn 1871, Patton moved to Chicago to become minister of the [[Jefferson Park, Chicago|Jefferson Park]] Presbyterian Church, Chicago (1874\u20131881).  From 1872 to 1881, he was also a professor at [[McCormick Theological Seminary]], Chicago.  He wrote ''The Inspiration of the Scriptures'' (1869), and ''Summary of Christian Doctrine'' (1874).{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=937}}\n\nPatton was opposed to the spread of [[liberal Christianity]] in his [[Christian denomination|denomination]], the [[Presbyterian Church in the United States of America]].  As editor of a Presbyterian weekly entitled ''Interior'', he denounced the growth of liberalism in the Chicago [[Presbytery (church polity)#The Presbytery|Presbytery]].{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=937}}\n\nHe brought charges of [[heresy]] in 1874 against [[David Swing]] (a confidant of [[Abraham Lincoln]] and [[Mary Todd Lincoln]]), and was prosecuting attorney at Swing's trial.  He accused Swing of subscribing to a modern version of the [[Christian heresy|heresy]] of [[Sabellianism]] and of unduly countenancing [[Unitarianism]].  Patton lost his case and Chicago Presbytery acquitted Swing, but Patton had gained a new prominence in the denomination and this was partially responsible for his election as [[moderator of the General Assembly]] of the Presbyterian Church in 1878.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=937}}\n\n==Early years at the College of New Jersey, 1881\u20131888==\n\nIn 1881, he left Chicago and became Stuart professor \"of the relation of philosophy and science to the Christian religion\" (a chair founded for him) at [[Princeton Theological Seminary]].  He co-edited the ''Presbyterian Review'' with [[Charles Augustus Briggs|Dr Charles A Briggs]] 1880-1888. {{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=937}} At Princeton, Patton found like-minded theologians - proponents of the so-called [[Princeton theologians|Princeton theology]] - a conservative theological position that, within the Presbyterian church, was a competitor to the liberal \"Chicago school\".{{citation needed|date=January 2017}}\n\n==President of Princeton University, 1888\u20131902==\n{{unreferenced section|date=January 2017}}\nIn 1888, he was elected president of the College of New Jersey (which in 1896 became [[Princeton University]]), replacing out-going president [[James McCosh]].  His appointment was criticized by some alumni, who noted that Patton was not an American citizen, while some feared he would harangue students with [[John Knox]]-style sermons.  He won over a large number of the alumni with a speech given in New York in 1888, in which he remarked \"I am not prepared to say that it is better to have gone and loafed than never to have gone at all, but I do believe in the ''genius loci''; and I sympathize with Sir [[Joshua Reynolds]] when he says, 'that there is around every seminary of learning, an atmosphere of floating knowledge where every one can imbibe something peculiar to his own original conceptions.'\"  The phrase \"Better to have gone and loafed than never to have gone at all\" was often quoted by proponents of the so-called \"Gentleman's C.\"  Patton was a popular president, and his class in [[Ethics]] was one of the most popular on campus.\n\nDuring Patton's time as university president, Princeton more than doubled in size, growing from 600 students in 1888 to 1,300 students in 1902.  Patton appointed many prominent Princeton professors, including: [[Woodrow Wilson]], [[Bliss Perry]], [[John Grier Hibben]], [[Henry van Dyke]], [[Paul Van Dyke]], and [[Howard C. Warren]].  Patton announced the name change from \"the College of New Jersey\" to \"Princeton University\" in the midst of the ceremonies celebrating the College's [[Sesquicentennial]] in 1896.  Although Princeton founded a [[graduate school]] while Patton was president (in 1900), Patton played little role in the foundation of the graduate school.\n\nIn 1891, Dr [[Charles Augustus Briggs|Charles A. Briggs]], Patton's former co-editor at the ''Presbyterian Review'' was appointed the first-ever Professor of [[Biblical Theology]] by [[Union Theological Seminary (New York City)|Union Theological Seminary]].  In his inaugural lecture, Briggs praised [[higher criticism]], a component of liberal Christianity, and argued that the Scriptures as a whole are riddled with errors and that the doctrine of [[biblical inerrancy]] taught at Princeton Theological Seminary \"is a ghost of modern evangelicalism to frighten children.\"  Patton was outraged by this lecture and moved that the [[Presbyterian polity#The general assembly|General Assembly]], which had the authority to veto all appointments of professors of theology at Presbyterian [[seminaries]], should exercise this power and remove Briggs from the Union faculty.  On Patton's urging, the General Assembly voted to remove Briggs from his position.  The faculty of Union Theological Seminary voted to withdraw from the denomination rather than remove Briggs from his chair in order to defend the institution's [[academic freedom]].\n\nAlthough Patton was popular as an academic, a theologian, and a public speaker, he was not a gifted [[Academic administration|administrator]].  In the 1890s, clerical control over Princeton waned, and more and more businessmen and lawyers were elected as [[Trustees of Princeton University]].  Dissatisfied with Patton's management of the university, in 1902, the Trustees voted to replace Patton as president, naming [[Woodrow Wilson]] as his successor.\n\n==President of Princeton Theological Seminary, 1902\u20131913==\n\nPatton thus became president of [[Princeton Theological Seminary]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ptsem.edu/about/history |title=History of Princeton Theological Seminary |publisher=Princeton Theological Seminary |accessdate=27 August 2017}}</ref> In that capacity, he opposed [[Henry van Dyke]]'s proposal to revise the [[Westminster Confession of Faith]].{{citation needed|date=January 2017}}\n\n==Later years, 1913\u20131932==\n\nPatton retired in 1913, with a pension of $3,000 a year. He returned to his native [[Bermuda]].  He continued to speak out on controversies within the Presbyterian church, and during the [[Fundamentalist\u2013Modernist Controversy]], he supported the Fundamentalist side.  He published a book entitled ''Fundamental Christianity'', in which he wrote \"We cannot change Christianity.  We may reject it if we please, but its meaning is plain\".{{citation needed|date=January 2017}}\n\nHe died in Bermuda on November 25, 1932.{{citation needed|date=January 2017}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* {{EB1911|wstitle=Patton, Francis Landey |volume=20 |pages=937\u2013938}}\n\n==External links==\n{{NIE Poster|year=1905|Patton, Francis Landey|Francis Landey Patton}}\n* {{Gutenberg author | id=Patton,+Francis+Landey | name=Francis Landey Patton}}\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Francis Landey Patton}}\n*[http://etcweb.princeton.edu/CampusWWW/Companion/patton_francis.html Princeton biography]\n*[https://archive.org/details/addressesatindu00pattgoog Addresses commemorating Patton's appointment at McCormick Theological Seminary, 1873]\n*[http://quod.lib.umich.edu/cgi/t/text/text-idx?c=moa;idno=AGU9808 ''The world's edition of the great Presbyterian conflict: Patton vs. Swing.: Both sides of the question'', 1874]\n*[http://quod.lib.umich.edu/cgi/t/text/text-idx?c=moa;idno=AJK3103 ''Presbyterian Principles'' by Francis L. Patton, 1875]\n*[http://scdc.library.ptsem.edu/mets/mets.aspx?src=PresReviewIndex.txt ''The Presbyterian Review'', 1880-89, made available by Princeton Theological Seminary]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-rel}}\n{{succession box\n| before = The Rev. James Eells\n| title  = [[List of Moderators of the General Assembly of the Presbyterian Church in the United States of America|Moderator of the 90th General Assembly of the Presbyterian Church in the United States of America]]\n| years  = 1878\u20131879\n| after  = The Rev. [[Henry Harris Jessup]]\n}}\n{{s-aca}}\n{{s-bef |before=[[James McCosh]]}}\n{{s-ttl |title=[[President of Princeton University|President of the College of New Jersey]]|years=1888-1896}}\n{{s-non |reason=Name of institution changed}}\n{{s-new|reason=Name of institution changed}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[President of Princeton University]]|years=1896-1902}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Woodrow Wilson]]}}\n{{s-bef | before = [[Benjamin Breckinridge Warfield]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title  = President of [[Princeton Theological Seminary]] | years = 1902-1913}}\n{{s-aft | after  = [[J. Ross Stevenson]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Princeton presidents}}\n{{Princeton Theological Seminary|state=expanded}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Patton, Francis}}\n[[Category:American educational theorists]]\n[[Category:1843 births]]\n[[Category:1932 deaths]]\n[[Category:Bermudian Presbyterians]]\n[[Category:Princeton Theological Seminary alumni]]\n[[Category:19th-century Presbyterian ministers]]\n[[Category:Presidents of Calvinist and Reformed seminaries]]\n[[Category:Presbyterian Church in the United States of America ministers]]\n[[Category:British emigrants to the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toScottish(link changed toScottish people) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Francis_Landey_Patton"}
{"title_page": "Dan Scavino", "text_new": "{{short description|Assistant to U.S. president Donald Trump and cousin of Kevin Lanning (hip hop artist)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Dan Scavino\n| image = Dan Scavino by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| office = [[Executive Office of the President|White House Director of Social Media]]\n| president = [[Donald Trump]]\n| term_start = January 22, 2017\n| term_end = \n| predecessor = Position established\n| successor = \n| birth_name = Daniel Scavino Jr.\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1976|01|15}}\n| birth_place = [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| education = [[State University of New York at Plattsburgh|State University of New York, Plattsburgh]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])\n}}\n\n'''Daniel Scavino Jr.''' (born January 15, 1976<ref>{{cite tweet|user=PressSec|author-link=Sarah Sanders|number=1085032821046038528|date=January 15, 2019|title=Happy Birthday @Scavino45 one of my favorite people at the WH and one of the most talented people I know.}}</ref>) is an American political advisor, currently serving as the White House Director of Social Media and [[Assistant to the President]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2016/12/22/trump-scavino-white-house-social-media-director/95759880/|title=Trump names Dan Scavino White House social media director|publisher=|accessdate=February 22, 2018}}</ref> His appointment was announced on December 22, 2016.<ref name=\"pressposts\">{{cite web| title=Trump picks Sean Spicer as White House press secretary, Jason Miller as communications director|url=http://money.cnn.com/2016/12/22/media/sean-spicer-jason-miller-white-house-press-secretary-donald-trump/index.html?adkey=bn|date=December 22, 2016|publisher=[[CNN Money]]|accessdate=December 22, 2016}}</ref> Scavino previously worked as the general manager of [[Trump National Golf Club Westchester]], and the director of social media for the [[Donald Trump 2016 presidential campaign]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://politi.co/2JJC2aE|title='Get Scavino in here': Trump's Twitter guru is the ultimate insider|last=Restuccia|first=Rew|last2=Lippman|first2=Daniel|website=POLITICO|language=en|access-date=2019-11-19|last3=Johnson|first3=Eliana}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nScavino was born in [[New York (state)|New York]], the son of Italian immigrants. He was raised in the [[New York City]] area.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wetheitalians.com/single_post/daniel-scavino-jr-turns-caddie-white-house-social-media-director|title=Daniel Scavino Jr. turns from caddie into White House social media director|website=We the Italians|access-date=2019-11-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/dan-scavino-bio-trump-golf-caddie-turned-social-media-director-2018-4|title=Trump's social media director Dan Scavino is the staffer who's been around the longest \u2014and he started as Trump's caddie|last=Panetta|first=Michal Kranz, Pat Ralph, Grace|website=Business Insider|access-date=2019-11-14}}</ref> In 1992, Scavino was selected as a [[caddie]] for Trump's golf party at [[Briar Hall Country Club]] (later renamed Trump National Golf Club Westchester). He graduated from the [[State University of New York at Plattsburgh]] in 1998 with a B.A. in Communications. \n\n== Career ==\nScavino worked for a few years at [[Coca-Cola]] and [[Galderma]] before being promoted to general manager of Trump National Golf Club Westchester.<ref name=\"CNN\">{{cite web|last=Moody|first=Chris|date=July 5, 2016|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2016/04/29/politics/donald-trump-tweets-daniel-scavino/ |title=How a golf caddie became Trump's campaign confidant}}</ref>\n\n====Trump presidential campaign====\nScavino was involved with Donald Trump's presidential campaign since it began in June 2015. In February 2016, Trump appointed Scavino as the campaign's director of social media. Over July 4, 2016 weekend, controversy arose when [[Trump's Twitter]] account posted an image selected by Scavino of [[Hillary Clinton]] with a text in the shape of a [[Star of David]] calling her the \"Most Corrupt Candidate Ever.\" The image had originally appeared on an [[anti-Semitic]], white supremacist message board. Trump's team defended its use saying that the star was a \"sheriff's badge\", before eventually deleting it and posting a new picture with a circle replacing the star.<ref name=\"CNN\" />\n\n====White House====\n[[File:President Trump at Davos (49419977697).jpg|thumb|Donald Trump, Scavino (second from left), [[Ivanka Trump]], and World Economic Forum Executive Chairman [[Klaus Schwab]] meet in [[Davos, Switzerland]] in 2020]]\nOn December 22, 2016, Scavino was announced to be White House Director of Social Media under President Donald Trump.<ref name=\"pressposts\" />\n\nIn April 2017, ethics attorney [[Richard Painter]] accused Scavino of violating the [[Hatch Act of 1939]] (which bars executive branch employees from engaging in electoral activities) after Scavino, from his personal Twitter account, had called for defeating Congressman [[Justin Amash]].<ref name=politico> {{cite news |last=SAMUELSOHN  |first=Darren |date=April 1, 2017 |title=Trump aide accused of Hatch Act violation after urging Amash primary challenge |url=http://www.politico.com/story/2017/04/dan-scavino-justin-amash-liability-trump-freedom-caucus-236780 |work=[[Politico]] |access-date=April 1, 2017 }}</ref> The [[United States Office of Special Counsel]] then informed Scavino that his tweet had indeed violated the Hatch Act and warned that future violations \"could result in further action.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-politics/wp/2017/06/09/white-house-social-media-director-dan-scavino-violated-hatch-act-with-tweet-targeting-gop-congressman/|title=White House social-media director Dan Scavino violated Hatch Act with tweet targeting GOP congressman|first=Matea|last=Gold|date=June 9, 2017|publisher=|accessdate=February 22, 2018|via=washingtonpost.com}}</ref> In May 2019, ''[[Politico]]'' reported that Scavino frequented the [[R/The Donald]] subreddit.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Restuccia |first1=Andrew |last2=Lippman |first2=Daniel |last3=Johnson |first3=Eliana |title='Get Scavino in here': Trump's Twitter guru is the ultimate insider |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/05/16/trump-scavino-1327921 |accessdate=May 17, 2019 |work=POLITICO |date=May 16, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn June 18, 2019, [[USA Today|''USA Today'']] released an article stating that Scavino is the one who writes Trump's tweets.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2019/06/18/donald-trump-twitter-president-white-house-dan-scavino-golf-course-covfefe/1495205001/|title=He writes Trump's tweets and has been with Trump's campaign since day one|website=USA TODAY|language=en|access-date=2019-06-19}}</ref>\n\nOn April 13, 2020 President Trump played a video during a televised briefing session to the press on the Corona virus pandemic.  The video was widely referred to as a election campaign video <ref>https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52276004</ref>.  In the following question and answer session one journalist asked who produced the video.  President Trump replied \"this was done by Dan and a group of people\" <ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LZ_l0z2LMws</ref>. The Dan mentioned is Dan Scavino. \nMSNBC and CNN cut away from the briefing session when the video played.  <ref>https://thehill.com/homenews/media/492612-cnn-cuts-away-from-propaganda-briefing-as-trump-plays-video-hitting-press</ref>\n\nTo date, Scavino is the longest-serving aide in the [[Trump Administration]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/16/magazine/dan-scavino-the-secretary-of-offense.html|title=The Man Behind the President's Tweets|last=Draper|first=Robert|access-date=November 10, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nDaniel and Jennifer Scavino were married in 2000; they have two children. His wife filed for divorce in January 2018.<ref name=\"Huffington Post\">{{cite web|last=Ali|first=Yashar|date=March 18, 2018|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/trump-aide-dan-scavino-divorce_us_5aaef507e4b0c33361b1bdcb/ |title=Wife Of Top Trump Aide Dan Scavino Files For Divorce}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{C-SPAN|Dan Scavino}}\n\n{{Trump Executive Office}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Scavino, Dan}}\n[[Category:1976 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Trump administration personnel]]\n[[Category:State University of New York at Plattsburgh alumni]]\n[[Category:Social media]]\n[[Category:American people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Republicans]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Assistant to U.S. president Donald Trump and cousin of Kevin Lanning (hip hop artist)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Dan Scavino\n| image = Dan Scavino by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| office = [[Executive Office of the President|White House Director of Social Media]]\n| president = [[Donald Trump]]\n| term_start = January 22, 2017\n| term_end = \n| predecessor = Position established\n| successor = \n| birth_name = Daniel Scavino Jr.\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1976|01|15}}\n| birth_place = [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| education = [[State University of New York at Plattsburgh|State University of New York, Plattsburgh]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])\n}}\n\n'''Daniel Scavino Jr.''' (born January 15, 1976<ref>{{cite tweet|user=PressSec|author-link=Sarah Sanders|number=1085032821046038528|date=January 15, 2019|title=Happy Birthday @Scavino45 one of my favorite people at the WH and one of the most talented people I know.}}</ref>) is an American political advisor, currently serving as the White House Director of Social Media and [[Assistant to the President]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2016/12/22/trump-scavino-white-house-social-media-director/95759880/|title=Trump names Dan Scavino White House social media director|publisher=|accessdate=February 22, 2018}}</ref> His appointment was announced on December 22, 2016.<ref name=\"pressposts\">{{cite web| title=Trump picks Sean Spicer as White House press secretary, Jason Miller as communications director|url=http://money.cnn.com/2016/12/22/media/sean-spicer-jason-miller-white-house-press-secretary-donald-trump/index.html?adkey=bn|date=December 22, 2016|publisher=[[CNN Money]]|accessdate=December 22, 2016}}</ref> Scavino previously worked as the general manager of [[Trump National Golf Club Westchester]], and the director of social media for the [[Donald Trump 2016 presidential campaign]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://politi.co/2JJC2aE|title='Get Scavino in here': Trump's Twitter guru is the ultimate insider|last=Restuccia|first=Rew|last2=Lippman|first2=Daniel|website=POLITICO|language=en|access-date=2019-11-19|last3=Johnson|first3=Eliana}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nScavino was born in [[New York (state)|New York]], the son of Italian immigrants. He was raised in the [[New York City]] area.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wetheitalians.com/single_post/daniel-scavino-jr-turns-caddie-white-house-social-media-director|title=Daniel Scavino Jr. turns from caddie into White House social media director|website=We the Italians|access-date=2019-11-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/dan-scavino-bio-trump-golf-caddie-turned-social-media-director-2018-4|title=Trump's social media director Dan Scavino is the staffer who's been around the longest \u2014and he started as Trump's caddie|last=Panetta|first=Michal Kranz, Pat Ralph, Grace|website=Business Insider|access-date=2019-11-14}}</ref> In 1992, Scavino was selected as a [[caddie]] for Trump's golf party at [[Briar Hall Country Club]] (later renamed Trump National Golf Club Westchester). He graduated from the [[State University of New York at Plattsburgh]] in 1998 with a B.A. in Communications. \n\n== Career ==\nScavino worked for a few years at [[Coca-Cola]] and [[Galderma]] before being promoted to general manager of Trump National Golf Club Westchester.<ref name=\"CNN\">{{cite web|last=Moody|first=Chris|date=July 5, 2016|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2016/04/29/politics/donald-trump-tweets-daniel-scavino/ |title=How a golf caddie became Trump's campaign confidant}}</ref>\n\n====Trump presidential campaign====\nScavino was involved with Donald Trump's presidential campaign since it began in June 2015. In February 2016, Trump appointed Scavino as the campaign's director of social media. Over July 4, 2016 weekend, controversy arose when [[Trump's Twitter]] account posted an image selected by Scavino of [[Hillary Clinton]] with a text in the shape of a [[Star of David]] calling her the \"Most Corrupt Candidate Ever.\" The image had originally appeared on an [[anti-Semitic]], white supremacist message board. Trump's team defended its use saying that the star was a \"sheriff's badge\", before eventually deleting it and posting a new picture with a circle replacing the star.<ref name=\"CNN\" />\n\n====White House====\n[[File:President Trump at Davos (49419977697).jpg|thumb|Donald Trump, Scavino (second from left), [[Ivanka Trump]], and World Economic Forum Executive Chairman [[Klaus Schwab]] meet in [[Davos, Switzerland]] in 2020]]\nOn December 22, 2016, Scavino was announced to be White House Director of Social Media under President Donald Trump.<ref name=\"pressposts\" />\n\nIn April 2017, ethics attorney [[Richard Painter]] accused Scavino of violating the [[Hatch Act of 1939]] (which bars executive branch employees from engaging in electoral activities) after Scavino, from his personal Twitter account, had called for defeating Congressman [[Justin Amash]].<ref name=politico> {{cite news |last=SAMUELSOHN  |first=Darren |date=April 1, 2017 |title=Trump aide accused of Hatch Act violation after urging Amash primary challenge |url=http://www.politico.com/story/2017/04/dan-scavino-justin-amash-liability-trump-freedom-caucus-236780 |work=[[Politico]] |access-date=April 1, 2017 }}</ref> The [[United States Office of Special Counsel]] then informed Scavino that his tweet had indeed violated the Hatch Act and warned that future violations \"could result in further action.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-politics/wp/2017/06/09/white-house-social-media-director-dan-scavino-violated-hatch-act-with-tweet-targeting-gop-congressman/|title=White House social-media director Dan Scavino violated Hatch Act with tweet targeting GOP congressman|first=Matea|last=Gold|date=June 9, 2017|publisher=|accessdate=February 22, 2018|via=washingtonpost.com}}</ref> In May 2019, ''[[Politico]]'' reported that Scavino frequented the [[R/The Donald]] subreddit.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Restuccia |first1=Andrew |last2=Lippman |first2=Daniel |last3=Johnson |first3=Eliana |title='Get Scavino in here': Trump's Twitter guru is the ultimate insider |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/05/16/trump-scavino-1327921 |accessdate=May 17, 2019 |work=POLITICO |date=May 16, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn June 18, 2019, [[USA Today|''USA Today'']] released an article stating that Scavino is the one who writes Trump's tweets.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2019/06/18/donald-trump-twitter-president-white-house-dan-scavino-golf-course-covfefe/1495205001/|title=He writes Trump's tweets and has been with Trump's campaign since day one|website=USA TODAY|language=en|access-date=2019-06-19}}</ref>\n\nOn April 13, 2020 President Trump played a video during a televised briefing session to the press on the Corona virus pandemic.  The video was widely referred to as a election campaign video <ref>https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52276004</ref>.  In the following question and answer session one journalist asked who produced the video.  President Trump replied \"this was done by Dan and a group of people\" <ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LZ_l0z2LMws</ref>. The Dan mentioned is Dan Scavino. \nMSNBC and CNN stoped cut away from the briefing session when the video played.  <ref>https://thehill.com/homenews/media/492612-cnn-cuts-away-from-propaganda-briefing-as-trump-plays-video-hitting-press</ref>\n\nTo date, Scavino is the longest-serving aide in the [[Trump Administration]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/16/magazine/dan-scavino-the-secretary-of-offense.html|title=The Man Behind the President's Tweets|last=Draper|first=Robert|access-date=November 10, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nDaniel and Jennifer Scavino were married in 2000; they have two children. His wife filed for divorce in January 2018.<ref name=\"Huffington Post\">{{cite web|last=Ali|first=Yashar|date=March 18, 2018|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/trump-aide-dan-scavino-divorce_us_5aaef507e4b0c33361b1bdcb/ |title=Wife Of Top Trump Aide Dan Scavino Files For Divorce}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{C-SPAN|Dan Scavino}}\n\n{{Trump Executive Office}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Scavino, Dan}}\n[[Category:1976 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Trump administration personnel]]\n[[Category:State University of New York at Plattsburgh alumni]]\n[[Category:Social media]]\n[[Category:American people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Republicans]]\n", "name_user": "Slygopher1", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eWhite House:spelling", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dan_Scavino"}
{"title_page": "John de Cresswell", "text_new": "{{short description|14th century English nobleman}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox noble|type\n| name              = John de Cresswell\n| title             = \n| image             =\n| caption           =\n| alt               = \n| CoA               = \n| more              = no\n| succession        = \n| reign             = \n| reign-type        = \n| predecessor       = \n| successor         = \n| suc-type          = \n| spouse            = \n| spouse-type       = \n| issue             = \n| issue-link        = \n| issue-pipe        = \n| full name         = \n| native_name       = \n| styles            = \n| titles            = \n| noble family      = \n| house-type        = \n| father            = \n| mother            = \n| birth_name        = \n| birth_date        = <!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} -->\n| birth_place       = \n| christening_date  = \n| christening_place = \n| death_date        = \n| death_place       = \n| burial_date       = \n| burial_place      = \n| religion          = \n| occupation        = \n| memorials         = \n| module            = \n}}\n\n'''John de Cresswell''' was an English soldier and nobleman.\n\n==Biography==\nJohn was a younger son of Alexander de Cresswell.{{sfn|Burke|1836|p=290}} He was engaged in the [[Hundred Years' War]] and was Captain of Bordeaux Castle. \n\nAfter the crushing English [[Battle of Pontvallain|defeat at  Pontvallain]], Cresswell was in charge of an English garrison at [[Saint-Maur-sur-Loire|Saint-Maur]]. A French army, led by [[Bertrand du Guesclin]] approached and after on assault was defeated negotiations arranged the English release on payment for the town.{{sfn|Sumption|2009|p=92}}\n\nDuring an expedition in Scotland he was taken prisoner, along with Lord Greystoke in 1380. [[Richard II of England]] organised his release. He is known to have had two sons John and George.\n\n==Citations==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* Burke, John. '' A Genealogical and Heraldic History of the Commoners of Great Britain and Ireland Enjoying Territorial Possessions Or High Official Rank: But Uninvested with Heritable Honours '', Volume 2. Colburn, 1836.\n* {{Cite book|title=The Hundred Years' War: Divided Houses|last=Sumption|first=J.|publisher=Faber & Faber|year=2009|edition=paperback|isbn=978-0571240128|volume=III|location=London|ref=harv}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cresswell, John de}}\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n[[Category:Year of death unknown]]\n[[Category:14th-century English people]]\n[[Category:English soldiers]]\n[[Category:14th-century military history of the Kingdom of England]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|14th century English nobleman}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox noble|type\n| name              = John de Cresswell\n| title             = \n| image             =\n| caption           =\n| alt               = \n| CoA               = \n| more              = no \n| succession        = \n| reign             = \n| reign-type        = \n| predecessor       = \n| successor         = \n| suc-type          = \n| spouse            =  \n| spouse-type       = \n| issue             = \n| issue-link        = \n| issue-pipe        = \n| full name         = \n| native_name       = \n| styles            = \n| titles            = \n| noble family      = \n| house-type        = \n| father            = \n| mother            = \n| birth_name        = \n| birth_date        = <!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} -->\n| birth_place       = \n| christening_date  = \n| christening_place = \n| death_date        = \n| death_place       = \n| burial_date       = \n| burial_place      = \n| religion          = \n| occupation        = \n| memorials         = \n| website           = <!-- {{{URL|example.com}} -->\n| module            = \n}}\n\n'''John de Cresswell''' was an English soldier and nobleman.\n\n==Biography==\nJohn was a younger son of Alexander de Cresswell.{{sfn|Burke|1836|p=290}} He was engaged in the [[Hundred Years\u2019 War]] and was Captain of Bordeaux Castle. \n\nAfter the crushing English [[Battle of Pontvallain|defeat at  Pontvallain]], Cresswell was in charge of an English garrison at [[Saint-Maur-sur-Loire|Saint-Maur]]. A French army, led by [[Bertrand du Guesclin]] approached and after on assault was defeated negotiations arranged the English release on payment for the town.{{sfn|Sumption|2009|p=92}}\n\nDuring an expedition in Scotland he was taken prisoner, along with Lord Greystoke in 1380. [[Richard II of England]] organised his release. He is known to have had two sons John and George.\n\n==Citations==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*Burke, John. '' A Genealogical and Heraldic History of the Commoners of Great Britain and Ireland Enjoying Territorial Possessions Or High Official Rank: But Uninvested with Heritable Honours '', Volume 2. Colburn, 1836.\n*{{Cite book|title=The Hundred Years' War: Divided Houses|last=Sumption|first=J.|publisher=Faber & Faber|year=2009|edition=paperback|isbn=978-0571240128|volume=III|location=London|ref=harv}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cresswell, John de}}\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n[[Category:Year of death unknown]]\n[[Category:14th-century English people]]\n[[Category:English soldiers]]\n[[Category:14th-century military history of the Kingdom of England]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing]]\n", "name_user": "Wiki13565", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_de_Cresswell"}
{"title_page": "Elsevier", "text_new": "{{short description|Dutch publishing and analytics company}}\n{{other uses}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2016}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Elsevier\n| logo = \n| logo_caption = \n| image = Elsevier logo 2019.svg\n| image_size = 200px\n| image_caption = \n| trading_name = <!-- d/b/a/, doing business as - if different from legal name above -->\n| native_name = <!-- Company's name in home country language -->\n| native_name_lang = <!-- Use ISO 639-1 code, e.g. \"fr\" for French. If there is more than one native name, in different languages, enter those names using {{tl|lang}}, instead. -->\n| romanized_name = \n| former_name = \n| type = \n| traded_as = \n| industry = Publishing\n| genre = <!-- Only used with media and publishing companies -->\n| fate = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| foundation = {{start date and age|df=yes|1880}}\n| founder = \n| defunct = <!-- {{End date|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| location_city = [[Amsterdam]], [[Netherlands]]\n| location_country = \n| locations = <!-- Number of locations, stores, offices, etc. -->\n| area_served = \n| key_people = \n| products = \n| brands = \n| production = \n| services = \n| revenue = \u00a32.54 billion (2018)<ref name=\"RELX 2018 Report\"/>\n| operating_income = \n| net_income = <!-- Removed due to lack of verifiability -->\n| aum = <!-- Only used with financial services companies -->\n| assets = \n| equity = \n| owner = \n| num_employees = \n| parent = [[RELX]]\n| divisions = \n| subsid = \n| website = {{URL|https://www.elsevier.com/}}\n| footnotes = \n| intl = \n}}\n\n'''Elsevier''' ({{IPA-nl|\u02c8\u025blz\u0259vi\u02d0r|lang}}) is a [[Netherlands|Dutch]] [[publishing]] and [[analytics]] company specializing in scientific, technical, and medical content. It is a part of the [[RELX Group]], known until 2015 as Reed Elsevier.  Its products include journals such as ''[[The Lancet]]'' and ''[[Cell (journal)|Cell]]'', the [[ScienceDirect]] collection of electronic journals, the ''[[Trends (journals)|Trends]]'' and ''[[Current Opinion (Elsevier)|Current Opinion]]'' series of journals, the online citation database [[Scopus]], and the [[ClinicalKey]] search engine for clinicians. Elsevier's products also include digital tools for data-management, instruction, and assessment.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://scholarlykitchen.sspnet.org/2017/02/02/plum-goes-orange-elsevier-acquires-plum-analytics/|title = Plum Goes Orange \u2013 Elsevier Acquires Plum Analytics |date = 2017-02-02 }}</ref>\n\nElsevier publishes more than 470,000 articles annually in 2,500 journals.<ref name=\"RELX 2018 Report\">{{Cite web |url = https://www.relx.com/~/media/Files/R/RELX-Group/documents/reports/annual-reports/2018-annual-report.pdf |title = 2018 RELX Group Annual Report |date = March 2019 |accessdate =  |website = RELX Company Reports |publisher = RELX}}</ref> Its archives contain over 16 million documents and 30,000 e-books. Total yearly downloads amount to more than 1 billion.<ref name = \"RELX 2018 Report\" />\n\nElsevier's high operating profit margins (37% in 2018) and 950 million pounds in profits, often on publicly funded research works<ref name=\"RELX 2018 Report\" /><ref name=\"relx-results-press-release-2018\">\n{{cite press release\n | author = RELX\n | title = RELX \u2014 Results for the year to December 2018\n | date = 21 February 2019\n | publisher = RELX Group\n | location = London, United Kingdom and Amsterdam, The Netherlands\n | url = https://www.relx.com/~/media/Files/R/RELX-Group/documents/press-releases/2019/relx-results-2018-pressrelease.pdf\n | access-date = 2019-03-27\n}}  Adjusted operating margin for 2017 for the publishing division is 36.8% (p6).\n</ref> \nand its [[Copyright policies of academic publishers|copyright practices]] have subjected it to criticism by researchers.<ref name=boyc >{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/02/14/science/researchers-boycott-elsevier-journal-publisher.html|title=Mathematicians Organize Boycott of a Publisher | work=The New York Times | first=Thomas|last=Lin|date=13 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n==History==\n\n[[File:Elsevier.svg|200px|right|thumb|The original seal of the Elsevier family, used by Elsevier company as logo until 2019.]]\nElsevier was founded in 1880{{sfn|Groen|2007|p=217}} and adopted the name and logo from the Dutch publishing house [[House of Elzevir|Elzevir]] that was an inspiration and has no connection to the contemporary Elsevier.{{sfn|Groen|2007|p=217}} The Elzevir family operated as booksellers and publishers in the [[Netherlands]]; the founder, [[Lodewijk Elzevir]] (1542\u20131617), lived in [[Leiden]] and established the business in 1580. As company logo, Elsevier used the Elzevir family's printer's mark, a tree entwined with a vine and the words ''Non Solus'', which is Latin for \"not alone.\"<ref name=\"AT 2019-03\" /> Elsevier suggests that this logo represents \"the symbiotic relationship between publisher and scholar\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.facebook.com/notes/elsevier-india/interesting-fact-history-of-the-elsevier-logo/295913917111368/ |title=Interesting Fact - History of the Elsevier Logo |website=[[Facebook]] |access-date=2019-06-12}}</ref>\n\nThe expansion of Elsevier in the scientific field after 1945 was funded with the profits of the newsweekly ''[[Elsevier (magazine)|Elsevier]]'', which published its first issue on 27 October 1945. The weekly was an instant success and earned lots of money.<ref>Gerry van der List, ''Meer dan een weekblad. De geschiedenis van Elsevier''</ref> The weekly was a continuation, as is stated in its first issue, of the monthly Elsevier, which was founded in 1891 to promote the name of the publishing house and had to stop publication in December 1940 because of the [[Netherlands in World War II|Nazi occupation of the Netherlands]].\n\nIn 1947, Elsevier began publishing its first English-language journal, ''[[Biochimica et Biophysica Acta]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Reed Elsevier Timeline |url=http://www.ulib.niu.edu/publishers/ReedElsevier.htm |website=www.ulib.niu.edu |accessdate=13 September 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151030233859/http://www.ulib.niu.edu/publishers/ReedElsevier.htm |archivedate=30 October 2015 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Elsevier acquired [[Mendeley]], a UK company making software for managing and sharing research papers. Mendeley, previously an open platform for sharing of research, was greatly criticized for the acquisition, which users saw as acceding to the \"[[paywall]]\" approach to research literature. Mendeley's previously open sharing system now allows exchange of paywalled resources only within private groups.<ref name=fast>{{cite web |last1=Amirtha |first1=Tina |title=THE OPEN PUBLISHING REVOLUTION, NOW BEHIND A BILLION-DOLLAR PAYWALL |url=http://www.fastcompany.com/3042443/mendeley-elsevier-and-the-future-of-scholarly-publishing |website=Fast Company |accessdate=26 January 2016 |date=2015-04-17}}</ref> ''[[The New Yorker]]'' described Elsevier's reasons for buying Mendeley as two-fold: to acquire its user data, and to \"destroy or co\u00f6pt an [[Open science|open-science]] icon that threatens its [[business model]]\".<ref name=\"NewYorker\">{{cite magazine |url=https://www.newyorker.com/online/blogs/elements/2013/04/elsevier-mendeley-journals-science-software.html |title=When the Rebel Alliance Sells Out |first=David |last=Dobbs |magazine=[[The New Yorker]] |date=12 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn the first half of 2019, RELX reported the first slowdown in revenue growth for Elsevier in several years: 1% vs. an expectation of 2% and a typical growth of at least 4% in the previous 5 years.<ref>{{cite news|title=Relx falls short of growth expectations|newspaper=Financial Times|author=Patricia Nilsson|date=2019-07-25|via=[https://finance.yahoo.com/m/c84c5326-55c5-3f81-b51d-9d1f4b7806e7/relx-falls-short-of-growth.html Yahoo Finance]}}</ref>\n\n== Company statistics ==\n{{as of | 2018 | alt = During 2018}}, researchers submitted over 1.8 million [[research papers]] to Elsevier-based publications. Over 20,000 editors managed the peer review and selection of these papers, resulting in the publication of more than 470,000 articles in over 2,500 journals.<ref name=\"RELX 2018 Report\" /> Editors are generally unpaid volunteers who perform their duties alongside a full-time job in academic institutions,<ref>{{cite journal|first1=James A.|last1=Coleman|title=How to get published in English: Advice from the outgoing Editor-in-Chief |url= |journal=System |date=2014-01-03 |issn=0346-251X |pages=404\u2013411 |volume=42 |doi=10.1016/j.system.2014.01.004|quote=Remember that editors and reviewers are unpaid, and are undertaking their tasks voluntarily, in addition to a full-time job}}</ref> although exceptions have been reported.\n\nIn 2013, the five editorial groups Elsevier, [[Springer Science+Business Media|Springer]], [[Wiley-Blackwell]], [[Taylor & Francis]], and [[SAGE Publications]] published more than half of all academic papers in the peer-reviewed literature.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vocativ.com/culture/science/five-corporations-control-academic-publishing/|title=These Five Corporations Control Academic Publishing|date=10 June 2015|website=Vocativ.com|accessdate=31 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=The Oligopoly of Academic Publishers in the Digital Era|author1=Vincent Larivi\u00e8re |author2=Stefanie Haustein |author3=Philippe Mongeon |journal=PLoS ONE|volume=10|issue=6|year=2015|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0127502 |pmid=26061978 |pmc=4465327 |pages=e0127502|bibcode=2015PLoSO..1027502L}}</ref> At that time, Elsevier accounted for 16% of the world market in science, technology, and medical publishing.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Elsevier leads the business the internet could not kill |url = https://www.ft.com/content/93138f3e-87d6-11e5-90de-f44762bf9896|website = www.ft.com|accessdate = 7 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nElsevier breaks down its revenue sources by format and by geographic region. Approximately 44% of revenue by geography in 2018 derived from North America, 24% from Europe and the remaining 32% from the rest of the world. Approximately 83% of revenue by format came from electronic usage and 17% came from print.<ref name=\"RELX 2018 Report\" />\n\nElsevier employs more than 7,800 people in over 70 offices across 24 countries. Following the integration of its Science & Technology and Health Sciences divisions in 2012, Elsevier has operated under a traditional business structure with a single [[chief executive officer]] (CEO).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.infotoday.com/it/mar13/Brynko--Mobed--Elseviers-Next-Steps.shtml|title=Elsevier Next Steps|publisher=Information Today|accessdate=7 November 2016}}</ref> The CEO is Kumsal Bayazit,<ref name=\"ataglance\">{{cite web |url= https://www.elsevier.com/about/management/kumsal-bayazit |title=Kumsal Bayazit |website=Elsevier.com |accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref> who was appointed on 15 February 2019.\n\nIn 2018, Elsevier accounted for 34% of the revenues of RELX group (\u20a42.538 billion of \u20a47.492 billion). In [[Earnings before interest and taxes|operating profits]], it represented 40% (\u20a4942 million of \u20a42,346 million). Adjusted operating profits (with constant currency) rose by 2% from 2017 to 2018.<ref name=\"RELX 2018 Report\" />\n\nIn 2018, Elsevier reported a mean 2017 [[gender pay gap]] of 29.1% for its UK workforce, while the median was 40.4%, more than twice the UK average and by far the worst figure recorded by any academic publisher in UK. Elsevier attributed the result to the under-representation of women in its senior ranks and the prevalence of men in its technical workforce.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2019-08-11|title=Elsevier reports 40% gender pay gap|url=https://www.thebookseller.com/news/elsevier-reports-40-gender-pay-gap-759606|website=www.thebookseller.com}}</ref>\n\n==Market model==\n\n===Products and services===\n\nProducts and services include electronic and print versions of journals, textbooks and [[reference work]]s, and cover the [[healthcare science|health]], life, physical and [[social science]]s.\n\nThe target markets are academic and government research institutions, corporate research labs, booksellers, librarians, scientific researchers, authors, editors, physicians, nurses, allied health professionals, medical and nursing students and schools, medical researchers, [[Pharmaceutical company|pharmaceutical companies]], hospitals, and research establishments. It publishes in 13 languages including English, German, French, Spanish, Italian, Portuguese, Polish, Japanese, Hindi, and Chinese.\n\nFlagship products and services include VirtualE, [[ScienceDirect]], [[Scopus]], [[Scirus]], [[EMBASE]], Engineering Village, [[Compendex]], [[Cell (journal)|Cell]], SciVal, Pure, and Analytical Services, The Consult series (FirstCONSULT, PathCONSULT, NursingCONSULT, MDConsult, StudentCONSULT), Virtual Clinical Excursions, and major reference works such as ''[[Gray's Anatomy]]'', ''Nelson Pediatrics'', ''[[Dorland's Illustrated Medical Dictionary]]'', ''[[Frank H. Netter|Netter]]'s Atlas of Human Anatomy'', and online versions of many journals<ref>[http://www.journals.elsevierhealth.com/ Health Advance]. Elsevier.</ref> including ''[[The Lancet]]''.\n\nScienceDirect is Elsevier's platform for online electronic access to its journals and over 6,000 e-books, reference works, book series, and handbooks. The articles are grouped in four main sections: ''Physical Sciences and Engineering'', ''Life Sciences'', ''Health Sciences'', and ''Social Sciences and Humanities''. For most articles on the website, abstracts are freely available; access to the full text of the article (in PDF, and also HTML for newer publications) often requires a subscription or pay-per-view purchase.\n\n===Research and information ecosystem===\n\n[[RELX Group]] has been [[RELX Group#Significant acquisitions|active]] in [[mergers and acquisitions]]. Elsevier has been joined by businesses which were either complementing or competing in the field of research and publishing and which reinforce its [[market power]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20170804/05454537924/elsevier-continues-to-build-monopoly-solution-all-aspects-scholarly-communication.shtml|title=Elsevier Continues To Build Its Monopoly Solution For All Aspects Of Scholarly Communication|last=|first=|date=2017-08-04|work=Techdirt|access-date=2018-10-17|author=Glyn Moody|author-link=Glyn Moody}}</ref> such as [[Mendeley]] (after the closure of [[2collab]]), [[SSRN]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20160517/13513134465/disappointing-elsevier-buys-open-access-academic-pre-publisher-ssrn.shtml|title=Disappointing: Elsevier Buys Open Access Academic Pre-Publisher SSRN|last=|first=|date=2016-05-17|work=Techdirt|access-date=2018-10-17|author=Mike Masnick|author-link=Mike Masnick}}</ref> [[bepress]]/[[Digital Commons (Elsevier)|Digital Commons]], [[PlumX]], Hivebench, Newsflo.<ref name=Herb2019/> These integrations are seen as a way to exert additional power on the research process.<ref name=Herb2019>{{cite journal |last1=Herb |first1=Ulrich|date=2019|title=Steering science through Output Indicators & Data Capitalism|doi=10.5281/zenodo.3333395|doi-access=free}}</ref> The group contains additional information and analytics companies, particularly [[LexisNexis]] and [[ThreatMetrix]].\n\n=== Conferences ===\nElsevier conducts conferences, exhibitions and workshops around the world, with over 50 conferences a year covering life sciences, physical sciences and engineering, social sciences, and health sciences.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.elsevier.com/events/conferences |title=Conferences |work=elsevier.com}}</ref>\n\n===Pricing===\n\nIn the 21st century, the subscription rates charged by the company for its journals have been criticized; some very large journals (with more than 5,000 articles) charge subscription prices as high as \u00a39,634, far above average,<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2011/aug/29/academic-publishers-murdoch-socialist|journal=Guardian|last=Monbiot|first=George|date=29 August 2011|title=Academic publishers make Murdoch look like a socialist}}</ref> and many British universities pay more than a million pounds to Elsevier annually.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://gowers.wordpress.com/2014/04/24/elsevier-journals-some-facts/ |title=Elsevier journals \u2014 some facts |work=Gowers's Weblog |date=24 April 2014 |accessdate=27 July 2014}}</ref> The company has been criticized not only by advocates of a switch to the [[Open access (publishing)|open-access]] publication model, but also by universities whose library budgets make it difficult for them to afford current journal prices.\n\nFor example, a resolution by [[Stanford University]]'s senate singled out Elsevier's journals as being \"disproportionately expensive compared to their educational and research value\", which librarians should consider dropping, and encouraged its faculty \"not to contribute articles or editorial or review efforts to publishers and journals that engage in exploitive or exorbitant pricing\".<ref>''[http://news-service.stanford.edu/news/2004/february25/minutes-225.html Faculty Senate minutes February 19 meeting]'' Stanford Report, 25 February 2004</ref> Similar guidelines and criticism of Elsevier's pricing policies have been passed by the [[University of California]], [[Harvard University]], and [[Duke University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.stanforddaily.com/?p=1013953 |title=Fac Sen addresses costly journals |work=The Stanford Daily |date=20 February 2004 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105040316/http://archive.stanforddaily.com/?p=1013953 |archivedate=5 November 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nIn July 2015, the [[Association of Universities in the Netherlands]] (VSNU) announced a plan to start boycotting Elsevier, which refused to negotiate on any [[Open Access]] policy for Dutch universities.<ref>Danny Kingsley [https://unlockingresearch.blog.lib.cam.ac.uk/?p=192 ''Dutch boycott of Elsevier \u2013 a game changer?''], University of Cambridge Office of Scholarly Communication</ref> In December 2016, [[Nature Publishing Group]] reported that academics in Germany, Peru and Taiwan are to lose access to Elsevier journals as negotiations had broken down with the publisher.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Schiermeier|first=Quirin|last2=Mega|first2=Emiliano Rodr\u00edguez|title=Scientists in Germany, Peru and Taiwan to lose access to Elsevier journals|journal=Nature|doi=10.1038/nature.2016.21223|pmid=28054621|volume=541|issue=7635|page=13|year=2016|bibcode=2017Natur.541...13S|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\nA complaint about Elsevier/RELX was made to the UK [[Competition and Markets Authority]] in December 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.martineve.com/2016/12/03/referring-elsevierrelx-to-the-competition-and-markets-authority/|title=Referring Elsevier/RELX to the Competition and Markets Authority|author=Martin Paul Eve|language=en-US|date=2016-12-14|author-link=Martin Paul Eve}}</ref> In October 2018, a competition complaint against Elsevier was filed with the European Commission, alleging anti-competitive practices stemming from Elsevier's confidential subscription agreements and market dominance.<ref name=\"competition_plaint\">{{cite news |last1=Kelly |first1=\u00c9anna |title=Researchers complain to Brussels over 'dominant position' of RELX Group in scientific publishing |url=https://sciencebusiness.net/framework-programmes/news/researchers-complain-brussels-over-dominant-position-relx-group |accessdate=16 January 2019 |work=sciencebusiness.net |date=2 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Shill review offer ===\n\nAccording to the [[BBC]], \"the firm [Elsevier] offered a \u00a317.25 Amazon voucher to academics who contributed to the textbook ''Clinical Psychology'' if they would go on [[Amazon.com]] and [[Barnes & Noble]] (a large US books retailer) and give it five stars.\" Elsevier said that \"encouraging interested parties to post book reviews isn't outside the norm in scholarly publishing, nor is it wrong to offer to nominally compensate people for their time. But in all instances the request should be unbiased, with no incentives for a positive review, and that's where this particular e-mail went too far\", and that it was a mistake by a marketing employee.<ref>Finlo Rohrer, \"[http://news.bbc.co.uk/go/pr/fr/-/2/hi/uk_news/magazine/8118577.stm The perils of five-star reviews]\", ''BBC News Magazine'', 25 June 2009.</ref>\n\n=== Blocking text mining research ===\nElsevier seeks to regulate [[text and data mining]] with private licenses,<ref name=nature527413f/> claiming that reading requires extra permission if automated and that the publisher holds copyright on [[threshold of originality|output of automated processes]]. The conflict on research and copyright policy has often resulted in researchers being blocked from their work.<ref>{{cite journal|first1=Richard|last1=Van Noorden|title=Elsevier opens its papers to text-mining|journal=Nature|date=2014-02-03|issn=0028-0836|pages=17|volume=506|issue=7486|doi=10.1038/506017a|pmid=24499898|doi-access=free|quote=\u201cIt was a legitimate criticism, that people sent text-mining requests in to publishers and they bounced around for a time without any response,\u201d admits Chris Shillum, vice-president of product management for platform and content at Elsevier.|bibcode=2014Natur.506...17V}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2015, Elsevier blocked a scientist from performing [[text mining]] research at scale on Elsevier papers, even though his institution already pays for access to Elsevier journal content.<ref name=nature527413f>{{cite journal|last1=Bloudoff-Indelicato|first1=Mollie|title=Text-mining block prompts online response|journal=Nature|date=20 November 2015|volume=527|issue=7579|pages=413|doi=10.1038/527413f|bibcode=2015Natur.527..413B}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Moody|first1=Glyn|title=Elsevier Says Downloading And Content-Mining Licensed Copies Of Research Papers 'Could Be Considered' Stealing|url=https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20151117/09383132839/elsevier-says-downloading-content-mining-licensed-copies-research-papers-could-be-considered-stealing.shtml|website=TechDirt|accessdate=21 November 2015}}</ref> The data were collected via parsing of downloaded PDF and HTML files,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Nuijten|first1=Mich\u00e8le B.|last2=Hartgerink|first2=Chris H. J.|last3=van Assen|first3=Marcel A. L. M.|last4=Epskamp|first4=Sacha|last5=Wicherts|first5=Jelte M.|title=The prevalence of statistical reporting errors in psychology (1985\u20132013)|journal=Behavior Research Methods|date=23 October 2015|volume=48|issue=4|pages=1205\u20131226|doi=10.3758/s13428-015-0664-2|pmid=26497820|pmc=5101263}}</ref> although Elsevier claimed that the method used was [[screenscraping]].<ref>A. Wise, 2015-11-17, [http://onsnetwork.org/chartgerink/2015/11/16/elsevier-stopped-me-doing-my-research/#comment-11 Elsevier stopped me doing my research - Comment by Dr Alicia Wise]</ref>\n\n== Academic practices ==\n\n=== \"Who's Afraid of Peer Review\" ===\n{{main|Who's Afraid of Peer Review?}}\n\nOne of Elsevier's journals was caught in the sting set up by [[John Bohannon]], published in [[Science (journal)|''Science'']], called \"Who's Afraid of Peer Review?\"<ref name=\"Bohannon2013\">{{Cite journal | last1 = Bohannon | first1 = John| authorlink1 = John Bohannon| title = Who's Afraid of Peer Review? | doi = 10.1126/science.342.6154.60 | journal = Science | volume = 342 | issue = 6154 | pages = 60\u201365 | year = 2013 | pmid =  24092725| pmc = |bibcode = 2013Sci...342...60B | doi-access = free }}</ref> The journal ''Drug Invention Today'' accepted an obviously bogus paper made up by Bohannon that should have been rejected by any good [[peer review]] system.<ref>{{cite news|author=Claire Shaw |url=https://www.theguardian.com/higher-education-network/2013/oct/04/open-access-journals-fake-paper |title=Hundreds of open access journals accept fake science paper |publisher=Theguardian.com |accessdate=26 December 2013|newspaper=The Guardian |date=2013-10-04 }}</ref> Instead, ''Drug Invention Today'' was among many [[open access]] journals that accepted the fake paper for publication. As of 2014, this journal had been transferred to a different publisher.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/journal/09757619|title=Drug Invention Today|work=sciencedirect.com}}</ref>\n\n=== Fake journals ===<!-- See talk section \"Elsevier published 6 fake journals\" for discussion of this heading\" -->\n{{further|Australasian Journal of Bone & Joint Medicine}}\n\nAt a 2009 court case in Australia where [[Merck & Co.]] was being sued by a user of [[Vioxx]], the plaintiff alleged that Merck had paid Elsevier to publish the ''[[Australasian Journal of Bone and Joint Medicine]]'', which had the appearance of being a [[peer-review]]ed [[academic journal]] but in fact contained only articles favourable to Merck drugs.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/story/0,25197,25311725-5013871,00.html |title=Doctors signed Merck's Vioxx studies |last=Rout |first=Milanda |date=9 April 2009 |work=[[The Australian]] |accessdate=4 May 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090506064629/http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/story/0,25197,25311725-5013871,00.html |archive-date=6 May 2009 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://classic.the-scientist.com/blog/display/55671/ |title=Merck published fake journal |last=Grant |first=Bob |date=30 April 2009 |work=[[The Scientist (magazine)|The Scientist]] |accessdate=4 May 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.theage.com.au/national/merck-accused-of-ghost-writing-medical-article-20090422-afdk.html?page=-1 |title=Merck accused of 'ghost writing' medical article |last=Hagan |first=Kate |date=23 April 2009 |work=[[The Age]] |accessdate=4 May 2009}}</ref><ref>Ben Goldacre, [https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2009/may/09/bad-science-medical-journals-companies \"The danger of drugs \u2026 and data\"], ''The Guardian'', 9 May 2009</ref> Merck described the journal as a \"complimentary publication,\" denied claims that articles within it were [[ghost writer|ghost written]] by Merck, and stated that the articles were all reprinted from peer-reviewed medical journals.<ref>{{cite press release|title=Merck Responds to Questions about the Australasian Journal of Bone and Joint Medicine Journal |date=30 April 2009 |url=http://www.merck.com/newsroom/vioxx/pdf/statement_20090430.pdf |publisher=[[Merck & Co.]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091231104929/http://merck.com/newsroom/vioxx/pdf/statement_20090430.pdf |archivedate=31 December 2009 |df=dmy }}</ref> In May 2009, Elsevier Health Sciences CEO Hansen released a statement regarding Australia-based sponsored journals, conceding that they were \"sponsored article compilation publications, on behalf of pharmaceutical clients, that were made to look like journals and lacked the proper disclosures.\" The statement acknowledged that it \"was an unacceptable practice.\"<ref>{{cite press release |title=Statement from Michael Hansen, CEO Of Elsevier's Health Sciences Division, regarding Australia based sponsored journal practices between 2000 and 2005 |url= http://www.elsevier.com/wps/find/authored_newsitem.cws_home/companynews05_01203 |publisher=Elsevier}}</ref> ''[[The Scientist (magazine)|The Scientist]]'' reported that, according to an Elsevier spokesperson, six sponsored publications \"were put out by their Australia office and bore the [[Excerpta Medica]] imprint from 2000 to 2005,\" namely the ''Australasian Journal of Bone and Joint Medicine'' (''Australas. J. Bone Joint Med.''), the ''Australasian Journal of General Practice'' (''Australas. J. Gen. Pract.''), the ''Australasian Journal of Neurology'' (''Australas. J. Neurol.''), the ''Australasian Journal of Cardiology'' (''Australas. J. Cardiol.''), the ''Australasian Journal of Clinical Pharmacy'' (''Australas. J. Clin. Pharm.''), and the ''Australasian Journal of Cardiovascular Medicine'' (''Australas. J. Cardiovasc. Med.'').<ref>{{cite news|first=Bob|last=Grant|title=Elsevier published 6 fake journals |url=http://www.the-scientist.com/blog/display/55679/ |date=7 May 2009 |work=[[The Scientist (magazine)|The Scientist]]}}</ref> Excerpta Medica was a \"strategic medical communications agency\" run by Elsevier, according to the imprint's web page.<ref>{{cite web|title=\"Excerpta Medica\", official webpage |url=http://www.excerptamedica.com/ |publisher=Elsevier}}</ref> In October 2010, Excerpta Medica was acquired by Adelphi Worldwide.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Excerpta Medica Joins Adelphi Worldwide\", press release |url= http://www.excerptamedica.com/?page=newsroom&item=301 |publisher=Elsevier}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Chaos, Solitons & Fractals'' ===\n\nThere was speculation<ref>{{cite journal |title=Self-publishing editor set to retire |doi=10.1038/456432a | volume=456 |issue=7221 | journal=Nature |pages=432 |pmid=19037282 | last1 = Schiermeier | first1 = Q|year=2008 |doi-access=free }}</ref> that the editor-in-chief of Elsevier journal ''Chaos, Solitons & Fractals'', [[Mohamed El Naschie]], misused his power to publish his own work without appropriate peer review. The journal had published 322 papers with El Naschie as author since 1993. The last issue of December 2008 featured five of his papers.<ref>''Chaos, Solitons & Fractals'' '''38'''(5), pp. 1229\u20131534 (December 2008)</ref> The controversy was covered extensively in blogs.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://scholarlykitchen.sspnet.org/?s=el+naschie| title= The Scholarly Kitchen}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://elnaschiewatch.blogspot.com/ |title= El Naschie Watch Blog |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101015195449/http://elnaschiewatch.blogspot.com/ |archivedate= 15 October 2010 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> The publisher announced in January 2009 that El Naschie had retired as editor-in-chief.<ref>{{Cite journal| doi = 10.1016/S0960-0779(09)00060-5| title = Publisher's note| year = 2009| journal = Chaos, Solitons & Fractals| volume = 39| pages = v\u2013|bibcode = 2009CSF....39D...5. }}</ref> {{As of|2011|11}} the co-Editors-in-Chief of the journal were Maurice Courbage and Paolo Grigolini.<ref>{{cite book |url= http://www.journals.elsevier.com/chaos-solitons-and-fractals/ |title= Chaos, Solitons and Fractals |date=November 2011}}</ref> In June 2011, El Naschie sued the journal ''[[Nature (journal)|Nature]]'' for libel, claiming that his reputation had been damaged by their November 2008 article about his retirement, which included statements that ''Nature'' had been unable to verify his claimed affiliations with certain international institutions.<ref name=\"BBC-CSF-libel\">{{cite news | title = Nature journal libel case begins | work = BBC News | last1 = Ghosh | first1 = Pallab | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-15697636 | accessdate = 11 November 2011 | date=11 November 2011}}</ref> The suit came to trial in November 2011 and was dismissed in July 2012, with the judge ruling that the article was \"substantially true\", contained \"honest comment\" and was \"the product of responsible journalism\". The judgement noted that El Naschie, who represented himself in court, had failed to provide any documentary evidence that his papers had been peer-reviewed.<ref name=\"Guardian2\">[https://www.theguardian.com/science/2012/jul/06/nature-libel-peer-review?newsfeed=true \"Nature libel verdict 'a victory for free speech'\"],''The Guardian'' 6 July 2012</ref> Judge [[Victoria Sharp]] also found \"reasonable and serious grounds\" for suspecting that El Naschie used a range of false names to defend his editorial practice in communications with ''Nature'', and described this behavior as \"curious\" and \"bizarre.\" <ref>{{cite journal\n| last       = Aron\n| first       = Jacob\n| date        = 6 July 2012\n| title       = Nature Publishing Group wins libel trial\n| journal     = New Scientist\n| issue       = 2873\n| url         = https://www.newscientist.com/article/dn22026-nature-publishing-group-wins-libel-trial.html\n| accessdate  = 14 July 2012\n}}</ref>\n\n===Plagiarism===\nSome Elsevier journals automatically screen submissions for plagiarism,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.elsevier.com/editors/perk/plagiarism-complaints/plagiarism-detection |title=Plagiarism detection |publisher=Elsevier}}</ref> but not all.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://retractionwatch.com/2018/08/23/elsevier-investigating-paper-on-solar-cells-that-appears-to-plagiarize-a-nature-journal/ |title=UPDATED: Elsevier retracts a paper on solar cells that appears to plagiarize a Nature journal. But the reason is\u2026odd |author=Ivan Oransky|date=2018-08-23}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Elsevier journal ''[[Procedia]]'' was reported to have published plagiarism by an Albanian politician in 2012.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://exit.al/en/2018/12/25/massive-plagiarism-scandal-hits-albanian-officials/ |title= Massive Plagiarism Scandal Hits Albanian Officials without Consequences |date=2018-12-25}}</ref>\n\n== Control of journals ==\n\n=== Resignation of editorial boards ===\nIn November 1999 the entire editorial board (50 persons) of the ''[[Journal of Logic Programming]]'' (founded in 1984 by [[John Alan Robinson|Alan Robinson]]) collectively resigned after 16 months of unsuccessful negotiations with Elsevier Press about the price of library subscriptions.<ref name=birman>[[Joan Birman]]. \"[http://www.ams.org/notices/200007/forum-birman.pdf Scientific publishing: a mathematician\u2019s viewpoint]\". ''[[Notices of the AMS]]''. Vol. 47, No. 7, August 2000</ref> The personnel created a new journal, ''Theory and Practice of Logic Programming'', with [[Cambridge University Press]] at a much lower price,<ref name=birman/> while Elsevier continued publication with a new editorial board and a slightly different name (the ''[[Journal of Logic and Algebraic Programming]]'').\n\nIn 2002, dissatisfaction at Elsevier's pricing policies caused the [[European Economic Association]] to terminate an agreement with Elsevier designating Elsevier's ''[[European Economic Review]]'' as the official journal of the association. The EEA launched a new journal, the ''[[Journal of the European Economic Association]]''.<ref>{{cite web|author=EffeDesign |url=http://www.eeassoc.org/index.php?page=14 |title=The EEA's journal: a brief history |publisher=Eeassoc.org |accessdate=26 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, the entire editorial board of the ''Journal of Algorithms'' resigned to start ''[[ACM Transactions on Algorithms]]'' with a different, lower-priced, not-for-profit publisher,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cs.colorado.edu/~hal/s.pdf |title=Changes at the Journal of Algorithms |accessdate=26 December 2013}}</ref> at the suggestion of ''Journal of Algorithms'' founder [[Donald Knuth]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www-cs-faculty.stanford.edu/~knuth/joalet.pdf | author=Donald Knuth| date=25 October 2003 | title=Letter to the editorial board of the Journal of Algorithms| accessdate=18 February 2008}}</ref> The ''Journal of Algorithms'' continued under Elsevier with a new editorial board until October 2009, when it was discontinued.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/journal/01966774 |title=Journal of Algorithms page at ScienceDirect |publisher=Sciencedirect.com |accessdate=26 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe same happened in 2005 to the ''International Journal of Solids and Structures'', whose editors resigned to start the ''[[Journal of Mechanics of Materials and Structures]]''. However, a new editorial board was quickly established and the journal continues in apparently unaltered form with editors D.A. Hills ([[Oxford University]]) and Stelios Kyriakides ([[University of Texas at Austin]]).<ref>{{cite web |title=Journal declarations of independence |url=http://oad.simmons.edu/oadwiki/Journal_declarations_of_independence#2005 |work=Open Access Directory |publisher=Simmons College |accessdate=23 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Kyriakides|first=Stelios|author2=Hills, David A.|title=Editorial|journal=International Journal of Solids and Structures|date=1 January 2006|volume=43|issue=1|page=1|doi=10.1016/j.ijsolstr.2005.11.001|accessdate=|quote=Charles R. Steele succeeded Herrmann as editor in chief in 1985 and served in that capacity until June 2005. During his 20-year tenure the journal grew both in size and in reputation, becoming one of the premier journals in the field. We have accepted an invitation to serve as editors of the journal as of October 1, 2005, being cognizant of the immense contributions, leadership, and high standards exercised by our two predecessors on the way to making IJSS the forum it is today.}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2006, the entire editorial board of the distinguished [[mathematical journal]] ''[[Topology (journal)|Topology]]'' handed in their resignation, again because of stalled negotiations with Elsevier to lower the subscription price.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://math.ucr.edu/home/baez/topology-letter.pdf | date=10 August 2006 | title=Resignation letter from the editors of Topology | accessdate=18 February 2008}}</ref> This board then launched the new ''[[Journal of Topology]]'' at a far lower price, under the auspices of the [[London Mathematical Society]].<ref>[http://www.lms.ac.uk/publications/jtop.html Journal of Topology] (pub. London Mathematical Society) {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070207123258/http://www.lms.ac.uk/publications/jtop.html |date=7 February 2007 }}</ref> After this mass resignation, ''[[Topology (journal)|Topology]]'' remained in circulation under a new editorial board until 2009, when the last issue was published.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://www.journals.elsevier.com/topology/|title=Topology|publisher=elsevier.com|accessdate=13 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/journal/00409383/48/2-4 |title=Topology page at ScienceDirect |publisher=Sciencedirect.com |accessdate=26 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe French [[\u00c9cole Normale Sup\u00e9rieure]] has stopped having Elsevier publish the journal ''[[Annales Scientifiques de l'\u00c9cole Normale Sup\u00e9rieure]]''<ref>[[John Baez]]: ''[http://math.ucr.edu/home/baez/journals.html What We Can Do About Science Journals]'' 13 August 2007</ref> (as of 2008).<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.elsevier.com/wps/find/journaldescription.cws_home/600714/description | title=Publisher's description of Annales Scientifiques de l'\u00c9cole Normale Sup\u00e9rieure | publisher=Elsevier | accessdate=18 February 2008 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080412014908/http://www.elsevier.com/wps/find/journaldescription.cws_home/600714/description | archivedate=12 April 2008 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe elevated pricing of field journals in economics, most of which are published by Elsevier, was one of the motivations that moved the [[American Economic Association]] to launch the ''[[American Economic Journal]]'' in 2009.<ref>David Glenn. \"American Economic Association Plans 4 New Journals\". '' The Chronicle of Higher Education''. 25 January 2008. Available online at [http://chronicle.com/article/American-Economic-Association/440 Chronicle.com]</ref>\n\nIn May 2015, [[Stephen Leeder]] was removed from his role as editor of the ''[[Medical Journal of Australia]]'' after its publisher decided to outsource the journal's production to Elsevier. As a consequence, all but one of the journal's editorial advisory committee members co-signed a letter of resignation.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/medical-journal-editor-sacked-and-editorial-committee-resigns-20150503-1myr8q.html | title=Medical journal editor sacked and editorial committee resigns | accessdate=18 May 2015| date=2015-05-03 }}</ref>\n\nIn October 2015, the entire editorial staff of the [[general linguistics]] journal ''[[Lingua (journal)|Lingua]]'' resigned in protest of Elsevier's unwillingness to agree to their terms of [[Fair Access to Science and Technology Research Act|Fair Open Access]]. Editor in Chief Johan Rooryck also announced that the Lingua staff would establish a new journal, ''[[Glossa (journal)|Glossa]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2015/11/02/editors-and-editorial-board-quit-top-linguistics-journal-protest-subscription-fees|title=Language of Protest|last=Jaschik|first=Scott|date=2 November 2015|work=Inside Higher Ed|access-date=18 January 2017|via=}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2019, the entire editorial board of Elsevier's ''[[Journal of Informetrics]]'' resigned over the open-access policies of its publisher and founded open-access journal called Quantitative Science Studies.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2019/01/14/elsevier-journal-editors-resign-start-rival-open-access-journal|title=Elsevier journal editors resign, start rival open-access journal}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2019/01/14/elsevier-journal-editors-resign-start-rival-open-access-journal|title=Elsevier journal editors resign, start rival open-access journal|website=www.insidehighered.com|language=en|access-date=2019-01-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Chawla|first=Dalmeet Singh|date=2019-01-14|title=Open-access row prompts editorial board of Elsevier journal to resign|url=http://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-019-00135-8|journal=Nature|language=EN|doi=10.1038/d41586-019-00135-8}}</ref>\n\n===\"The Cost of Knowledge\" boycott===\n{{Main|The Cost of Knowledge}}\n\nIn 2003 various university librarians began coordinating with each other to complain about Elsevier's \"[[Subscription business model|big deal]]\" journal bundling packages, in which the company offered a group of journal subscriptions to libraries at a certain rate, but in which librarians claimed there was no economical option to subscribe to only the popular journals at a rate comparable to the bundled rate.{{sfn|Groen|2007|p=177}} Librarians continued to discuss the implications of the pricing schemes, many feeling pressured into buying the Elsevier packages without other options.{{sfn|Groen|2007|p=180}}\n\nOn 21 January 2012, mathematician [[Timothy Gowers]] publicly announced he would boycott Elsevier, noting that others in the field have been doing so privately. The three reasons for the [[boycott]] are high subscription prices for individual journals, bundling subscriptions to journals of different value and importance, and Elsevier's support for [[Stop Online Piracy Act|SOPA]], [[PROTECT IP Act|PIPA]], and the [[Research Works Act]].<ref name=Guardian>{{cite news|last=Flood |first=Alison |url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2012/feb/02/academics-boycott-publisher-elsevier |title=Scientists sign petition to boycott academic publisher Elsevier |newspaper=The Guardian |date=2 February 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/65VHiGo2Z?url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/science/2012/feb/02/academics-boycott-publisher-elsevier |archivedate=16 February 2012 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref><ref name=Chronicle>{{cite news|last=Fischman |first=Josh |url=http://chronicle.com/blogs/wiredcampus/elsevier-publishing-boycott-gathers-steam-among-academics/35216 |title=Elsevier Publishing Boycott Gathers Steam Among Academics |newspaper=The Chronicle of Higher Education |date=30 January 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/65VIHYC2S?url=http://chronicle.com/blogs/wiredcampus/elsevier-publishing-boycott-gathers-steam-among-academics/35216 |archivedate=16 February 2012 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref><ref name=Economist>{{cite news|url=http://www.economist.com/node/21545974 |title=Scientific publishing: The price of information |work=The Economist |date=4 February 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/65VHxfKJ9?url=http://www.economist.com/node/21545974 |archivedate=16 February 2012 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nFollowing this, a petition advocating non-cooperation with Elsevier (that is, not submitting papers to Elsevier journals, not [[peer review|refereeing]] articles in Elsevier journals, and not participating in journal editorial boards), appeared on the site \"The Cost of Knowledge\". By February 2012 this petition had been signed by over 5,000 academics,<ref name=Guardian/><ref name=Chronicle/> growing to over 17,000 by November 2018.<ref>{{cite web|title=thecostofknowledge.com|url=http://thecostofknowledge.com/|accessdate=12 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nElsevier disputed the claims, claiming that their prices are below the industry average, and stating that bundling is only one of several different options available to buy access to Elsevier journals.<ref name=Guardian/> The company also claimed that its profit margins are \"simply a consequence of the firm's efficient operation\".<ref name=Economist/> The academics replied that their work was funded by public money and thus should be freely available.\n\nOn 27 February 2012, Elsevier issued a statement on its website that declared that it has withdrawn support from the Research Works Act.<ref>{{cite web|title=Elsevier Backs Down as Boycott Grows|url=http://www.elsevier.com/about/issues-and-information/newmessagerwa|accessdate=25 August 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140911222130/http://www.elsevier.com/about/issues-and-information/newmessagerwa|archivedate=11 September 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Although the Cost of Knowledge movement was not mentioned, the statement indicated the hope that the move would \"help create a less heated and more productive climate\" for ongoing discussions with research funders. Hours after Elsevier's statement, the sponsors of the bill, [[United States House of Representatives|US House Representatives]] [[Darrell Issa]] and [[Carolyn Maloney]], issued a joint statement saying that they would not push the bill in Congress.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sponsors and Supporters Back Away from Research Works Act|url=http://www.sparc.arl.org/news/sponsors-and-supporters-back-away-research-works-act|accessdate=25 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Plan S===\nThe [[Plan S]] open-access initiative, which began in Europe and has since spread to some US research funding agencies would force researchers receiving some grants to publish in open access journals by 2020.<ref name=\"US_funders\">{{cite journal |last1=Noorden |first1=Richard Van |title=Wellcome and Gates join bold European open-access plan |journal=Nature |date=5 November 2018 |doi=10.1038/d41586-018-07300-5 |url=https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-018-07300-5 |accessdate=16 January 2019 |language=EN}}</ref> A spokesman for Elsevier said \"If you think that information should be free of charge, go to Wikipedia\".<ref>{{cite news |title=11 EU-landen besluiten: vanaf 2020 moet alle wetenschappelijke literatuur gratis beschikbaar zijn |first=Maarten |last=Keulemans |url= https://www.volkskrant.nl/nieuws-achtergrond/11-eu-landen-besluiten-vanaf-2020-moet-alle-wetenschappelijke-literatuur-gratis-beschikbaar-zijn~be002c39/ |newspaper=De Volkskrant |date=4 September 2018 |accessdate=25 September 2018 |language=Dutch |quote=Als je vindt dat informatie gratis moet zijn: ga naar Wikipedia.}}</ref> In September 2018 [[UBS]] advised to sell Elsevier (RELX) stocks, noting that Plan S could affect 5-10% of scientific funding and may force Elsevier to reduce pricing.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Elder |first1=Bryce |title=Stocks to watch: SSE, BAT, Gal\u00e1pagos, RELX, Telef\u00f3nica, RBS |url=https://www.ft.com/content/2a2064e2-b669-11e8-bbc3-ccd7de085ffe |accessdate=14 October 2018 |work=[[Financial Times]] |date=12 September 2018 }}</ref>\n\n== Relationship with academic institutions ==\n\n=== Finland ===\nIn 2015 Finnish research organizations paid a total of 27 million euros in subscription fees. Over one third of the total costs went to Elsevier. The information was revealed after successful court appeal following a denied request on the subscription fees, due to confidentiality clauses in contracts with the publishers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ropengov.github.io/r/2016/06/10/FOI/|title=Scientific journal subscription costs in Finland 2010-2015: a preliminary analysis|website=rOpenGov|access-date=2017-10-15}}</ref> Establishing of this fact lead to creation of tiedonhinta.fi petition demanding more reasonable pricing and open access to content signed by more than 2800 members of the research community.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://tiedonhinta.fi/en/english/|title=Tiedonhinta.fi|website=tiedonhinta.fi|language=en-GB|access-date=2017-10-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171015203433/http://tiedonhinta.fi/en/english/|archive-date=15 October 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> While deals with other publishers have been made, this was not the case for Elsevier, leading to the nodealnoreview.org boycott of the publisher signed more than 600 times.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nodealnoreview.org/|title=No deal, no review \u2013 #nodealnoreview|website=Nodealnoreview.org|language=en-US|access-date=2017-10-15}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018, it was confirmed that a deal had been reached between those concerned.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kansalliskirjasto.fi/en/news/finelib-and-elsevier-reach-agreement-for-subscription-access-and-open-access-publishing|title=FinELib and Elsevier Reach Agreement for Subscription Access and Open Access Publishing|last=Kukkonen|first=Suvi|date=2018-01-17|website=National Library|language=en|access-date=2018-01-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mostlyphysics.net/blog/2018/1/25/finland-takes-a-step-back-in-the-openness-of-academic-journal-pricing|title=Finland takes steps in the openness of academic journal pricing|author=Toma Susi|date=2018-01-25|newspaper=Mostly Physics|accessdate=2018-05-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite publication|author=Marie Farge|accessdate=2018-05-01|title=Transition vers l'Acc\u00e8s Libre: le pi\u00e8ge des accords globaux avec les \u00e9diteurs|url=https://blogs.mediapart.fr/edition/au-coeur-de-la-recherche/article/130418/transition-vers-l-acces-libre-le-piege-des-accords-globaux-avec-les-editeur|newspaper=Matematika|publisher=Club de Mediapart|language=fr}}</ref>\n\n=== France ===\nThe French [[Couperin (consortium)|Couperin consortium]] agreed in 2019 to a 4-year contract with Elsevier,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aefinfo.fr/assets/medias/documents/4/8/482545.pdf|title=Communiqu\u00e9 sur la n\u00e9gociation Elsevier|last=Consortium Couperin|date=2019-06-11}}</ref> despite criticism from the scientific community.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.lemonde.fr/sciences/article/2019/05/13/embrouilles-a-propos-de-l-acces-aux-revues-scientifiques_5461530_1650684.html|title=Embrouilles \u00e0 propos de l'acc\u00e8s aux revues scientifiques|date=2019-05-13|access-date=2019-08-26|language=fr}}</ref>\n\n===Germany===\nAlmost no academic institution in Germany is subscribed to Elsevier.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.projekt-deal.de/vertragskundigungen-elsevier-2018/|title=Vertragsk\u00fcndigungen Elsevier 2018|last=Haufe|first=Gottfried|date=20 November 2018|website=www.projekt-deal.de|access-date=6 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-019-00492-4|title=Thousands of scientists run up against Elsevier's paywall|last=Else|first=Holly|date=5 February 2019|journal=Nature|access-date=6 March 2019|doi=10.1038/d41586-019-00492-4}}</ref>\n\nGermany's DEAL project ([[Projekt DEAL]]) which includes over 60 major research institutions<!--consortium of state-funded universities and research organizations-->, has announced that all of its members are cancelling their contracts with Elsevier, effective 1 January 2017. The boycott is in response to Elsevier's refusal to adopt \"transparent business models\" to \"make publications more openly accessible\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Doctorow|first1=Cory|title=Germany-wide consortium of research libraries announce boycott of Elsevier journals over open access|url=https://boingboing.net/2016/12/15/germany-wide-consortium-of-res.html|publisher=Boing Boing|accessdate=27 December 2016|date=15 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=No full-text access to Elsevier journals to be expected from 1 January 2017 on|url=https://www.sub.uni-goettingen.de/en/news/details/voraussichtlich-keine-volltexte-von-zeitschriften-des-elsevier-verlags-ab-dem-112017/|publisher=G\u00f6ttingen State and University Library|accessdate=27 December 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161227132101/https://www.sub.uni-goettingen.de/en/news/details/voraussichtlich-keine-volltexte-von-zeitschriften-des-elsevier-verlags-ab-dem-112017/|archivedate=27 December 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=nature1/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lrk-bw.de/index.php/pressemitteilungen|title=Pressemitteilungen|website=Lrk-bw.de|language=de-de|access-date=2017-07-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.the-scientist.com/?articles.view/articleNo/49906/title/Major-German-Universities-Cancel-Elsevier-Contracts/|title=Major German Universities Cancel Elsevier Contracts|website=The Scientist|access-date=2017-07-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://www.sciencemag.org/news/2017/08/bold-open-access-push-germany-could-change-future-academic-publishing|title=A bold open-access push in Germany could change the future of academic publishing|date=2017-08-23|journal=Science|access-date=2017-08-24|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hrk.de/press/press-releases/press-release/meldung/researchers-resign-editorship-of-elsevier-journals-4237/|title=Researchers resign editorship of Elsevier journals|last=Conference|first=German Rectors'|access-date=2017-10-16|language=en}}</ref> Horst Hippler, spokesperson for the DEAL consortium states that \"taxpayers have a right to read what they are paying for\" and that \"publishers must understand that the route to open-access publishing at an affordable price is irreversible\".<ref name=nature1/> In July 2017, another 13 institutions announced that they would also be cancelling their subscriptions to Elsevier journals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.booksandpublishing.com.au/articles/2017/07/26/93682/german-universities-to-let-elsevier-contracts-lapse/|title=German universities to let Elsevier contracts lapse {{!}} Books+Publishing|website=Booksandpublishing.com.au|language=en-AU|access-date=2017-07-29}}</ref> In August 2017, at least 185 German institutions had cancelled their contracts with Elsevier.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.projekt-deal.de/vertragskundigungen-elsevier-2017/|title=Vertragsk\u00fcndigungen Elsevier 2017 \u2013 Projekt DEAL|website=Projekt-deal.de|language=en-US|access-date=2017-09-12}}</ref> In 2018, whilst negotiations were ongoing, around 200 German universities who cancelled their subscriptions to Elsevier journals were granted complimentary open access to them until this ended in July of the year.<ref name=\"matthews-2018\">{{cite news\n | last1 = Matthews | first1 = David\n | title = Elsevier maintains German access despite failure to strike deal\n | date = 4 January 2018\n | work = Times Higher Education (THE)\n | location = London, United Kingdom\n | issn = 0049-3929\n | url = https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/elsevier-maintains-german-access-despite-failure-strike-deal\n | access-date = 2018-01-05\n}}</ref><ref>[https://www.the-scientist.com/news-opinion/universities-in-germany-and-sweden-lose-access-to-elsevier-journals--64522 Universities in Germany and Sweden Lose Access to Elsevier Journals], DIANA KWON, The Scientist, July 19, 2018</ref><ref name=\"schiermeier-2018\">\n{{cite journal\n | last1 = Schiermeier | first1 = Quirin\n | title = Germany vs Elsevier: universities win temporary journal access after refusing to pay fees\n | date = 4 January 2018\n | journal = Nature News\n | volume =553\n | issue =7687\n | page =137\n | issn = 1476-4687\n | doi=10.1038/d41586-018-00093-7\n| pmid = 29323311\n | bibcode =2018Natur.553..137S\n | doi-access = free\n }}</ref>\n\nOn 19 December 2018 the [[Max Planck Society]] (MPS) announced that the existing subscription agreement with Elsevier would not be renewed after the expiration date of 31 December 2018. The Max Planck Society counts 14.000 scientists in 84 research institutes, publishing 12.000 articles each year.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mpdl.mpg.de/en/505|title=Max Planck Society discontinues agreement with Elsevier; stands firm with Projekt DEAL negotiations - MPDL}}</ref><ref name=\"mps20181219\">{{cite news |first1=Gary |last1=Price |url=https://www.infodocket.com/2018/12/19/max-planck-society-discontinues-agreement-with-elsevier-affirms-support-for-projekt-deal/ |title=Max Planck Society Discontinues Agreement with Elsevier. Affirms Support for Projekt Deal | work=infodocket.com Library Journal |date=19 December 2018 |accessdate=19 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Hungary===\nIn March 2018, the Hungarian ''Electronic Information Service National Programme'' entered negotiations on its 2019 Elsevier subscriptions, asking for a read-and-publish deal.<ref name=\"hungary_terminates\">{{cite web |first1= |title=Hungarian Consortium terminates negotiations with Elsevier |url=http://eisz.mtak.hu/index.php/en/283-hungarian-consortium-terminates-negotiations-with-elsevier.html |website=eisz.mtak.hu |accessdate=16 January 2019}}</ref> Negotiations were ended by the Hungarian consortium in December 2018, and the subscription was not renewed.<ref>{{cite news |last1=McKenzie |first1=Lindsay |title=Elsevier journal editors resign, start rival open-access journal |url=http://www.insidehighered.com/news/2019/01/14/elsevier-journal-editors-resign-start-rival-open-access-journal |accessdate=16 January 2019 |work=www.insidehighered.com |date=14 January 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Iran===\n\nIn 2013, Elsevier changed its policies in response to sanctions announced by the US [[Office of Foreign Assets Control]] that year. This included a request that all Elsevier journals avoid publishing papers by Iranian nationals which are employed by the Iranian government.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.issuesinmedicalethics.org/articles/scientific-sanctions-a-catastrophe-for-the-civilised-world/?galley=print|title=Scientific sanctions: A catastrophe for the civilized world|first=Behnam|last=Baghianimoghadam|publisher=Indian Journal of Medical Ethics|date=2014-02-09|accessdate=2018-12-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.farsnews.com/print.aspx?nn=13920814000991|title=Taylor & Francis group bans publication of articles by Iranian authors|publisher=Fars News|date=2013-11-05|accessdate=2018-12-25}}</ref> Elsevier executive Mark Seeley expressed regret on behalf of the company but did not announce an intention to challenge this interpretation of the law.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/trade-sanctions-against-iran-affect-publishers|first=Mark|last=Seeley|title=Trade sanctions against Iran affect publishers|publisher=Elsevier|date=2013-05-09|accessdate=2018-12-25}}</ref>\n\n=== Italy ===\n\nCRUI (association of Italian universities) sealed a 5-year-long deal for 2018\u20132022,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.crui.it/archivio-notizie/i-ricercatori-italiani-potranno-beneficiare-dell%E2%80%99accesso-continuo-al-database-sciencedirect-di-elsevie.html|title=I ricercatori italiani potranno beneficiare dell'accesso continuo al database ScienceDirect di Elsevier - CRUI - Conferenza dei Rettori delle Universit\u00e0 italiane}}</ref> despite protests from the scientific community, protests focused on aspects such as the lack of prevention of cost increases by means of the [[Double dipping (publishing)|double dipping]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.roars.it/online/svezia-italia-1-0-berlino-2018-italia-fanalino-di-coda-nellopen-science/|title=Svezia-Italia 1-0. Berlino 2018: Italia fanalino di coda nell'Open Science|date=2018-12-10|author=Paola Galimberti|newspaper=Roars: Returns on Academic Research}}</ref>\n\n===Netherlands===\nIn 2015 a consortium of all of Netherlands' 14 universities threatened to boycott Elsevier if it could not agree that articles by Dutch authors would be made open access and settled with the compromise of 30% of its Dutch papers becoming open access by 2018. Gerard Meijer, president of [[Radboud University]] in [[Nijmegen]] and lead negotiator on the Dutch side notes that \"it's not the 100% that I hoped for\".<ref name=nature1>{{cite journal|last1=Schiermeier|first1=Quirin|last2=Mega|first2=Emiliano Rodr\u00edguez|title=Scientists in Germany, Peru and Taiwan to lose access to Elsevier journals|journal=Nature|volume=541|issue=7635|pages=13|doi=10.1038/nature.2016.21223|pmid=28054621|bibcode=2017Natur.541...13S|year=2016|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Bohannon|first1=John|title=In unique deal, Elsevier agrees to make some papers by Dutch authors free|url=http://www.sciencemag.org/news/2015/12/unique-deal-elsevier-agrees-make-some-papers-dutch-authors-free|journal=Science|accessdate=27 December 2016|date=11 December 2015|doi=10.1126/science.aad7565|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Dutch Universities and Elsevier reach agreement in principle - Library UvA - University of Amsterdam|url=http://uba.uva.nl/en/news/news/content/2015/12/elsevier-deal.html|publisher=Universiteit van Amsterdam|accessdate=27 December 2016|date=12 October 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161227130822/http://uba.uva.nl/en/news/news/content/2015/12/elsevier-deal.html|archivedate=27 December 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/@SiccodeKnecht/how-elsevier-plans-to-sabotage-open-access-76fbd46593ae|title=How Elsevier plans to sabotage Open Access|date=2017-03-25|website=Medium|access-date=2017-03-26}}</ref>\n\n===Norway===\nIn March 2019, the Norwegian government on behalf of 44 institutions &mdash; universities, university colleges, research institutes and hospitals &mdash; decided to break negotiations on renewal of their subscription deal with Elsevier, because of disagreement regarding open access policy and Elsevier's unwillingness to reduce the cost of reading access.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.mynewsdesk.com/no/unit/pressreleases/norwegian-research-institutions-have-decided-not-to-renew-their-agreement-with-elsevier-2846284|title=Norwegian research institutions have decided not to renew their agreement with Elsevier|date=2019-03-12|website=UNIT|access-date=2019-03-12}}</ref>\n\n=== South Korea ===\nIn 2017, over 70 university libraries confirmed a \"contract boycott\" movement involving three publishers including Elsevier. As of January 2018, whilst negotiations remain underway, a decision will be made as to whether or not continue the participating libraries will continue the boycott.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.unn.net/news/articleView.html?idxno=183521|title=70\uc5ec\uac1c \ub300\ud559 \ub3c4\uc11c\uad00, \uc0c8\ud574 \uccab \ub0a0\ubd80\ud130 \uc77c\ubd80 \ub17c\ubb38 \ubabb \ubd10 - \ud55c\uad6d\ub300\ud559\uc2e0\ubb38|date=2017-12-29|access-date=2018-01-05|language=ko-KR}}</ref> It was subsequently confirmed that an agreement had been reached.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.sciencemag.org/news/2018/01/south-korean-universities-reach-agreement-elsevier-after-long-standoff|title=South Korean universities reach agreement with Elsevier after long standoff|date=2018-01-15|journal=Science|access-date=2018-01-16|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Sweden ===\nIn May 2018, the [[Bibsam Consortium]], which negotiates license agreements on behalf of all Swedish universities and research institutes, decided not to renew their contract with Elsevier,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/sweden-cancels-elsevier-contract-open-access-dispute-spreads|title=Sweden cancels Elsevier contract as open-access dispute spreads|date=16 May 2018|website=www.timeshighereducation.com}}</ref><ref name=sparc>{{citation |url=https://sparcopen.org/our-work/big-deal-cancellation-tracking/ |title=Big Deal Cancellation Tracking |work=Sparcopen.org |publisher=[[Scholarly Publishing and Academic Resources Coalition]] |location=US |accessdate= 30 June 2018 }}</ref> alleging that the publisher does not meet the demands of transition towards a more open access model, and referring to the rapidly increasing costs for publishing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kb.se/bibliotek/centrala-avtal/|title=Bibsamkonsortiet - Kungliga biblioteket|last=annwen|website=www.kb.se|language=SV|access-date=2018-05-31}}</ref> Swedish universities will still have access to articles published before 30 June 2018. Astrid S\u00f6derbergh Widding, Chairman of the Bibsam Consortium, said that \"the current system for scholarly communication must change and our only option is to cancel deals when they don't meet our demands for a sustainable transition to open access\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://openaccess.blogg.kb.se/2018/05/16/sweden-stands-up-for-open-access-cancels-agreement-with-elsevier/|title=Sweden stands up for open access \u2013 cancels agreement with Elsevier|date=2018-05-16|work=OpenAccess.se|access-date=2018-05-30|language=sv-SE}}</ref>\n\nSweden has a goal of open access by 2026.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://openaccess.blogg.kb.se/2018/05/16/sweden-stands-up-for-open-access-cancels-agreement-with-elsevier/|title=Sweden stands up for open access \u2013 cancels agreement with Elsevier|last=Wentzel|first=Annica|date=16 May 2018|website=openaccess.blogg.kb.se|access-date=6 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Taiwan===\nIn Taiwan more than 75% of universities, including the region's top 11 institutions, have joined a collective boycott against Elsevier. On 7 December 2016, the Taiwanese consortium, CONCERT, which represents more than 140 institutions, announced it would not renew its contract with Elsevier.<ref name=nature1/><ref>{{cite web|title=\u95dc\u65bcElsevier\u8cc7\u6599\u5eab\u5408\u7d04\u8ac7\u5224 CONCERT\u8072\u660e|url=https://concert.stpi.narl.org.tw/news/249|accessdate=27 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Taiwan Tech to Discontinue Subscription to Elsevier ScienceDirect Starting 2017 - NTUST Library|url=http://library.ntust.edu.tw/files/14-1025-58346,r1-1.php?Lang=en|accessdate=27 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/asia-advances-open-access-research_us_58dd0e6de4b0fa4c09598679|title=Asia Advances Open Access Research|last=Schmitt|first=Jason|date=2017-03-30|website=Huffington Post|language=en-US|access-date=2017-04-29}}</ref>\n\n===United States===\nIn March 2018, [[Florida State University]]'s faculty elected to cancel its $2 million subscription to a bundle of several journals. Starting in 2019 it will instead buy access to titles \u00e0 la carte.<ref name=sparc />\n\nIn February 2019, the [[University of California]] said it would terminate subscriptions \"in push for open access to publicly funded research.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.universityofcalifornia.edu/press-room/uc-terminates-subscriptions-worlds-largest-scientific-publisher-push-open-access-publicly|title=UC terminates subscriptions with world's largest scientific publisher in push for open access to publicly funded research|date=28 February 2019|website=www.universityofcalifornia.edu|access-date=6 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://phys.org/news/2019-03-university-california-terminates-subscriptions-elsevier.html|title=University of California terminates subscriptions to Elsevier|last=Yirka|first=Bob|date=4 March 2019|website=phys.org|access-date=6 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"AT 2019-03\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2019/03/uc-elsevier-publisher/583909/|title=The Real Cost of Knowledge|last=Zhang|first=Sarah|date=4 March 2019|work=[[The Atlantic]]|access-date=6 March 2019|language=en-US}}</ref> After months of negotiations over open access to research by UC researchers and prices for subscriptions to Elsevier journals, a press release by the UC Office of the President issued Thursday, 28 February 2019 stated \"Under Elsevier\u2019s proposed terms, the publisher would have charged UC authors large publishing fees on top of the university\u2019s multi-million dollar subscription, resulting in much greater cost to the university and much higher profits for Elsevier.\"<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.universityofcalifornia.edu/news/why-uc-split-publishing-giant-elsevier|title=Why UC split with publishing giant Elsevier|last=Kell|first=Gretchen|last2=Berkeley|first2=U. C.|date=2019-03-06|website=University of California|language=en|access-date=2019-06-12}}</ref> On July 10, 2019 Elsevier began restricting access to all new paywalled articles and approximately 5% of paywalled articles published before 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statnews.com/2019/07/10/university-of-california-loses-access-to-new-journal-articles-published-by-elsevier-after-research-access-fight|title=University of California loses access to new journal articles published by Elsevier after research access fight|website=statnews.com|language=en|access-date=2019-07-10|date=10 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2020, the [[University of North Carolina]] elected not to renew its bundled Elsevier package citing a failure \"to provide an affordable path\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Upcoming Elsevier Cancellations |url=https://library.unc.edu/2020/04/upcoming-elsevier-cancellations |publisher=University of North Carolina |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>. Rather than extend the license which was stated to cost $2.6 million annually, the university decided to continue subscribing to a smaller set of individual journals. The [[State University of New York]] Libraries Consortium also announced similar outcome.<ref>{{Cite news|publisher=Inside Highered|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/quicktakes/2020/04/13/suny-cancels-big-deal-elsevier|title=SUNY Cancels Big Deal With Elsevier|date=April 13, 2020|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|publisher=SUNY Libraries Consortium (SLC)|title=State University of New York Steps Away From the \u201cBig Deal\u201d with Elsevier|url=http://slcny.libguides.com/slc/elsevier2020update|date=April 7, 2020|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Dissemination of research ==\n\n=== Lobbying efforts against open access ===\nElsevier have been known to be involved in lobbying against [[open access]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.opensecrets.org/lobby/clientsum.php?id=D000067394&year=2017|title=Lobbying Spending Database - RELX Group, 2017|website=Opensecrets.org|language=en|access-date=2017-08-30}}</ref> These have included the likes of:\n* The [[Federal Research Public Access Act]] (FRPPA)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.taxpayeraccess.org/issues/frpaa/index.shtml|title=Federal Research Public Access Act (Alliance for Taxpayer Access)|website=Taxpayeraccess.org|language=en|access-date=2017-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.chronicle.com/article/Legislation-to-Bar/130949/|title=Legislation to Bar Public-Access Requirement on Federal Research Is Dead|date=2012-02-27|work=The Chronicle of Higher Education|access-date=2017-03-25}}</ref> \n* The [[Research Works Act]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thinkprogress.org/how-corporations-score-big-profits-by-limiting-access-to-publicly-funded-academic-research-fcee09671b22#.joxfvmi94|title=How Corporations Score Big Profits By Limiting Access To Publicly Funded Academic Research|date=2013-03-03|work=ThinkProgress|access-date=2017-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2012/02/15/the-dangerous-research-works-act/|title=The Dangerous \"Research Works Act\"|last=Contributor|website=TechCrunch|access-date=2017-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2016/01/elsevier-academic-publishing-petition/427059/|title=Academics Want You to Read Their Work for Free|last=Hu|first=Jane C.|work=The Atlantic|access-date=2017-03-25|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elsevier.com/about/company-information/policies/message-on-the-research-works-act|title=Message on the Research Works Act|last=Elsevier|website=Elsevier.com|language=en|access-date=2017-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/future_tense/2012/02/28/research_works_act_elsevier_and_politicians_back_down_from_open_access_threat_.html|title=Scientists' Victory Over the Research Works Act Is Like the SOPA Defeat|last=Kakaes|first=Konstantin|date=2012-02-28|work=Slate|access-date=2017-03-25|language=en-US|issn=1091-2339}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://boingboing.net/2012/02/28/elsevier-withdraws-support-fro.html|title=Elsevier withdraws support from Research Works Act, bill collapses|date=2012-02-28|website=Boing Boing|access-date=2017-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2012/jan/16/academic-publishers-enemies-science|title=Academic publishers have become the enemies of science|date=2012-01-16|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-03-26|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> \n* PRISM.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://scienceblogs.com/transcript/2007/01/27/elsevier-wiley-are-getting-pr/|title=Elsevier, Wiley are getting PR advice from Eric Dezenhall|work=Transcription and Translation|access-date=2017-03-25|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dyer|first=Owen|date=2007-02-03|title=Publishers hire PR heavyweight to defend themselves against open access|journal=BMJ: British Medical Journal|volume=334|issue=7587|pages=227|doi=10.1136/bmj.39112.439051.DB|issn=0959-8138|pmc=1790741|pmid=17272546}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.sciencemag.org/news/2013/06/scientific-publishers-offer-solution-white-houses-public-access-mandate|title=Scientific Publishers Offer Solution to White House's Public Access Mandate|date=2013-06-04|journal=Science|access-date=2017-03-25|language=en}}</ref> In the case of PRISM, the [[Association of American Publishers]] hired [[Eric Dezenhall]], the so-called \"Pit Bull Of Public Relations\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2006-04-16/the-pit-bull-of-public-relations|title=\"The Pit Bull Of Public Relations\" - Bloomberg|date=2006-04-17|work=Bloomberg.com|access-date=2017-03-25}}</ref>\n* [[Horizon 2020]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/muscle-from-brussels-as-open-access-gets-an-80bn-boost/419949.article|title=Muscle from Brussels as open access gets an \u20ac80bn boost|date=2012-05-17|work=Times Higher Education (THE)|access-date=2017-03-26|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gowers.wordpress.com/2012/05/17/horizon-2020-to-promote-open-access/|title=Horizon 2020 to promote open access|date=2012-05-17|website=Gowers's Weblog|access-date=2017-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.sciencemag.org/news/2012/05/horizon-2020-80-billion-battlefield-open-access|title=Horizon 2020: A \u20ac80 Billion Battlefield for Open Access|date=2012-05-24|journal=Science|access-date=2017-03-26|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2012/05/17/european-union-links-research-grants-open-access|title=European Union links research grants to open access|access-date=2017-03-26}}</ref>\n* [[Office of Science and Technology Policy]] (OSTP)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/inside-higher-ed-big-push-for-open-access/2002057.article|title=Inside Higher Ed: Big push for open access|date=2013-02-26|work=Times Higher Education (THE)|access-date=2017-03-26|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/elsevier-distances-itself-from-open-access-article/2004055.article|title=Elsevier distances itself from open-access article|date=2013-05-22|work=Times Higher Education (THE)|access-date=2017-03-26|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thinkprogress.org/how-corporations-score-big-profits-by-limiting-access-to-publicly-funded-academic-research-fcee09671b22#.u06x7x9zu|title=How Corporations Score Big Profits By Limiting Access To Publicly Funded Academic Research|date=2013-03-03|work=ThinkProgress|access-date=2017-03-26}}</ref>\n* The [[European Union]]'s [[Open science|Open Science]] Monitor was criticised after Elsevier were confirmed as a subcontractor.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20180402/09131239544/hated-science-publisher-elsevier-to-help-eu-monitor-open-science-including-open-access.shtml|title=Hated Science Publisher Elsevier To Help EU Monitor Open Science - Including Open Access|work=Techdirt.|access-date=2018-04-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Lykkja|first1=P\u00e5l Magnus|last2=Myklebust|first2=Jan Petter|title=Open science in the EU \u2013 Will the astroturfers take over?|url=http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=20180317044918836|website=University World News|accessdate=2018-04-13|date=17 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Selling open access articles ===\nIn 2014, 2015, 2016 and 2017,<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=2018-04-30|title=Hybrid open access is unreliable|url=http://rossmounce.co.uk/2017/02/20/hybrid-open-access-is-unreliable/|author=Ross Mounce|date=2017-02-20}}</ref> Elsevier was found to be selling some articles which should have been open access, but had been put behind a paywall.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/news/elsevier-bumps-on-road-to-open-access/2012238.article |title=Elsevier: bumps on road to open access |work=[[Times Higher Education]] |date=27 March 2014 |accessdate=9 March 2015 |last1=Jump |first1=Paul}}</ref> A related case occurred in 2015, when Elsevier charged for downloading an open access article from a journal published by [[John Wiley & Sons]]. However, it was not clear whether Elsevier was in violation of the license under which the article was made available on their website.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://creativecommons.org/weblog/entry/45175 |title=Are commercial publishers wrongly selling access to openly licensed scholarly articles? |work=Creative Commons News|date=13 March 2015 |accessdate=14 March 2015 |last1=Vollmer |first1=Timothy}}</ref>\n\n===Action against academics posting their own articles online===\n\nIn 2013, [[Digimarc]], a company representing Elsevier, told the [[University of Calgary]] to remove articles published by faculty authors on university web pages; although such [[self-archiving]] of academic articles may be legal under the [[fair dealing]] provisions in Canadian [[copyright law]],<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=2018-05-01|title=Elsevier Ramps Up Its War On Access To Knowledge|url=https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20131218/00393725601/elsevier-ramps-up-its-war-access-to-knowledge.shtml|newspaper=[[Techdirt]]|author= Mike Masnick}}</ref> the university complied. [[Harvard University]] and the [[University of California, Irvine]] also received [[Notice and take down|takedown notices]] for self-archived academic articles, a first for Harvard, according to [[Peter Suber]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Peterson|first1=Andrea|title=How one publisher is stopping academics from sharing their research|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/the-switch/wp/2013/12/19/how-one-publisher-is-stopping-academics-from-sharing-their-research/|accessdate=6 January 2015|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=19 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Masnick|first1=Mike|title=Elsevier Ramps Up Its War On Access To Knowledge|url=https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20131218/00393725601/elsevier-ramps-up-its-war-access-to-knowledge.shtml|accessdate=6 January 2015|work=[[Techdirt]]|date=20 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-switch/wp/2013/12/19/how-one-publisher-is-stopping-academics-from-sharing-their-research/|title=How one publisher is stopping academics from sharing their research|website=Washington Post|access-date=2017-03-26}}</ref>\n\nMonths after its acquisition of [[Academia.edu]] rival [[Mendeley]], Elsevier sent thousands of [[takedown notice]]s to Academia.edu, a practice that has since ceased following widespread complaint by academics, according to Academia.edu founder and chief executive Richard Price.<ref name=\"Parr2014\">{{cite journal|last1=Parr|first1=Chris|title=Sharing is a way of life for millions on Academia.edu|journal=Times Higher Education|date=12 June 2014|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/news/sharing-is-a-way-of-life-for-millions-on-academiaedu/2013839.article?nopaging=1 |accessdate=14 September 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Howard2013\">{{cite journal|last1=Howard|first1=Jennifer|title=Posting Your Latest Article? You Might Have to Take It Down|journal=The Chronicle of Higher Education|date=6 December 2013|url=http://chronicle.com/blogs/wiredcampus/posting-your-latest-article-you-might-have-to-take-it-down/48865|accessdate=14 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter Elsevier acquired the repository [[SSRN]] in May 2016 academics started complaining that some of their work has been removed without notice. The action was explained as a technical error.<ref>Mike Masnick [https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20160718/02211935003/just-as-open-competitor-to-elseviers-ssrn-launches-ssrn-accused-copyright-crackdown.shtml ''SSRN accused of copyright crackdown''], Techdirt.</ref>\n\n===Sci-Hub and LibGen lawsuit===\n\nIn 2015 Elsevier filed a lawsuit against the sites [[Sci-Hub]] and [[Library Genesis|LibGen]], which make copyright protected articles available for free. Elsevier also claimed illegal access to institutional accounts.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.stephenmclaughlin.net/2016/03/18/elsevier-v-sci-hub-on-the-docket/ |title=Elsevier v. Sci-Hub on the docket |first=Stephen Reid |last=McLaughlin |date=18 March 2016 |access-date=2016-06-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/simba-information-five-professional-publishing-news-events-of-2015-signal-times-are-a-changin-300194611.html|title = Simba Information: Five Professional Publishing News Events of 2015 Signal Times Are A-Changin'|date =17 December 2015 |accessdate = 28 June 2016 |website = PR Newswire }}</ref>\n\n===Rejection of the Initiative for Open Citations===\nAmong the major academic publishers, Elsevier alone declined to join the [[Initiative for Open Citations]]. In the context of the resignation of the ''[[Journal of Informetrics]]''' editorial board, Elsevier stated:<ref name=\"Elsevier\">{{cite web|url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/about-the-resignation-of-the-journal-of-informetrics-editorial-board|title=About the resignation of the Journal of Informetrics Editorial Board|date=15 January 2019|last = Reller|first = Tom|work=Elsevier Connect|accessdate=15 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote|Elsevier invests significantly in citation extraction technology. While these are made available to those who wish to license this data, Elsevier cannot make such a large corpus of data, to which it has added significant value, available for free.}}\n\n==Imprints==\n\nElsevier uses its [[Imprint (trade name)|imprint]]s (that is, [[Brand|brand names]] used in publishing) to market to different consumer segments. Many of the imprints have previously been the names of publishing companies that were purchased by Reed Elsevier.\n\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* [[Academic Press]]\n* Bailli\u00e8re Tindall\n* BC Decker\n* [[Butterworth\u2013Heinemann]]\n* CMP\n* [[Cell Press]]\n* [[Churchill Livingstone]]\n* Digital Press\n* Elsevier\n* [[Gulf Professional Publishing]]\n* GW Medical Publishing\n* Hanley & Belfus\n* [[Masson (publisher)|Masson]]\n* [[Medicine Publishing]]\n* [[Morgan Kaufmann Publishers]]\n* [[Mosby (publisher)|Mosby]]\n* Newnes\n* North-Holland Publishing Company\n* [[Pergamon Press]]\n* Pergamon Flexible Learning\n* [[Saunders (publisher)|Saunders]]\n* Syngress\n* Urban & Fischer\n* [[William Andrew (publisher)|William Andrew]]\n* [[Woodhead Publishing]] (including Chandos and Horwood)\n}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Netherlands|Companies|Books}}\n* [[List of Elsevier periodicals]]\n* [[2collab]], a free researcher collaboration tool launched by Elsevier in 2007 and discontinued in 2011\n* [[Sci-Hub]], a website providing free access to otherwise paywalled academic papers on a massive scale that is involved in a legal case with Elsevier\n{{clear}}\n\n== References ==\n=== Citations ===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |ref = harv |last = Groen |first = Frances K. |title = Access to medical knowledge : libraries, digitization, and the public good |year = 2007 |publisher = Scarecrow Press |location = Lanham, Mar. |isbn = 978-0-8108-52723 |page = 217 }}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Elsevier}}\n*{{Official website}}\n*[http://www.caat.org.uk/issues/arms-fairs/reed-elsevier/ Campaign success: Reed Elsevier sells international arms fairs]\n*{{cite web |title=Reed Elsevier Timeline |url=http://www.ulib.niu.edu/publishers/index.htm |work=The Academic Publishing Industry: A Story of Merger and Acquisition |author=Mary H. Munroe |year=2004 |via=Northern Illinois University |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141020153836/http://www.ulib.niu.edu/publishers/Holtzbrinck.htm |archivedate=20 October 2014 |df=dmy-all}}\n\n{{Reed Elsevier|state=collapsed}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Elsevier| ]]\n[[Category:1880 establishments in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Academic publishing companies]]\n[[Category:Bibliographic database providers]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Amsterdam]]\n[[Category:Multinational companies headquartered in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Publishing companies established in 1880]]\n[[Category:Publishing companies of the Netherlands]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Dutch publishing and analytics company}}\n{{other uses}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2016}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Elsevier\n| logo = \n| logo_caption = \n| image = Elsevier logo 2019.svg\n| image_size = 200px\n| image_caption = \n| trading_name = <!-- d/b/a/, doing business as - if different from legal name above -->\n| native_name = <!-- Company's name in home country language -->\n| native_name_lang = <!-- Use ISO 639-1 code, e.g. \"fr\" for French. If there is more than one native name, in different languages, enter those names using {{tl|lang}}, instead. -->\n| romanized_name = \n| former_name = \n| type = \n| traded_as = \n| industry = Publishing\n| genre = <!-- Only used with media and publishing companies -->\n| fate = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| foundation = {{start date and age|df=yes|1880}}\n| founder = \n| defunct = <!-- {{End date|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| location_city = [[Amsterdam]], [[Netherlands]]\n| location_country = \n| locations = <!-- Number of locations, stores, offices, etc. -->\n| area_served = \n| key_people = \n| products = \n| brands = \n| production = \n| services = \n| revenue = \u00a32.54 billion (2018)<ref name=\"RELX 2018 Report\"/>\n| operating_income = \n| net_income = <!-- Removed due to lack of verifiability -->\n| aum = <!-- Only used with financial services companies -->\n| assets = \n| equity = \n| owner = \n| num_employees = \n| parent = [[RELX]]\n| divisions = \n| subsid = \n| website = {{URL|https://www.elsevier.com/}}\n| footnotes = \n| intl = \n}}\n\n'''Elsevier''' ({{IPA-nl|\u02c8\u025blz\u0259vi\u02d0r|lang}}) is a [[Netherlands|Dutch]] [[publishing]] and [[analytics]] company specializing in scientific, technical, and medical content. It is a part of the [[RELX Group]], known until 2015 as Reed Elsevier.  Its products include journals such as ''[[The Lancet]]'' and ''[[Cell (journal)|Cell]]'', the [[ScienceDirect]] collection of electronic journals, the ''[[Trends (journals)|Trends]]'' and ''[[Current Opinion (Elsevier)|Current Opinion]]'' series of journals, the online citation database [[Scopus]], and the [[ClinicalKey]] search engine for clinicians. Elsevier's products also include digital tools for data-management, instruction, and assessment.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://scholarlykitchen.sspnet.org/2017/02/02/plum-goes-orange-elsevier-acquires-plum-analytics/|title = Plum Goes Orange \u2013 Elsevier Acquires Plum Analytics |date = 2017-02-02 }}</ref>\n\nElsevier publishes more than 470,000 articles annually in 2,500 journals.<ref name=\"RELX 2018 Report\">{{Cite web |url = https://www.relx.com/~/media/Files/R/RELX-Group/documents/reports/annual-reports/2018-annual-report.pdf |title = 2018 RELX Group Annual Report |date = March 2019 |accessdate =  |website = RELX Company Reports |publisher = RELX}}</ref> Its archives contain over 16 million documents and 30,000 e-books. Total yearly downloads amount to more than 1 billion.<ref name = \"RELX 2018 Report\" />\n\nElsevier's high operating profit margins (37% in 2018) and 950 million pounds in profits, often on publicly funded research works<ref name=\"RELX 2018 Report\" /><ref name=\"relx-results-press-release-2018\">\n{{cite press release\n | author = RELX\n | title = RELX \u2014 Results for the year to December 2018\n | date = 21 February 2019\n | publisher = RELX Group\n | location = London, United Kingdom and Amsterdam, The Netherlands\n | url = https://www.relx.com/~/media/Files/R/RELX-Group/documents/press-releases/2019/relx-results-2018-pressrelease.pdf\n | access-date = 2019-03-27\n}}  Adjusted operating margin for 2017 for the publishing division is 36.8% (p6).\n</ref> \nand its [[Copyright policies of academic publishers|copyright practices]] have subjected it to criticism by researchers.<ref name=boyc >{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/02/14/science/researchers-boycott-elsevier-journal-publisher.html|title=Mathematicians Organize Boycott of a Publisher | work=The New York Times | first=Thomas|last=Lin|date=13 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n==History==\n\n[[File:Elsevier.svg|200px|right|thumb|The original seal of the Elsevier family, used by Elsevier company as logo until 2019.]]\nElsevier was founded in 1880{{sfn|Groen|2007|p=217}} and adopted the name and logo from the Dutch publishing house [[House of Elzevir|Elzevir]] that was an inspiration and has no connection to the contemporary Elsevier.{{sfn|Groen|2007|p=217}} The Elzevir family operated as booksellers and publishers in the [[Netherlands]]; the founder, [[Lodewijk Elzevir]] (1542\u20131617), lived in [[Leiden]] and established the business in 1580. As company logo, Elsevier used the Elzevir family's printer's mark, a tree entwined with a vine and the words ''Non Solus'', which is Latin for \"not alone.\"<ref name=\"AT 2019-03\" /> Elsevier suggests that this logo represents \"the symbiotic relationship between publisher and scholar\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.facebook.com/notes/elsevier-india/interesting-fact-history-of-the-elsevier-logo/295913917111368/ |title=Interesting Fact - History of the Elsevier Logo |website=[[Facebook]] |access-date=2019-06-12}}</ref>\n\nThe expansion of Elsevier in the scientific field after 1945 was funded with the profits of the newsweekly ''[[Elsevier (magazine)|Elsevier]]'', which published its first issue on 27 October 1945. The weekly was an instant success and earned lots of money.<ref>Gerry van der List, ''Meer dan een weekblad. De geschiedenis van Elsevier''</ref> The weekly was a continuation, as is stated in its first issue, of the monthly Elsevier, which was founded in 1891 to promote the name of the publishing house and had to stop publication in December 1940 because of the [[Netherlands in World War II|Nazi occupation of the Netherlands]].\n\nIn 1947, Elsevier began publishing its first English-language journal, ''[[Biochimica et Biophysica Acta]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Reed Elsevier Timeline |url=http://www.ulib.niu.edu/publishers/ReedElsevier.htm |website=www.ulib.niu.edu |accessdate=13 September 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151030233859/http://www.ulib.niu.edu/publishers/ReedElsevier.htm |archivedate=30 October 2015 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Elsevier acquired [[Mendeley]], a UK company making software for managing and sharing research papers. Mendeley, previously an open platform for sharing of research, was greatly criticized for the acquisition, which users saw as acceding to the \"[[paywall]]\" approach to research literature. Mendeley's previously open sharing system now allows exchange of paywalled resources only within private groups.<ref name=fast>{{cite web |last1=Amirtha |first1=Tina |title=THE OPEN PUBLISHING REVOLUTION, NOW BEHIND A BILLION-DOLLAR PAYWALL |url=http://www.fastcompany.com/3042443/mendeley-elsevier-and-the-future-of-scholarly-publishing |website=Fast Company |accessdate=26 January 2016 |date=2015-04-17}}</ref> ''[[The New Yorker]]'' described Elsevier's reasons for buying Mendeley as two-fold: to acquire its user data, and to \"destroy or co\u00f6pt an [[Open science|open-science]] icon that threatens its [[business model]]\".<ref name=\"NewYorker\">{{cite magazine |url=https://www.newyorker.com/online/blogs/elements/2013/04/elsevier-mendeley-journals-science-software.html |title=When the Rebel Alliance Sells Out |first=David |last=Dobbs |magazine=[[The New Yorker]] |date=12 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn the first half of 2019, RELX reported the first slowdown in revenue growth for Elsevier in several years: 1% vs. an expectation of 2% and a typical growth of at least 4% in the previous 5 years.<ref>{{cite news|title=Relx falls short of growth expectations|newspaper=Financial Times|author=Patricia Nilsson|date=2019-07-25|via=[https://finance.yahoo.com/m/c84c5326-55c5-3f81-b51d-9d1f4b7806e7/relx-falls-short-of-growth.html Yahoo Finance]}}</ref>\n\n== Company statistics ==\n{{as of | 2018 | alt = During 2018}}, researchers submitted over 1.8 million [[research papers]] to Elsevier-based publications. Over 20,000 editors managed the peer review and selection of these papers, resulting in the publication of more than 470,000 articles in over 2,500 journals.<ref name=\"RELX 2018 Report\" /> Editors are generally unpaid volunteers who perform their duties alongside a full-time job in academic institutions,<ref>{{cite journal|first1=James A.|last1=Coleman|title=How to get published in English: Advice from the outgoing Editor-in-Chief |url= |journal=System |date=2014-01-03 |issn=0346-251X |pages=404\u2013411 |volume=42 |doi=10.1016/j.system.2014.01.004|quote=Remember that editors and reviewers are unpaid, and are undertaking their tasks voluntarily, in addition to a full-time job}}</ref> although exceptions have been reported.\n\nIn 2013, the five editorial groups Elsevier, [[Springer Science+Business Media|Springer]], [[Wiley-Blackwell]], [[Taylor & Francis]], and [[SAGE Publications]] published more than half of all academic papers in the peer-reviewed literature.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vocativ.com/culture/science/five-corporations-control-academic-publishing/|title=These Five Corporations Control Academic Publishing|date=10 June 2015|website=Vocativ.com|accessdate=31 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=The Oligopoly of Academic Publishers in the Digital Era|author1=Vincent Larivi\u00e8re |author2=Stefanie Haustein |author3=Philippe Mongeon |journal=PLoS ONE|volume=10|issue=6|year=2015|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0127502 |pmid=26061978 |pmc=4465327 |pages=e0127502|bibcode=2015PLoSO..1027502L}}</ref> At that time, Elsevier accounted for 16% of the world market in science, technology, and medical publishing.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Elsevier leads the business the internet could not kill |url = https://www.ft.com/content/93138f3e-87d6-11e5-90de-f44762bf9896|website = www.ft.com|accessdate = 7 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nElsevier breaks down its revenue sources by format and by geographic region. Approximately 44% of revenue by geography in 2018 derived from North America, 24% from Europe and the remaining 32% from the rest of the world. Approximately 83% of revenue by format came from electronic usage and 17% came from print.<ref name=\"RELX 2018 Report\" />\n\nElsevier employs more than 7,800 people in over 70 offices across 24 countries. Following the integration of its Science & Technology and Health Sciences divisions in 2012, Elsevier has operated under a traditional business structure with a single [[chief executive officer]] (CEO).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.infotoday.com/it/mar13/Brynko--Mobed--Elseviers-Next-Steps.shtml|title=Elsevier Next Steps|publisher=Information Today|accessdate=7 November 2016}}</ref> The CEO is Kumsal Bayazit,<ref name=\"ataglance\">{{cite web |url= https://www.elsevier.com/about/management/kumsal-bayazit |title=Kumsal Bayazit |website=Elsevier.com |accessdate=22 February 2019}}</ref> who was appointed on 15 February 2019.\n\nIn 2018, Elsevier accounted for 34% of the revenues of RELX group (\u20a42.538 billion of \u20a47.492 billion). In [[Earnings before interest and taxes|operating profits]], it represented 40% (\u20a4942 million of \u20a42,346 million). Adjusted operating profits (with constant currency) rose by 2% from 2017 to 2018.<ref name=\"RELX 2018 Report\" />\n\nIn 2018, Elsevier reported a mean 2017 [[gender pay gap]] of 29.1% for its UK workforce, while the median was 40.4%, more than twice the UK average and by far the worst figure recorded by any academic publisher in UK. Elsevier attributed the result to the under-representation of women in its senior ranks and the prevalence of men in its technical workforce.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2019-08-11|title=Elsevier reports 40% gender pay gap|url=https://www.thebookseller.com/news/elsevier-reports-40-gender-pay-gap-759606|website=www.thebookseller.com}}</ref>\n\n==Market model==\n\n===Products and services===\n\nProducts and services include electronic and print versions of journals, textbooks and [[reference work]]s, and cover the [[healthcare science|health]], life, physical and [[social science]]s.\n\nThe target markets are academic and government research institutions, corporate research labs, booksellers, librarians, scientific researchers, authors, editors, physicians, nurses, allied health professionals, medical and nursing students and schools, medical researchers, [[Pharmaceutical company|pharmaceutical companies]], hospitals, and research establishments. It publishes in 13 languages including English, German, French, Spanish, Italian, Portuguese, Polish, Japanese, Hindi, and Chinese.\n\nFlagship products and services include VirtualE, [[ScienceDirect]], [[Scopus]], [[Scirus]], [[EMBASE]], Engineering Village, [[Compendex]], [[Cell (journal)|Cell]], SciVal, Pure, and Analytical Services, The Consult series (FirstCONSULT, PathCONSULT, NursingCONSULT, MDConsult, StudentCONSULT), Virtual Clinical Excursions, and major reference works such as ''[[Gray's Anatomy]]'', ''Nelson Pediatrics'', ''[[Dorland's Illustrated Medical Dictionary]]'', ''[[Frank H. Netter|Netter]]'s Atlas of Human Anatomy'', and online versions of many journals<ref>[http://www.journals.elsevierhealth.com/ Health Advance]. Elsevier.</ref> including ''[[The Lancet]]''.\n\nScienceDirect is Elsevier's platform for online electronic access to its journals and over 6,000 e-books, reference works, book series, and handbooks. The articles are grouped in four main sections: ''Physical Sciences and Engineering'', ''Life Sciences'', ''Health Sciences'', and ''Social Sciences and Humanities''. For most articles on the website, abstracts are freely available; access to the full text of the article (in PDF, and also HTML for newer publications) often requires a subscription or pay-per-view purchase.\n\n===Research and information ecosystem===\n\n[[RELX Group]] has been [[RELX Group#Significant acquisitions|active]] in [[mergers and acquisitions]]. Elsevier has been joined by businesses which were either complementing or competing in the field of research and publishing and which reinforce its [[market power]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20170804/05454537924/elsevier-continues-to-build-monopoly-solution-all-aspects-scholarly-communication.shtml|title=Elsevier Continues To Build Its Monopoly Solution For All Aspects Of Scholarly Communication|last=|first=|date=2017-08-04|work=Techdirt|access-date=2018-10-17|author=Glyn Moody|author-link=Glyn Moody}}</ref> such as [[Mendeley]] (after the closure of [[2collab]]), [[SSRN]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20160517/13513134465/disappointing-elsevier-buys-open-access-academic-pre-publisher-ssrn.shtml|title=Disappointing: Elsevier Buys Open Access Academic Pre-Publisher SSRN|last=|first=|date=2016-05-17|work=Techdirt|access-date=2018-10-17|author=Mike Masnick|author-link=Mike Masnick}}</ref> [[bepress]]/[[Digital Commons (Elsevier)|Digital Commons]], [[PlumX]], Hivebench, Newsflo.<ref name=Herb2019/> These integrations are seen as a way to exert additional power on the research process.<ref name=Herb2019>{{cite journal |last1=Herb |first1=Ulrich|date=2019|title=Steering science through Output Indicators & Data Capitalism|doi=10.5281/zenodo.3333395|doi-access=free}}</ref> The group contains additional information and analytics companies, particularly [[LexisNexis]] and [[ThreatMetrix]].\n\n=== Conferences ===\nElsevier conducts conferences, exhibitions and workshops around the world, with over 50 conferences a year covering life sciences, physical sciences and engineering, social sciences, and health sciences.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.elsevier.com/events/conferences |title=Conferences |work=elsevier.com}}</ref>\n\n===Pricing===\n\nIn the 21st century, the subscription rates charged by the company for its journals have been criticized; some very large journals (with more than 5,000 articles) charge subscription prices as high as \u00a39,634, far above average,<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2011/aug/29/academic-publishers-murdoch-socialist|journal=Guardian|last=Monbiot|first=George|date=29 August 2011|title=Academic publishers make Murdoch look like a socialist}}</ref> and many British universities pay more than a million pounds to Elsevier annually.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://gowers.wordpress.com/2014/04/24/elsevier-journals-some-facts/ |title=Elsevier journals \u2014 some facts |work=Gowers's Weblog |date=24 April 2014 |accessdate=27 July 2014}}</ref> The company has been criticized not only by advocates of a switch to the [[Open access (publishing)|open-access]] publication model, but also by universities whose library budgets make it difficult for them to afford current journal prices.\n\nFor example, a resolution by [[Stanford University]]'s senate singled out Elsevier's journals as being \"disproportionately expensive compared to their educational and research value\", which librarians should consider dropping, and encouraged its faculty \"not to contribute articles or editorial or review efforts to publishers and journals that engage in exploitive or exorbitant pricing\".<ref>''[http://news-service.stanford.edu/news/2004/february25/minutes-225.html Faculty Senate minutes February 19 meeting]'' Stanford Report, 25 February 2004</ref> Similar guidelines and criticism of Elsevier's pricing policies have been passed by the [[University of California]], [[Harvard University]], and [[Duke University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.stanforddaily.com/?p=1013953 |title=Fac Sen addresses costly journals |work=The Stanford Daily |date=20 February 2004 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105040316/http://archive.stanforddaily.com/?p=1013953 |archivedate=5 November 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nIn July 2015, the [[Association of Universities in the Netherlands]] (VSNU) announced a plan to start boycotting Elsevier, which refused to negotiate on any [[Open Access]] policy for Dutch universities.<ref>Danny Kingsley [https://unlockingresearch.blog.lib.cam.ac.uk/?p=192 ''Dutch boycott of Elsevier \u2013 a game changer?''], University of Cambridge Office of Scholarly Communication</ref> In December 2016, [[Nature Publishing Group]] reported that academics in Germany, Peru and Taiwan are to lose access to Elsevier journals as negotiations had broken down with the publisher.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Schiermeier|first=Quirin|last2=Mega|first2=Emiliano Rodr\u00edguez|title=Scientists in Germany, Peru and Taiwan to lose access to Elsevier journals|journal=Nature|doi=10.1038/nature.2016.21223|pmid=28054621|volume=541|issue=7635|page=13|year=2016|bibcode=2017Natur.541...13S|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\nA complaint about Elsevier/RELX was made to the UK [[Competition and Markets Authority]] in December 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.martineve.com/2016/12/03/referring-elsevierrelx-to-the-competition-and-markets-authority/|title=Referring Elsevier/RELX to the Competition and Markets Authority|author=Martin Paul Eve|language=en-US|date=2016-12-14|author-link=Martin Paul Eve}}</ref> In October 2018, a competition complaint against Elsevier was filed with the European Commission, alleging anti-competitive practices stemming from Elsevier's confidential subscription agreements and market dominance.<ref name=\"competition_plaint\">{{cite news |last1=Kelly |first1=\u00c9anna |title=Researchers complain to Brussels over 'dominant position' of RELX Group in scientific publishing |url=https://sciencebusiness.net/framework-programmes/news/researchers-complain-brussels-over-dominant-position-relx-group |accessdate=16 January 2019 |work=sciencebusiness.net |date=2 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Shill review offer ===\n\nAccording to the [[BBC]], \"the firm [Elsevier] offered a \u00a317.25 Amazon voucher to academics who contributed to the textbook ''Clinical Psychology'' if they would go on [[Amazon.com]] and [[Barnes & Noble]] (a large US books retailer) and give it five stars.\" Elsevier said that \"encouraging interested parties to post book reviews isn't outside the norm in scholarly publishing, nor is it wrong to offer to nominally compensate people for their time. But in all instances the request should be unbiased, with no incentives for a positive review, and that's where this particular e-mail went too far\", and that it was a mistake by a marketing employee.<ref>Finlo Rohrer, \"[http://news.bbc.co.uk/go/pr/fr/-/2/hi/uk_news/magazine/8118577.stm The perils of five-star reviews]\", ''BBC News Magazine'', 25 June 2009.</ref>\n\n=== Blocking text mining research ===\nElsevier seeks to regulate [[text and data mining]] with private licenses,<ref name=nature527413f/> claiming that reading requires extra permission if automated and that the publisher holds copyright on [[threshold of originality|output of automated processes]]. The conflict on research and copyright policy has often resulted in researchers being blocked from their work.<ref>{{cite journal|first1=Richard|last1=Van Noorden|title=Elsevier opens its papers to text-mining|journal=Nature|date=2014-02-03|issn=0028-0836|pages=17|volume=506|issue=7486|doi=10.1038/506017a|pmid=24499898|doi-access=free|quote=\u201cIt was a legitimate criticism, that people sent text-mining requests in to publishers and they bounced around for a time without any response,\u201d admits Chris Shillum, vice-president of product management for platform and content at Elsevier.|bibcode=2014Natur.506...17V}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2015, Elsevier blocked a scientist from performing [[text mining]] research at scale on Elsevier papers, even though his institution already pays for access to Elsevier journal content.<ref name=nature527413f>{{cite journal|last1=Bloudoff-Indelicato|first1=Mollie|title=Text-mining block prompts online response|journal=Nature|date=20 November 2015|volume=527|issue=7579|pages=413|doi=10.1038/527413f|bibcode=2015Natur.527..413B}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Moody|first1=Glyn|title=Elsevier Says Downloading And Content-Mining Licensed Copies Of Research Papers 'Could Be Considered' Stealing|url=https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20151117/09383132839/elsevier-says-downloading-content-mining-licensed-copies-research-papers-could-be-considered-stealing.shtml|website=TechDirt|accessdate=21 November 2015}}</ref> The data were collected via parsing of downloaded PDF and HTML files,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Nuijten|first1=Mich\u00e8le B.|last2=Hartgerink|first2=Chris H. J.|last3=van Assen|first3=Marcel A. L. M.|last4=Epskamp|first4=Sacha|last5=Wicherts|first5=Jelte M.|title=The prevalence of statistical reporting errors in psychology (1985\u20132013)|journal=Behavior Research Methods|date=23 October 2015|volume=48|issue=4|pages=1205\u20131226|doi=10.3758/s13428-015-0664-2|pmid=26497820|pmc=5101263}}</ref> although Elsevier claimed that the method used was [[screenscraping]].<ref>A. Wise, 2015-11-17, [http://onsnetwork.org/chartgerink/2015/11/16/elsevier-stopped-me-doing-my-research/#comment-11 Elsevier stopped me doing my research - Comment by Dr Alicia Wise]</ref>\n\n== Academic practices ==\n\n=== \"Who's Afraid of Peer Review\" ===\n{{main|Who's Afraid of Peer Review?}}\n\nOne of Elsevier's journals was caught in the sting set up by [[John Bohannon]], published in [[Science (journal)|''Science'']], called \"Who's Afraid of Peer Review?\"<ref name=\"Bohannon2013\">{{Cite journal | last1 = Bohannon | first1 = John| authorlink1 = John Bohannon| title = Who's Afraid of Peer Review? | doi = 10.1126/science.342.6154.60 | journal = Science | volume = 342 | issue = 6154 | pages = 60\u201365 | year = 2013 | pmid =  24092725| pmc = |bibcode = 2013Sci...342...60B | doi-access = free }}</ref> The journal ''Drug Invention Today'' accepted an obviously bogus paper made up by Bohannon that should have been rejected by any good [[peer review]] system.<ref>{{cite news|author=Claire Shaw |url=https://www.theguardian.com/higher-education-network/2013/oct/04/open-access-journals-fake-paper |title=Hundreds of open access journals accept fake science paper |publisher=Theguardian.com |accessdate=26 December 2013|newspaper=The Guardian |date=2013-10-04 }}</ref> Instead, ''Drug Invention Today'' was among many [[open access]] journals that accepted the fake paper for publication. As of 2014, this journal had been transferred to a different publisher.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/journal/09757619|title=Drug Invention Today|work=sciencedirect.com}}</ref>\n\n=== Fake journals ===<!-- See talk section \"Elsevier published 6 fake journals\" for discussion of this heading\" -->\n{{further|Australasian Journal of Bone & Joint Medicine}}\n\nAt a 2009 court case in Australia where [[Merck & Co.]] was being sued by a user of [[Vioxx]], the plaintiff alleged that Merck had paid Elsevier to publish the ''[[Australasian Journal of Bone and Joint Medicine]]'', which had the appearance of being a [[peer-review]]ed [[academic journal]] but in fact contained only articles favourable to Merck drugs.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/story/0,25197,25311725-5013871,00.html |title=Doctors signed Merck's Vioxx studies |last=Rout |first=Milanda |date=9 April 2009 |work=[[The Australian]] |accessdate=4 May 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090506064629/http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/story/0,25197,25311725-5013871,00.html |archive-date=6 May 2009 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://classic.the-scientist.com/blog/display/55671/ |title=Merck published fake journal |last=Grant |first=Bob |date=30 April 2009 |work=[[The Scientist (magazine)|The Scientist]] |accessdate=4 May 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.theage.com.au/national/merck-accused-of-ghost-writing-medical-article-20090422-afdk.html?page=-1 |title=Merck accused of 'ghost writing' medical article |last=Hagan |first=Kate |date=23 April 2009 |work=[[The Age]] |accessdate=4 May 2009}}</ref><ref>Ben Goldacre, [https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2009/may/09/bad-science-medical-journals-companies \"The danger of drugs \u2026 and data\"], ''The Guardian'', 9 May 2009</ref> Merck described the journal as a \"complimentary publication,\" denied claims that articles within it were [[ghost writer|ghost written]] by Merck, and stated that the articles were all reprinted from peer-reviewed medical journals.<ref>{{cite press release|title=Merck Responds to Questions about the Australasian Journal of Bone and Joint Medicine Journal |date=30 April 2009 |url=http://www.merck.com/newsroom/vioxx/pdf/statement_20090430.pdf |publisher=[[Merck & Co.]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091231104929/http://merck.com/newsroom/vioxx/pdf/statement_20090430.pdf |archivedate=31 December 2009 |df=dmy }}</ref> In May 2009, Elsevier Health Sciences CEO Hansen released a statement regarding Australia-based sponsored journals, conceding that they were \"sponsored article compilation publications, on behalf of pharmaceutical clients, that were made to look like journals and lacked the proper disclosures.\" The statement acknowledged that it \"was an unacceptable practice.\"<ref>{{cite press release |title=Statement from Michael Hansen, CEO Of Elsevier's Health Sciences Division, regarding Australia based sponsored journal practices between 2000 and 2005 |url= http://www.elsevier.com/wps/find/authored_newsitem.cws_home/companynews05_01203 |publisher=Elsevier}}</ref> ''[[The Scientist (magazine)|The Scientist]]'' reported that, according to an Elsevier spokesperson, six sponsored publications \"were put out by their Australia office and bore the [[Excerpta Medica]] imprint from 2000 to 2005,\" namely the ''Australasian Journal of Bone and Joint Medicine'' (''Australas. J. Bone Joint Med.''), the ''Australasian Journal of General Practice'' (''Australas. J. Gen. Pract.''), the ''Australasian Journal of Neurology'' (''Australas. J. Neurol.''), the ''Australasian Journal of Cardiology'' (''Australas. J. Cardiol.''), the ''Australasian Journal of Clinical Pharmacy'' (''Australas. J. Clin. Pharm.''), and the ''Australasian Journal of Cardiovascular Medicine'' (''Australas. J. Cardiovasc. Med.'').<ref>{{cite news|first=Bob|last=Grant|title=Elsevier published 6 fake journals |url=http://www.the-scientist.com/blog/display/55679/ |date=7 May 2009 |work=[[The Scientist (magazine)|The Scientist]]}}</ref> Excerpta Medica was a \"strategic medical communications agency\" run by Elsevier, according to the imprint's web page.<ref>{{cite web|title=\"Excerpta Medica\", official webpage |url=http://www.excerptamedica.com/ |publisher=Elsevier}}</ref> In October 2010, Excerpta Medica was acquired by Adelphi Worldwide.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Excerpta Medica Joins Adelphi Worldwide\", press release |url= http://www.excerptamedica.com/?page=newsroom&item=301 |publisher=Elsevier}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Chaos, Solitons & Fractals'' ===\n\nThere was speculation<ref>{{cite journal |title=Self-publishing editor set to retire |doi=10.1038/456432a | volume=456 |issue=7221 | journal=Nature |pages=432 |pmid=19037282 | last1 = Schiermeier | first1 = Q|year=2008 |doi-access=free }}</ref> that the editor-in-chief of Elsevier journal ''Chaos, Solitons & Fractals'', [[Mohamed El Naschie]], misused his power to publish his own work without appropriate peer review. The journal had published 322 papers with El Naschie as author since 1993. The last issue of December 2008 featured five of his papers.<ref>''Chaos, Solitons & Fractals'' '''38'''(5), pp. 1229\u20131534 (December 2008)</ref> The controversy was covered extensively in blogs.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://scholarlykitchen.sspnet.org/?s=el+naschie| title= The Scholarly Kitchen}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://elnaschiewatch.blogspot.com/ |title= El Naschie Watch Blog |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101015195449/http://elnaschiewatch.blogspot.com/ |archivedate= 15 October 2010 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> The publisher announced in January 2009 that El Naschie had retired as editor-in-chief.<ref>{{Cite journal| doi = 10.1016/S0960-0779(09)00060-5| title = Publisher's note| year = 2009| journal = Chaos, Solitons & Fractals| volume = 39| pages = v\u2013|bibcode = 2009CSF....39D...5. }}</ref> {{As of|2011|11}} the co-Editors-in-Chief of the journal were Maurice Courbage and Paolo Grigolini.<ref>{{cite book |url= http://www.journals.elsevier.com/chaos-solitons-and-fractals/ |title= Chaos, Solitons and Fractals |date=November 2011}}</ref> In June 2011, El Naschie sued the journal ''[[Nature (journal)|Nature]]'' for libel, claiming that his reputation had been damaged by their November 2008 article about his retirement, which included statements that ''Nature'' had been unable to verify his claimed affiliations with certain international institutions.<ref name=\"BBC-CSF-libel\">{{cite news | title = Nature journal libel case begins | work = BBC News | last1 = Ghosh | first1 = Pallab | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-15697636 | accessdate = 11 November 2011 | date=11 November 2011}}</ref> The suit came to trial in November 2011 and was dismissed in July 2012, with the judge ruling that the article was \"substantially true\", contained \"honest comment\" and was \"the product of responsible journalism\". The judgement noted that El Naschie, who represented himself in court, had failed to provide any documentary evidence that his papers had been peer-reviewed.<ref name=\"Guardian2\">[https://www.theguardian.com/science/2012/jul/06/nature-libel-peer-review?newsfeed=true \"Nature libel verdict 'a victory for free speech'\"],''The Guardian'' 6 July 2012</ref> Judge [[Victoria Sharp]] also found \"reasonable and serious grounds\" for suspecting that El Naschie used a range of false names to defend his editorial practice in communications with ''Nature'', and described this behavior as \"curious\" and \"bizarre.\" <ref>{{cite journal\n| last       = Aron\n| first       = Jacob\n| date        = 6 July 2012\n| title       = Nature Publishing Group wins libel trial\n| journal     = New Scientist\n| issue       = 2873\n| url         = https://www.newscientist.com/article/dn22026-nature-publishing-group-wins-libel-trial.html\n| accessdate  = 14 July 2012\n}}</ref>\n\n===Plagiarism===\nSome Elsevier journals automatically screen submissions for plagiarism,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.elsevier.com/editors/perk/plagiarism-complaints/plagiarism-detection |title=Plagiarism detection |publisher=Elsevier}}</ref> but not all.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://retractionwatch.com/2018/08/23/elsevier-investigating-paper-on-solar-cells-that-appears-to-plagiarize-a-nature-journal/ |title=UPDATED: Elsevier retracts a paper on solar cells that appears to plagiarize a Nature journal. But the reason is\u2026odd |author=Ivan Oransky|date=2018-08-23}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Elsevier journal ''[[Procedia]]'' was reported to have published plagiarism by an Albanian politician in 2012.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://exit.al/en/2018/12/25/massive-plagiarism-scandal-hits-albanian-officials/ |title= Massive Plagiarism Scandal Hits Albanian Officials without Consequences |date=2018-12-25}}</ref>\n\n== Control of journals ==\n\n=== Resignation of editorial boards ===\nIn November 1999 the entire editorial board (50 persons) of the ''[[Journal of Logic Programming]]'' (founded in 1984 by [[John Alan Robinson|Alan Robinson]]) collectively resigned after 16 months of unsuccessful negotiations with Elsevier Press about the price of library subscriptions.<ref name=birman>[[Joan Birman]]. \"[http://www.ams.org/notices/200007/forum-birman.pdf Scientific publishing: a mathematician\u2019s viewpoint]\". ''[[Notices of the AMS]]''. Vol. 47, No. 7, August 2000</ref> The personnel created a new journal, ''Theory and Practice of Logic Programming'', with [[Cambridge University Press]] at a much lower price,<ref name=birman/> while Elsevier continued publication with a new editorial board and a slightly different name (the ''[[Journal of Logic and Algebraic Programming]]'').\n\nIn 2002, dissatisfaction at Elsevier's pricing policies caused the [[European Economic Association]] to terminate an agreement with Elsevier designating Elsevier's ''[[European Economic Review]]'' as the official journal of the association. The EEA launched a new journal, the ''[[Journal of the European Economic Association]]''.<ref>{{cite web|author=EffeDesign |url=http://www.eeassoc.org/index.php?page=14 |title=The EEA's journal: a brief history |publisher=Eeassoc.org |accessdate=26 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, the entire editorial board of the ''Journal of Algorithms'' resigned to start ''[[ACM Transactions on Algorithms]]'' with a different, lower-priced, not-for-profit publisher,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cs.colorado.edu/~hal/s.pdf |title=Changes at the Journal of Algorithms |accessdate=26 December 2013}}</ref> at the suggestion of ''Journal of Algorithms'' founder [[Donald Knuth]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www-cs-faculty.stanford.edu/~knuth/joalet.pdf | author=Donald Knuth| date=25 October 2003 | title=Letter to the editorial board of the Journal of Algorithms| accessdate=18 February 2008}}</ref> The ''Journal of Algorithms'' continued under Elsevier with a new editorial board until October 2009, when it was discontinued.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/journal/01966774 |title=Journal of Algorithms page at ScienceDirect |publisher=Sciencedirect.com |accessdate=26 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe same happened in 2005 to the ''International Journal of Solids and Structures'', whose editors resigned to start the ''[[Journal of Mechanics of Materials and Structures]]''. However, a new editorial board was quickly established and the journal continues in apparently unaltered form with editors D.A. Hills ([[Oxford University]]) and Stelios Kyriakides ([[University of Texas at Austin]]).<ref>{{cite web |title=Journal declarations of independence |url=http://oad.simmons.edu/oadwiki/Journal_declarations_of_independence#2005 |work=Open Access Directory |publisher=Simmons College |accessdate=23 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Kyriakides|first=Stelios|author2=Hills, David A.|title=Editorial|journal=International Journal of Solids and Structures|date=1 January 2006|volume=43|issue=1|page=1|doi=10.1016/j.ijsolstr.2005.11.001|accessdate=|quote=Charles R. Steele succeeded Herrmann as editor in chief in 1985 and served in that capacity until June 2005. During his 20-year tenure the journal grew both in size and in reputation, becoming one of the premier journals in the field. We have accepted an invitation to serve as editors of the journal as of October 1, 2005, being cognizant of the immense contributions, leadership, and high standards exercised by our two predecessors on the way to making IJSS the forum it is today.}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2006, the entire editorial board of the distinguished [[mathematical journal]] ''[[Topology (journal)|Topology]]'' handed in their resignation, again because of stalled negotiations with Elsevier to lower the subscription price.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://math.ucr.edu/home/baez/topology-letter.pdf | date=10 August 2006 | title=Resignation letter from the editors of Topology | accessdate=18 February 2008}}</ref> This board then launched the new ''[[Journal of Topology]]'' at a far lower price, under the auspices of the [[London Mathematical Society]].<ref>[http://www.lms.ac.uk/publications/jtop.html Journal of Topology] (pub. London Mathematical Society) {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070207123258/http://www.lms.ac.uk/publications/jtop.html |date=7 February 2007 }}</ref> After this mass resignation, ''[[Topology (journal)|Topology]]'' remained in circulation under a new editorial board until 2009, when the last issue was published.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://www.journals.elsevier.com/topology/|title=Topology|publisher=elsevier.com|accessdate=13 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/journal/00409383/48/2-4 |title=Topology page at ScienceDirect |publisher=Sciencedirect.com |accessdate=26 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe French [[\u00c9cole Normale Sup\u00e9rieure]] has stopped having Elsevier publish the journal ''[[Annales Scientifiques de l'\u00c9cole Normale Sup\u00e9rieure]]''<ref>[[John Baez]]: ''[http://math.ucr.edu/home/baez/journals.html What We Can Do About Science Journals]'' 13 August 2007</ref> (as of 2008).<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.elsevier.com/wps/find/journaldescription.cws_home/600714/description | title=Publisher's description of Annales Scientifiques de l'\u00c9cole Normale Sup\u00e9rieure | publisher=Elsevier | accessdate=18 February 2008 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080412014908/http://www.elsevier.com/wps/find/journaldescription.cws_home/600714/description | archivedate=12 April 2008 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe elevated pricing of field journals in economics, most of which are published by Elsevier, was one of the motivations that moved the [[American Economic Association]] to launch the ''[[American Economic Journal]]'' in 2009.<ref>David Glenn. \"American Economic Association Plans 4 New Journals\". '' The Chronicle of Higher Education''. 25 January 2008. Available online at [http://chronicle.com/article/American-Economic-Association/440 Chronicle.com]</ref>\n\nIn May 2015, [[Stephen Leeder]] was removed from his role as editor of the ''[[Medical Journal of Australia]]'' after its publisher decided to outsource the journal's production to Elsevier. As a consequence, all but one of the journal's editorial advisory committee members co-signed a letter of resignation.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/medical-journal-editor-sacked-and-editorial-committee-resigns-20150503-1myr8q.html | title=Medical journal editor sacked and editorial committee resigns | accessdate=18 May 2015| date=2015-05-03 }}</ref>\n\nIn October 2015, the entire editorial staff of the [[general linguistics]] journal ''[[Lingua (journal)|Lingua]]'' resigned in protest of Elsevier's unwillingness to agree to their terms of [[Fair Access to Science and Technology Research Act|Fair Open Access]]. Editor in Chief Johan Rooryck also announced that the Lingua staff would establish a new journal, ''[[Glossa (journal)|Glossa]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2015/11/02/editors-and-editorial-board-quit-top-linguistics-journal-protest-subscription-fees|title=Language of Protest|last=Jaschik|first=Scott|date=2 November 2015|work=Inside Higher Ed|access-date=18 January 2017|via=}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2019, the entire editorial board of Elsevier's ''[[Journal of Informetrics]]'' resigned over the open-access policies of its publisher and founded open-access journal called Quantitative Science Studies.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2019/01/14/elsevier-journal-editors-resign-start-rival-open-access-journal|title=Elsevier journal editors resign, start rival open-access journal}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2019/01/14/elsevier-journal-editors-resign-start-rival-open-access-journal|title=Elsevier journal editors resign, start rival open-access journal|website=www.insidehighered.com|language=en|access-date=2019-01-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Chawla|first=Dalmeet Singh|date=2019-01-14|title=Open-access row prompts editorial board of Elsevier journal to resign|url=http://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-019-00135-8|journal=Nature|language=EN|doi=10.1038/d41586-019-00135-8}}</ref>\n\n===\"The Cost of Knowledge\" boycott===\n{{Main|The Cost of Knowledge}}\n\nIn 2003 various university librarians began coordinating with each other to complain about Elsevier's \"[[Subscription business model|big deal]]\" journal bundling packages, in which the company offered a group of journal subscriptions to libraries at a certain rate, but in which librarians claimed there was no economical option to subscribe to only the popular journals at a rate comparable to the bundled rate.{{sfn|Groen|2007|p=177}} Librarians continued to discuss the implications of the pricing schemes, many feeling pressured into buying the Elsevier packages without other options.{{sfn|Groen|2007|p=180}}\n\nOn 21 January 2012, mathematician [[Timothy Gowers]] publicly announced he would boycott Elsevier, noting that others in the field have been doing so privately. The three reasons for the [[boycott]] are high subscription prices for individual journals, bundling subscriptions to journals of different value and importance, and Elsevier's support for [[Stop Online Piracy Act|SOPA]], [[PROTECT IP Act|PIPA]], and the [[Research Works Act]].<ref name=Guardian>{{cite news|last=Flood |first=Alison |url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2012/feb/02/academics-boycott-publisher-elsevier |title=Scientists sign petition to boycott academic publisher Elsevier |newspaper=The Guardian |date=2 February 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/65VHiGo2Z?url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/science/2012/feb/02/academics-boycott-publisher-elsevier |archivedate=16 February 2012 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref><ref name=Chronicle>{{cite news|last=Fischman |first=Josh |url=http://chronicle.com/blogs/wiredcampus/elsevier-publishing-boycott-gathers-steam-among-academics/35216 |title=Elsevier Publishing Boycott Gathers Steam Among Academics |newspaper=The Chronicle of Higher Education |date=30 January 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/65VIHYC2S?url=http://chronicle.com/blogs/wiredcampus/elsevier-publishing-boycott-gathers-steam-among-academics/35216 |archivedate=16 February 2012 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref><ref name=Economist>{{cite news|url=http://www.economist.com/node/21545974 |title=Scientific publishing: The price of information |work=The Economist |date=4 February 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/65VHxfKJ9?url=http://www.economist.com/node/21545974 |archivedate=16 February 2012 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nFollowing this, a petition advocating non-cooperation with Elsevier (that is, not submitting papers to Elsevier journals, not [[peer review|refereeing]] articles in Elsevier journals, and not participating in journal editorial boards), appeared on the site \"The Cost of Knowledge\". By February 2012 this petition had been signed by over 5,000 academics,<ref name=Guardian/><ref name=Chronicle/> growing to over 17,000 by November 2018.<ref>{{cite web|title=thecostofknowledge.com|url=http://thecostofknowledge.com/|accessdate=12 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nElsevier disputed the claims, claiming that their prices are below the industry average, and stating that bundling is only one of several different options available to buy access to Elsevier journals.<ref name=Guardian/> The company also claimed that its profit margins are \"simply a consequence of the firm's efficient operation\".<ref name=Economist/> The academics replied that their work was funded by public money and thus should be freely available.\n\nOn 27 February 2012, Elsevier issued a statement on its website that declared that it has withdrawn support from the Research Works Act.<ref>{{cite web|title=Elsevier Backs Down as Boycott Grows|url=http://www.elsevier.com/about/issues-and-information/newmessagerwa|accessdate=25 August 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140911222130/http://www.elsevier.com/about/issues-and-information/newmessagerwa|archivedate=11 September 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Although the Cost of Knowledge movement was not mentioned, the statement indicated the hope that the move would \"help create a less heated and more productive climate\" for ongoing discussions with research funders. Hours after Elsevier's statement, the sponsors of the bill, [[United States House of Representatives|US House Representatives]] [[Darrell Issa]] and [[Carolyn Maloney]], issued a joint statement saying that they would not push the bill in Congress.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sponsors and Supporters Back Away from Research Works Act|url=http://www.sparc.arl.org/news/sponsors-and-supporters-back-away-research-works-act|accessdate=25 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Plan S===\nThe [[Plan S]] open-access initiative, which began in Europe and has since spread to some US research funding agencies would force researchers receiving some grants to publish in open access journals by 2020.<ref name=\"US_funders\">{{cite journal |last1=Noorden |first1=Richard Van |title=Wellcome and Gates join bold European open-access plan |journal=Nature |date=5 November 2018 |doi=10.1038/d41586-018-07300-5 |url=https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-018-07300-5 |accessdate=16 January 2019 |language=EN}}</ref> A spokesman for Elsevier said \"If you think that information should be free of charge, go to Wikipedia\".<ref>{{cite news |title=11 EU-landen besluiten: vanaf 2020 moet alle wetenschappelijke literatuur gratis beschikbaar zijn |first=Maarten |last=Keulemans |url= https://www.volkskrant.nl/nieuws-achtergrond/11-eu-landen-besluiten-vanaf-2020-moet-alle-wetenschappelijke-literatuur-gratis-beschikbaar-zijn~be002c39/ |newspaper=De Volkskrant |date=4 September 2018 |accessdate=25 September 2018 |language=Dutch |quote=Als je vindt dat informatie gratis moet zijn: ga naar Wikipedia.}}</ref> In September 2018 [[UBS]] advised to sell Elsevier (RELX) stocks, noting that Plan S could affect 5-10% of scientific funding and may force Elsevier to reduce pricing.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Elder |first1=Bryce |title=Stocks to watch: SSE, BAT, Gal\u00e1pagos, RELX, Telef\u00f3nica, RBS |url=https://www.ft.com/content/2a2064e2-b669-11e8-bbc3-ccd7de085ffe |accessdate=14 October 2018 |work=[[Financial Times]] |date=12 September 2018 }}</ref>\n\n== Relationship with academic institutions ==\n\n=== Finland ===\nIn 2015 Finnish research organizations paid a total of 27 million euros in subscription fees. Over one third of the total costs went to Elsevier. The information was revealed after successful court appeal following a denied request on the subscription fees, due to confidentiality clauses in contracts with the publishers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ropengov.github.io/r/2016/06/10/FOI/|title=Scientific journal subscription costs in Finland 2010-2015: a preliminary analysis|website=rOpenGov|access-date=2017-10-15}}</ref> Establishing of this fact lead to creation of tiedonhinta.fi petition demanding more reasonable pricing and open access to content signed by more than 2800 members of the research community.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://tiedonhinta.fi/en/english/|title=Tiedonhinta.fi|website=tiedonhinta.fi|language=en-GB|access-date=2017-10-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171015203433/http://tiedonhinta.fi/en/english/|archive-date=15 October 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> While deals with other publishers have been made, this was not the case for Elsevier, leading to the nodealnoreview.org boycott of the publisher signed more than 600 times.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nodealnoreview.org/|title=No deal, no review \u2013 #nodealnoreview|website=Nodealnoreview.org|language=en-US|access-date=2017-10-15}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018, it was confirmed that a deal had been reached between those concerned.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kansalliskirjasto.fi/en/news/finelib-and-elsevier-reach-agreement-for-subscription-access-and-open-access-publishing|title=FinELib and Elsevier Reach Agreement for Subscription Access and Open Access Publishing|last=Kukkonen|first=Suvi|date=2018-01-17|website=National Library|language=en|access-date=2018-01-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mostlyphysics.net/blog/2018/1/25/finland-takes-a-step-back-in-the-openness-of-academic-journal-pricing|title=Finland takes steps in the openness of academic journal pricing|author=Toma Susi|date=2018-01-25|newspaper=Mostly Physics|accessdate=2018-05-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite publication|author=Marie Farge|accessdate=2018-05-01|title=Transition vers l'Acc\u00e8s Libre: le pi\u00e8ge des accords globaux avec les \u00e9diteurs|url=https://blogs.mediapart.fr/edition/au-coeur-de-la-recherche/article/130418/transition-vers-l-acces-libre-le-piege-des-accords-globaux-avec-les-editeur|newspaper=Matematika|publisher=Club de Mediapart|language=fr}}</ref>\n\n=== France ===\nThe French [[Couperin (consortium)|Couperin consortium]] agreed in 2019 to a 4-year contract with Elsevier,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aefinfo.fr/assets/medias/documents/4/8/482545.pdf|title=Communiqu\u00e9 sur la n\u00e9gociation Elsevier|last=Consortium Couperin|date=2019-06-11}}</ref> despite criticism from the scientific community.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.lemonde.fr/sciences/article/2019/05/13/embrouilles-a-propos-de-l-acces-aux-revues-scientifiques_5461530_1650684.html|title=Embrouilles \u00e0 propos de l'acc\u00e8s aux revues scientifiques|date=2019-05-13|access-date=2019-08-26|language=fr}}</ref>\n\n===Germany===\nAlmost no academic institution in Germany is subscribed to Elsevier.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.projekt-deal.de/vertragskundigungen-elsevier-2018/|title=Vertragsk\u00fcndigungen Elsevier 2018|last=Haufe|first=Gottfried|date=20 November 2018|website=www.projekt-deal.de|access-date=6 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-019-00492-4|title=Thousands of scientists run up against Elsevier's paywall|last=Else|first=Holly|date=5 February 2019|journal=Nature|access-date=6 March 2019|doi=10.1038/d41586-019-00492-4}}</ref>\n\nGermany's DEAL project ([[Projekt DEAL]]) which includes over 60 major research institutions<!--consortium of state-funded universities and research organizations-->, has announced that all of its members are cancelling their contracts with Elsevier, effective 1 January 2017. The boycott is in response to Elsevier's refusal to adopt \"transparent business models\" to \"make publications more openly accessible\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Doctorow|first1=Cory|title=Germany-wide consortium of research libraries announce boycott of Elsevier journals over open access|url=https://boingboing.net/2016/12/15/germany-wide-consortium-of-res.html|publisher=Boing Boing|accessdate=27 December 2016|date=15 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=No full-text access to Elsevier journals to be expected from 1 January 2017 on|url=https://www.sub.uni-goettingen.de/en/news/details/voraussichtlich-keine-volltexte-von-zeitschriften-des-elsevier-verlags-ab-dem-112017/|publisher=G\u00f6ttingen State and University Library|accessdate=27 December 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161227132101/https://www.sub.uni-goettingen.de/en/news/details/voraussichtlich-keine-volltexte-von-zeitschriften-des-elsevier-verlags-ab-dem-112017/|archivedate=27 December 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=nature1/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lrk-bw.de/index.php/pressemitteilungen|title=Pressemitteilungen|website=Lrk-bw.de|language=de-de|access-date=2017-07-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.the-scientist.com/?articles.view/articleNo/49906/title/Major-German-Universities-Cancel-Elsevier-Contracts/|title=Major German Universities Cancel Elsevier Contracts|website=The Scientist|access-date=2017-07-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://www.sciencemag.org/news/2017/08/bold-open-access-push-germany-could-change-future-academic-publishing|title=A bold open-access push in Germany could change the future of academic publishing|date=2017-08-23|journal=Science|access-date=2017-08-24|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hrk.de/press/press-releases/press-release/meldung/researchers-resign-editorship-of-elsevier-journals-4237/|title=Researchers resign editorship of Elsevier journals|last=Conference|first=German Rectors'|access-date=2017-10-16|language=en}}</ref> Horst Hippler, spokesperson for the DEAL consortium states that \"taxpayers have a right to read what they are paying for\" and that \"publishers must understand that the route to open-access publishing at an affordable price is irreversible\".<ref name=nature1/> In July 2017, another 13 institutions announced that they would also be cancelling their subscriptions to Elsevier journals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.booksandpublishing.com.au/articles/2017/07/26/93682/german-universities-to-let-elsevier-contracts-lapse/|title=German universities to let Elsevier contracts lapse {{!}} Books+Publishing|website=Booksandpublishing.com.au|language=en-AU|access-date=2017-07-29}}</ref> In August 2017, at least 185 German institutions had cancelled their contracts with Elsevier.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.projekt-deal.de/vertragskundigungen-elsevier-2017/|title=Vertragsk\u00fcndigungen Elsevier 2017 \u2013 Projekt DEAL|website=Projekt-deal.de|language=en-US|access-date=2017-09-12}}</ref> In 2018, whilst negotiations were ongoing, around 200 German universities who cancelled their subscriptions to Elsevier journals were granted complimentary open access to them until this ended in July of the year.<ref name=\"matthews-2018\">{{cite news\n | last1 = Matthews | first1 = David\n | title = Elsevier maintains German access despite failure to strike deal\n | date = 4 January 2018\n | work = Times Higher Education (THE)\n | location = London, United Kingdom\n | issn = 0049-3929\n | url = https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/elsevier-maintains-german-access-despite-failure-strike-deal\n | access-date = 2018-01-05\n}}</ref><ref>[https://www.the-scientist.com/news-opinion/universities-in-germany-and-sweden-lose-access-to-elsevier-journals--64522 Universities in Germany and Sweden Lose Access to Elsevier Journals], DIANA KWON, The Scientist, July 19, 2018</ref><ref name=\"schiermeier-2018\">\n{{cite journal\n | last1 = Schiermeier | first1 = Quirin\n | title = Germany vs Elsevier: universities win temporary journal access after refusing to pay fees\n | date = 4 January 2018\n | journal = Nature News\n | volume =553\n | issue =7687\n | page =137\n | issn = 1476-4687\n | doi=10.1038/d41586-018-00093-7\n| pmid = 29323311\n | bibcode =2018Natur.553..137S\n | doi-access = free\n }}</ref>\n\nOn 19 December 2018 the [[Max Planck Society]] (MPS) announced that the existing subscription agreement with Elsevier would not be renewed after the expiration date of 31 December 2018. The Max Planck Society counts 14.000 scientists in 84 research institutes, publishing 12.000 articles each year.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mpdl.mpg.de/en/505|title=Max Planck Society discontinues agreement with Elsevier; stands firm with Projekt DEAL negotiations - MPDL}}</ref><ref name=\"mps20181219\">{{cite news |first1=Gary |last1=Price |url=https://www.infodocket.com/2018/12/19/max-planck-society-discontinues-agreement-with-elsevier-affirms-support-for-projekt-deal/ |title=Max Planck Society Discontinues Agreement with Elsevier. Affirms Support for Projekt Deal | work=infodocket.com Library Journal |date=19 December 2018 |accessdate=19 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Hungary===\nIn March 2018, the Hungarian ''Electronic Information Service National Programme'' entered negotiations on its 2019 Elsevier subscriptions, asking for a read-and-publish deal.<ref name=\"hungary_terminates\">{{cite web |first1= |title=Hungarian Consortium terminates negotiations with Elsevier |url=http://eisz.mtak.hu/index.php/en/283-hungarian-consortium-terminates-negotiations-with-elsevier.html |website=eisz.mtak.hu |accessdate=16 January 2019}}</ref> Negotiations were ended by the Hungarian consortium in December 2018, and the subscription was not renewed.<ref>{{cite news |last1=McKenzie |first1=Lindsay |title=Elsevier journal editors resign, start rival open-access journal |url=http://www.insidehighered.com/news/2019/01/14/elsevier-journal-editors-resign-start-rival-open-access-journal |accessdate=16 January 2019 |work=www.insidehighered.com |date=14 January 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Iran===\n\nIn 2013, Elsevier changed its policies in response to sanctions announced by the US [[Office of Foreign Assets Control]] that year. This included a request that all Elsevier journals avoid publishing papers by Iranian nationals which are employed by the Iranian government.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.issuesinmedicalethics.org/articles/scientific-sanctions-a-catastrophe-for-the-civilised-world/?galley=print|title=Scientific sanctions: A catastrophe for the civilized world|first=Behnam|last=Baghianimoghadam|publisher=Indian Journal of Medical Ethics|date=2014-02-09|accessdate=2018-12-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.farsnews.com/print.aspx?nn=13920814000991|title=Taylor & Francis group bans publication of articles by Iranian authors|publisher=Fars News|date=2013-11-05|accessdate=2018-12-25}}</ref> Elsevier executive Mark Seeley expressed regret on behalf of the company but did not announce an intention to challenge this interpretation of the law.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/trade-sanctions-against-iran-affect-publishers|first=Mark|last=Seeley|title=Trade sanctions against Iran affect publishers|publisher=Elsevier|date=2013-05-09|accessdate=2018-12-25}}</ref>\n\n=== Italy ===\n\nCRUI (association of Italian universities) sealed a 5-year-long deal for 2018\u20132022,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.crui.it/archivio-notizie/i-ricercatori-italiani-potranno-beneficiare-dell%E2%80%99accesso-continuo-al-database-sciencedirect-di-elsevie.html|title=I ricercatori italiani potranno beneficiare dell'accesso continuo al database ScienceDirect di Elsevier - CRUI - Conferenza dei Rettori delle Universit\u00e0 italiane}}</ref> despite protests from the scientific community, protests focused on aspects such as the lack of prevention of cost increases by means of the [[Double dipping (publishing)|double dipping]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.roars.it/online/svezia-italia-1-0-berlino-2018-italia-fanalino-di-coda-nellopen-science/|title=Svezia-Italia 1-0. Berlino 2018: Italia fanalino di coda nell'Open Science|date=2018-12-10|author=Paola Galimberti|newspaper=Roars: Returns on Academic Research}}</ref>\n\n===Netherlands===\nIn 2015 a consortium of all of Netherlands' 14 universities threatened to boycott Elsevier if it could not agree that articles by Dutch authors would be made open access and settled with the compromise of 30% of its Dutch papers becoming open access by 2018. Gerard Meijer, president of [[Radboud University]] in [[Nijmegen]] and lead negotiator on the Dutch side notes that \"it's not the 100% that I hoped for\".<ref name=nature1>{{cite journal|last1=Schiermeier|first1=Quirin|last2=Mega|first2=Emiliano Rodr\u00edguez|title=Scientists in Germany, Peru and Taiwan to lose access to Elsevier journals|journal=Nature|volume=541|issue=7635|pages=13|doi=10.1038/nature.2016.21223|pmid=28054621|bibcode=2017Natur.541...13S|year=2016|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Bohannon|first1=John|title=In unique deal, Elsevier agrees to make some papers by Dutch authors free|url=http://www.sciencemag.org/news/2015/12/unique-deal-elsevier-agrees-make-some-papers-dutch-authors-free|journal=Science|accessdate=27 December 2016|date=11 December 2015|doi=10.1126/science.aad7565|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Dutch Universities and Elsevier reach agreement in principle - Library UvA - University of Amsterdam|url=http://uba.uva.nl/en/news/news/content/2015/12/elsevier-deal.html|publisher=Universiteit van Amsterdam|accessdate=27 December 2016|date=12 October 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161227130822/http://uba.uva.nl/en/news/news/content/2015/12/elsevier-deal.html|archivedate=27 December 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/@SiccodeKnecht/how-elsevier-plans-to-sabotage-open-access-76fbd46593ae|title=How Elsevier plans to sabotage Open Access|date=2017-03-25|website=Medium|access-date=2017-03-26}}</ref>\n\n===Norway===\nIn March 2019, the Norwegian government on behalf of 44 institutions &mdash; universities, university colleges, research institutes and hospitals &mdash; decided to break negotiations on renewal of their subscription deal with Elsevier, because of disagreement regarding open access policy and Elsevier's unwillingness to reduce the cost of reading access.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.mynewsdesk.com/no/unit/pressreleases/norwegian-research-institutions-have-decided-not-to-renew-their-agreement-with-elsevier-2846284|title=Norwegian research institutions have decided not to renew their agreement with Elsevier|date=2019-03-12|website=UNIT|access-date=2019-03-12}}</ref>\n\n=== South Korea ===\nIn 2017, over 70 university libraries confirmed a \"contract boycott\" movement involving three publishers including Elsevier. As of January 2018, whilst negotiations remain underway, a decision will be made as to whether or not continue the participating libraries will continue the boycott.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.unn.net/news/articleView.html?idxno=183521|title=70\uc5ec\uac1c \ub300\ud559 \ub3c4\uc11c\uad00, \uc0c8\ud574 \uccab \ub0a0\ubd80\ud130 \uc77c\ubd80 \ub17c\ubb38 \ubabb \ubd10 - \ud55c\uad6d\ub300\ud559\uc2e0\ubb38|date=2017-12-29|access-date=2018-01-05|language=ko-KR}}</ref> It was subsequently confirmed that an agreement had been reached.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.sciencemag.org/news/2018/01/south-korean-universities-reach-agreement-elsevier-after-long-standoff|title=South Korean universities reach agreement with Elsevier after long standoff|date=2018-01-15|journal=Science|access-date=2018-01-16|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Sweden ===\nIn May 2018, the [[Bibsam Consortium]], which negotiates license agreements on behalf of all Swedish universities and research institutes, decided not to renew their contract with Elsevier,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/sweden-cancels-elsevier-contract-open-access-dispute-spreads|title=Sweden cancels Elsevier contract as open-access dispute spreads|date=16 May 2018|website=www.timeshighereducation.com}}</ref><ref name=sparc>{{citation |url=https://sparcopen.org/our-work/big-deal-cancellation-tracking/ |title=Big Deal Cancellation Tracking |work=Sparcopen.org |publisher=[[Scholarly Publishing and Academic Resources Coalition]] |location=US |accessdate= 30 June 2018 }}</ref> alleging that the publisher does not meet the demands of transition towards a more open access model, and referring to the rapidly increasing costs for publishing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kb.se/bibliotek/centrala-avtal/|title=Bibsamkonsortiet - Kungliga biblioteket|last=annwen|website=www.kb.se|language=SV|access-date=2018-05-31}}</ref> Swedish universities will still have access to articles published before 30 June 2018. Astrid S\u00f6derbergh Widding, Chairman of the Bibsam Consortium, said that \"the current system for scholarly communication must change and our only option is to cancel deals when they don't meet our demands for a sustainable transition to open access\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://openaccess.blogg.kb.se/2018/05/16/sweden-stands-up-for-open-access-cancels-agreement-with-elsevier/|title=Sweden stands up for open access \u2013 cancels agreement with Elsevier|date=2018-05-16|work=OpenAccess.se|access-date=2018-05-30|language=sv-SE}}</ref>\n\nSweden has a goal of open access by 2026.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://openaccess.blogg.kb.se/2018/05/16/sweden-stands-up-for-open-access-cancels-agreement-with-elsevier/|title=Sweden stands up for open access \u2013 cancels agreement with Elsevier|last=Wentzel|first=Annica|date=16 May 2018|website=openaccess.blogg.kb.se|access-date=6 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Taiwan===\nIn Taiwan more than 75% of universities, including the region's top 11 institutions, have joined a collective boycott against Elsevier. On 7 December 2016, the Taiwanese consortium, CONCERT, which represents more than 140 institutions, announced it would not renew its contract with Elsevier.<ref name=nature1/><ref>{{cite web|title=\u95dc\u65bcElsevier\u8cc7\u6599\u5eab\u5408\u7d04\u8ac7\u5224 CONCERT\u8072\u660e|url=https://concert.stpi.narl.org.tw/news/249|accessdate=27 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Taiwan Tech to Discontinue Subscription to Elsevier ScienceDirect Starting 2017 - NTUST Library|url=http://library.ntust.edu.tw/files/14-1025-58346,r1-1.php?Lang=en|accessdate=27 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/asia-advances-open-access-research_us_58dd0e6de4b0fa4c09598679|title=Asia Advances Open Access Research|last=Schmitt|first=Jason|date=2017-03-30|website=Huffington Post|language=en-US|access-date=2017-04-29}}</ref>\n\n===United States===\nIn March 2018, [[Florida State University]]'s faculty elected to cancel its $2 million subscription to a bundle of several journals. Starting in 2019 it will instead buy access to titles \u00e0 la carte.<ref name=sparc />\n\nIn February 2019, the [[University of California]] said it would terminate subscriptions \"in push for open access to publicly funded research.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.universityofcalifornia.edu/press-room/uc-terminates-subscriptions-worlds-largest-scientific-publisher-push-open-access-publicly|title=UC terminates subscriptions with world's largest scientific publisher in push for open access to publicly funded research|date=28 February 2019|website=www.universityofcalifornia.edu|access-date=6 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://phys.org/news/2019-03-university-california-terminates-subscriptions-elsevier.html|title=University of California terminates subscriptions to Elsevier|last=Yirka|first=Bob|date=4 March 2019|website=phys.org|access-date=6 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"AT 2019-03\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2019/03/uc-elsevier-publisher/583909/|title=The Real Cost of Knowledge|last=Zhang|first=Sarah|date=4 March 2019|work=[[The Atlantic]]|access-date=6 March 2019|language=en-US}}</ref> After months of negotiations over open access to research by UC researchers and prices for subscriptions to Elsevier journals, a press release by the UC Office of the President issued Thursday, 28 February 2019 stated \"Under Elsevier\u2019s proposed terms, the publisher would have charged UC authors large publishing fees on top of the university\u2019s multi-million dollar subscription, resulting in much greater cost to the university and much higher profits for Elsevier.\"<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.universityofcalifornia.edu/news/why-uc-split-publishing-giant-elsevier|title=Why UC split with publishing giant Elsevier|last=Kell|first=Gretchen|last2=Berkeley|first2=U. C.|date=2019-03-06|website=University of California|language=en|access-date=2019-06-12}}</ref> On July 10, 2019 Elsevier began restricting access to all new paywalled articles and approximately 5% of paywalled articles published before 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statnews.com/2019/07/10/university-of-california-loses-access-to-new-journal-articles-published-by-elsevier-after-research-access-fight|title=University of California loses access to new journal articles published by Elsevier after research access fight|website=statnews.com|language=en|access-date=2019-07-10|date=10 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2020, the [[University of North Carolina]] elected not to renew its bundled Elsevier package citing a failure \"to provide an affordable path\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Upcoming Elsevier Cancellations |url=https://library.unc.edu/2020/04/upcoming-elsevier-cancellations |publisher=Univeristy of North Carolina |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>. Rather than extend the license which was stated to cost $2.6 million annually, the university decided to continue subscribing to a smaller set of individual journals. The [[State University of New York]] Libraries Consortium also announced similar outcome.<ref>{{Cite news|publisher=Inside Highered|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/quicktakes/2020/04/13/suny-cancels-big-deal-elsevier|title=SUNY Cancels Big Deal With Elsevier|date=April 13, 2020|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|publisher=SUNY Libraries Consortium (SLC)|title=State University of New York Steps Away From the \u201cBig Deal\u201d with Elsevier|url=http://slcny.libguides.com/slc/elsevier2020update|date=April 7, 2020|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Dissemination of research ==\n\n=== Lobbying efforts against open access ===\nElsevier have been known to be involved in lobbying against [[open access]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.opensecrets.org/lobby/clientsum.php?id=D000067394&year=2017|title=Lobbying Spending Database - RELX Group, 2017|website=Opensecrets.org|language=en|access-date=2017-08-30}}</ref> These have included the likes of:\n* The [[Federal Research Public Access Act]] (FRPPA)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.taxpayeraccess.org/issues/frpaa/index.shtml|title=Federal Research Public Access Act (Alliance for Taxpayer Access)|website=Taxpayeraccess.org|language=en|access-date=2017-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.chronicle.com/article/Legislation-to-Bar/130949/|title=Legislation to Bar Public-Access Requirement on Federal Research Is Dead|date=2012-02-27|work=The Chronicle of Higher Education|access-date=2017-03-25}}</ref> \n* The [[Research Works Act]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thinkprogress.org/how-corporations-score-big-profits-by-limiting-access-to-publicly-funded-academic-research-fcee09671b22#.joxfvmi94|title=How Corporations Score Big Profits By Limiting Access To Publicly Funded Academic Research|date=2013-03-03|work=ThinkProgress|access-date=2017-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2012/02/15/the-dangerous-research-works-act/|title=The Dangerous \"Research Works Act\"|last=Contributor|website=TechCrunch|access-date=2017-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2016/01/elsevier-academic-publishing-petition/427059/|title=Academics Want You to Read Their Work for Free|last=Hu|first=Jane C.|work=The Atlantic|access-date=2017-03-25|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elsevier.com/about/company-information/policies/message-on-the-research-works-act|title=Message on the Research Works Act|last=Elsevier|website=Elsevier.com|language=en|access-date=2017-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/future_tense/2012/02/28/research_works_act_elsevier_and_politicians_back_down_from_open_access_threat_.html|title=Scientists' Victory Over the Research Works Act Is Like the SOPA Defeat|last=Kakaes|first=Konstantin|date=2012-02-28|work=Slate|access-date=2017-03-25|language=en-US|issn=1091-2339}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://boingboing.net/2012/02/28/elsevier-withdraws-support-fro.html|title=Elsevier withdraws support from Research Works Act, bill collapses|date=2012-02-28|website=Boing Boing|access-date=2017-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2012/jan/16/academic-publishers-enemies-science|title=Academic publishers have become the enemies of science|date=2012-01-16|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-03-26|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> \n* PRISM.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://scienceblogs.com/transcript/2007/01/27/elsevier-wiley-are-getting-pr/|title=Elsevier, Wiley are getting PR advice from Eric Dezenhall|work=Transcription and Translation|access-date=2017-03-25|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dyer|first=Owen|date=2007-02-03|title=Publishers hire PR heavyweight to defend themselves against open access|journal=BMJ: British Medical Journal|volume=334|issue=7587|pages=227|doi=10.1136/bmj.39112.439051.DB|issn=0959-8138|pmc=1790741|pmid=17272546}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.sciencemag.org/news/2013/06/scientific-publishers-offer-solution-white-houses-public-access-mandate|title=Scientific Publishers Offer Solution to White House's Public Access Mandate|date=2013-06-04|journal=Science|access-date=2017-03-25|language=en}}</ref> In the case of PRISM, the [[Association of American Publishers]] hired [[Eric Dezenhall]], the so-called \"Pit Bull Of Public Relations\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2006-04-16/the-pit-bull-of-public-relations|title=\"The Pit Bull Of Public Relations\" - Bloomberg|date=2006-04-17|work=Bloomberg.com|access-date=2017-03-25}}</ref>\n* [[Horizon 2020]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/muscle-from-brussels-as-open-access-gets-an-80bn-boost/419949.article|title=Muscle from Brussels as open access gets an \u20ac80bn boost|date=2012-05-17|work=Times Higher Education (THE)|access-date=2017-03-26|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gowers.wordpress.com/2012/05/17/horizon-2020-to-promote-open-access/|title=Horizon 2020 to promote open access|date=2012-05-17|website=Gowers's Weblog|access-date=2017-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.sciencemag.org/news/2012/05/horizon-2020-80-billion-battlefield-open-access|title=Horizon 2020: A \u20ac80 Billion Battlefield for Open Access|date=2012-05-24|journal=Science|access-date=2017-03-26|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2012/05/17/european-union-links-research-grants-open-access|title=European Union links research grants to open access|access-date=2017-03-26}}</ref>\n* [[Office of Science and Technology Policy]] (OSTP)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/inside-higher-ed-big-push-for-open-access/2002057.article|title=Inside Higher Ed: Big push for open access|date=2013-02-26|work=Times Higher Education (THE)|access-date=2017-03-26|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/elsevier-distances-itself-from-open-access-article/2004055.article|title=Elsevier distances itself from open-access article|date=2013-05-22|work=Times Higher Education (THE)|access-date=2017-03-26|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thinkprogress.org/how-corporations-score-big-profits-by-limiting-access-to-publicly-funded-academic-research-fcee09671b22#.u06x7x9zu|title=How Corporations Score Big Profits By Limiting Access To Publicly Funded Academic Research|date=2013-03-03|work=ThinkProgress|access-date=2017-03-26}}</ref>\n* The [[European Union]]'s [[Open science|Open Science]] Monitor was criticised after Elsevier were confirmed as a subcontractor.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20180402/09131239544/hated-science-publisher-elsevier-to-help-eu-monitor-open-science-including-open-access.shtml|title=Hated Science Publisher Elsevier To Help EU Monitor Open Science - Including Open Access|work=Techdirt.|access-date=2018-04-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Lykkja|first1=P\u00e5l Magnus|last2=Myklebust|first2=Jan Petter|title=Open science in the EU \u2013 Will the astroturfers take over?|url=http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=20180317044918836|website=University World News|accessdate=2018-04-13|date=17 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Selling open access articles ===\nIn 2014, 2015, 2016 and 2017,<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=2018-04-30|title=Hybrid open access is unreliable|url=http://rossmounce.co.uk/2017/02/20/hybrid-open-access-is-unreliable/|author=Ross Mounce|date=2017-02-20}}</ref> Elsevier was found to be selling some articles which should have been open access, but had been put behind a paywall.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/news/elsevier-bumps-on-road-to-open-access/2012238.article |title=Elsevier: bumps on road to open access |work=[[Times Higher Education]] |date=27 March 2014 |accessdate=9 March 2015 |last1=Jump |first1=Paul}}</ref> A related case occurred in 2015, when Elsevier charged for downloading an open access article from a journal published by [[John Wiley & Sons]]. However, it was not clear whether Elsevier was in violation of the license under which the article was made available on their website.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://creativecommons.org/weblog/entry/45175 |title=Are commercial publishers wrongly selling access to openly licensed scholarly articles? |work=Creative Commons News|date=13 March 2015 |accessdate=14 March 2015 |last1=Vollmer |first1=Timothy}}</ref>\n\n===Action against academics posting their own articles online===\n\nIn 2013, [[Digimarc]], a company representing Elsevier, told the [[University of Calgary]] to remove articles published by faculty authors on university web pages; although such [[self-archiving]] of academic articles may be legal under the [[fair dealing]] provisions in Canadian [[copyright law]],<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=2018-05-01|title=Elsevier Ramps Up Its War On Access To Knowledge|url=https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20131218/00393725601/elsevier-ramps-up-its-war-access-to-knowledge.shtml|newspaper=[[Techdirt]]|author= Mike Masnick}}</ref> the university complied. [[Harvard University]] and the [[University of California, Irvine]] also received [[Notice and take down|takedown notices]] for self-archived academic articles, a first for Harvard, according to [[Peter Suber]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Peterson|first1=Andrea|title=How one publisher is stopping academics from sharing their research|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/the-switch/wp/2013/12/19/how-one-publisher-is-stopping-academics-from-sharing-their-research/|accessdate=6 January 2015|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=19 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Masnick|first1=Mike|title=Elsevier Ramps Up Its War On Access To Knowledge|url=https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20131218/00393725601/elsevier-ramps-up-its-war-access-to-knowledge.shtml|accessdate=6 January 2015|work=[[Techdirt]]|date=20 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-switch/wp/2013/12/19/how-one-publisher-is-stopping-academics-from-sharing-their-research/|title=How one publisher is stopping academics from sharing their research|website=Washington Post|access-date=2017-03-26}}</ref>\n\nMonths after its acquisition of [[Academia.edu]] rival [[Mendeley]], Elsevier sent thousands of [[takedown notice]]s to Academia.edu, a practice that has since ceased following widespread complaint by academics, according to Academia.edu founder and chief executive Richard Price.<ref name=\"Parr2014\">{{cite journal|last1=Parr|first1=Chris|title=Sharing is a way of life for millions on Academia.edu|journal=Times Higher Education|date=12 June 2014|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/news/sharing-is-a-way-of-life-for-millions-on-academiaedu/2013839.article?nopaging=1 |accessdate=14 September 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Howard2013\">{{cite journal|last1=Howard|first1=Jennifer|title=Posting Your Latest Article? You Might Have to Take It Down|journal=The Chronicle of Higher Education|date=6 December 2013|url=http://chronicle.com/blogs/wiredcampus/posting-your-latest-article-you-might-have-to-take-it-down/48865|accessdate=14 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter Elsevier acquired the repository [[SSRN]] in May 2016 academics started complaining that some of their work has been removed without notice. The action was explained as a technical error.<ref>Mike Masnick [https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20160718/02211935003/just-as-open-competitor-to-elseviers-ssrn-launches-ssrn-accused-copyright-crackdown.shtml ''SSRN accused of copyright crackdown''], Techdirt.</ref>\n\n===Sci-Hub and LibGen lawsuit===\n\nIn 2015 Elsevier filed a lawsuit against the sites [[Sci-Hub]] and [[Library Genesis|LibGen]], which make copyright protected articles available for free. Elsevier also claimed illegal access to institutional accounts.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.stephenmclaughlin.net/2016/03/18/elsevier-v-sci-hub-on-the-docket/ |title=Elsevier v. Sci-Hub on the docket |first=Stephen Reid |last=McLaughlin |date=18 March 2016 |access-date=2016-06-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/simba-information-five-professional-publishing-news-events-of-2015-signal-times-are-a-changin-300194611.html|title = Simba Information: Five Professional Publishing News Events of 2015 Signal Times Are A-Changin'|date =17 December 2015 |accessdate = 28 June 2016 |website = PR Newswire }}</ref>\n\n===Rejection of the Initiative for Open Citations===\nAmong the major academic publishers, Elsevier alone declined to join the [[Initiative for Open Citations]]. In the context of the resignation of the ''[[Journal of Informetrics]]''' editorial board, Elsevier stated:<ref name=\"Elsevier\">{{cite web|url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/about-the-resignation-of-the-journal-of-informetrics-editorial-board|title=About the resignation of the Journal of Informetrics Editorial Board|date=15 January 2019|last = Reller|first = Tom|work=Elsevier Connect|accessdate=15 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote|Elsevier invests significantly in citation extraction technology. While these are made available to those who wish to license this data, Elsevier cannot make such a large corpus of data, to which it has added significant value, available for free.}}\n\n==Imprints==\n\nElsevier uses its [[Imprint (trade name)|imprint]]s (that is, [[Brand|brand names]] used in publishing) to market to different consumer segments. Many of the imprints have previously been the names of publishing companies that were purchased by Reed Elsevier.\n\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* [[Academic Press]]\n* Bailli\u00e8re Tindall\n* BC Decker\n* [[Butterworth\u2013Heinemann]]\n* CMP\n* [[Cell Press]]\n* [[Churchill Livingstone]]\n* Digital Press\n* Elsevier\n* [[Gulf Professional Publishing]]\n* GW Medical Publishing\n* Hanley & Belfus\n* [[Masson (publisher)|Masson]]\n* [[Medicine Publishing]]\n* [[Morgan Kaufmann Publishers]]\n* [[Mosby (publisher)|Mosby]]\n* Newnes\n* North-Holland Publishing Company\n* [[Pergamon Press]]\n* Pergamon Flexible Learning\n* [[Saunders (publisher)|Saunders]]\n* Syngress\n* Urban & Fischer\n* [[William Andrew (publisher)|William Andrew]]\n* [[Woodhead Publishing]] (including Chandos and Horwood)\n}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Netherlands|Companies|Books}}\n* [[List of Elsevier periodicals]]\n* [[2collab]], a free researcher collaboration tool launched by Elsevier in 2007 and discontinued in 2011\n* [[Sci-Hub]], a website providing free access to otherwise paywalled academic papers on a massive scale that is involved in a legal case with Elsevier\n{{clear}}\n\n== References ==\n=== Citations ===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |ref = harv |last = Groen |first = Frances K. |title = Access to medical knowledge : libraries, digitization, and the public good |year = 2007 |publisher = Scarecrow Press |location = Lanham, Mar. |isbn = 978-0-8108-52723 |page = 217 }}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Elsevier}}\n*{{Official website}}\n*[http://www.caat.org.uk/issues/arms-fairs/reed-elsevier/ Campaign success: Reed Elsevier sells international arms fairs]\n*{{cite web |title=Reed Elsevier Timeline |url=http://www.ulib.niu.edu/publishers/index.htm |work=The Academic Publishing Industry: A Story of Merger and Acquisition |author=Mary H. Munroe |year=2004 |via=Northern Illinois University |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141020153836/http://www.ulib.niu.edu/publishers/Holtzbrinck.htm |archivedate=20 October 2014 |df=dmy-all}}\n\n{{Reed Elsevier|state=collapsed}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Elsevier| ]]\n[[Category:1880 establishments in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Academic publishing companies]]\n[[Category:Bibliographic database providers]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Amsterdam]]\n[[Category:Multinational companies headquartered in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Publishing companies established in 1880]]\n[[Category:Publishing companies of the Netherlands]]\n", "name_user": "Vanisaac", "label": "safe", "comment": "Correcting spelling: univeristy->university", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elsevier"}
{"title_page": "Tom's Restaurant", "text_new": "{{Infobox restaurant\n| name              = Tom's Restaurant\n| logo              =\n| logo_width        =\n| logo_alt          =\n| image             = Tom's_Restaurant,_NYC.jpg\n| image_width       = 280px\n| image_alt         =\n| image_caption     = Tom's Restaurant in 2000\n| pushpin_map       =\n| map_width         =\n| map_alt           =\n| map_caption       =\n| slogan            =\n| established       =\n| closed            = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| current-owner     =\n| chef              =\n| head-chef         =\n| food-type         =\n| dress-code        =\n| rating            =\n| street-address    = 2880 [[Broadway (Manhattan)|Broadway]]<br>[[Morningside Heights, Manhattan|Morningside Heights]], [[Manhattan]]\n| city              = [[New York City]]\n| county            =\n| state             = [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| postcode          =\n| country           =\n| coordinates       =\n| seating-capacity  =\n| reservations      =\n| other-locations   =\n| other-information =\n| website           = {{URL|tomsrestaurant.net|TomsRestaurant.net}}\n}}\n[[File:Tom's Restaurant (Manhattan, New York) P001.jpg|thumb|right|285 px|Tom's Restaurant interior]]\n'''Tom's Restaurant''' is a [[diner]] located at 2880 [[Broadway (Manhattan)|Broadway]] (on the corner of West [[112th Street]]) in the [[Morningside Heights, Manhattan|Morningside Heights]] neighborhood of [[Manhattan]] in [[New York City]],<ref name=\"nytimes\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/restaurants/1002207994638/toms-restaurant/details.html|title=Tom's Restaurant|work=New York Times|accessdate=4 April 2013}}</ref> and on the ground floor of [[Columbia University]]'s Armstrong Hall, home to the [[Goddard Institute for Space Studies]]. Frequented by Columbia students and faculty, it has been owned and operated by the [[Greek American|Greek-American]] family of Minas Zoulis since the 1940s.<ref name=\"vines\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=newsarchive&sid=aQX.iN_G21k8&refer=home |title=Real 'Seinfeld' Restaurant Is New York Staple |last=Vines |first=Richard |date=2008-03-13 |publisher=Bloomberg |accessdate=4 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nTom's Restaurant was the locale that inspired [[Suzanne Vega]]'s 1987 [[song]] \"[[Tom's Diner]].\"<ref name=\"vines\" /> Later, its exterior was used as a stand-in for the fictional [[Monk's Caf\u00e9]] in the [[television]] [[Situation comedy|sitcom]] ''[[Seinfeld]]'', where [[comedian]] [[Jerry Seinfeld]]'s [[Jerry Seinfeld (character)|eponymous character]] and his friends regularly gathered to eat.<ref name=\"nytimes\" /><ref name=\"vines\" /> The interior shown on the television show, however, looked very little like the real \"Tom's\", as indoor scenes were filmed on a set in [[Los Angeles]].<ref name=\"vines\" />\n\nEarly ''Seinfeld'' episodes showed the entire neon sign; later, the \"Tom's\" portion was cropped out, showing only the \"RESTAURANT\" wraparound. Even though the interior and exterior have undergone minor remodeling since the show, the distinctive sign has remained the same. Tom's is featured in \"Kramer's Reality Tour\" conducted by [[Kenny Kramer]].\n\n[[US Senator|Senator]] [[John McCain]] often ate at Tom's when he visited his daughter [[Meghan McCain|Meghan]] when she was a student at Columbia.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://allday.today.com/_news/2008/09/09/4377908-11-questions-for-meghan-mccain |title=11 questions for Meghan McCain |date=2008-09-09 |work=Allday.Today.com |accessdate=4 April 2013}}</ref> Likewise, [[Barack Obama]] frequented the restaurant as a student at Columbia.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/01/20/recollections-of-obamas-ex-roommate/|title=Recollections of Obama's Ex-Roommate |date=2009-01-20 |work=New York Times |accessdate=11 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nPrior to ''Seinfeld'', Tom's exterior had been seen on television in the 1978 ''[[The Bionic Woman]]'' episode \"Long Live the King\" at around the 27 minute mark of the DVD release.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of restaurants in New York City]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* [http://www.tomsrestaurant.net Tom's Restaurant Official Homepage]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nLedFWpF9EA Video shows Suzanne Vega talking about the Tom's Restaurant]\n* [http://www.morningside-heights.net/toms.htm Morningside Heights: Tom's Restaurant]\n* [http://www.virtualnyc.info/panopages/west/toms-rest.htm  VirtualNYC panoramic image of Tom's Restaurant]\n* [https://maps.google.com/?ie=UTF8&ll=40.80537,-73.965561&spn=0,359.998273&t=h&z=19&layer=c&cbll=40.805411,-73.965661&panoid=7ioLPjtm9kB26kw7TyKEAA&cbp=12,84.67786569807919,,0,5.9511790126069215 Google Street View: 112th Street and Broadway]\n\n{{Coord|40|48|20|N|73|57|56|W|region:US-NY_type:landmark_source:dewiki|display=title}}\n\n{{Morningside Heights, Manhattan}}\n\n[[Category:Coffee houses of the United States]]\n[[Category:Morningside Heights, Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Restaurants in Manhattan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox restaurant\n| name              = Tom's Restaurant\n| logo              =\n| logo_width        =\n| logo_alt          =\n| image             = Tom's_Restaurant,_NYC.jpg\n| image_width       = 280px\n| image_alt         =\n| image_caption     = Tom's Restaurant in 2000\n| pushpin_map       =\n| map_width         =\n| map_alt           =\n| map_caption       =\n| slogan            =\n| established       =\n| closed            = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| current-owner     =\n| chef              =\n| head-chef         =\n| food-type         =\n| dress-code        =\n| rating            =\n| street-address    = 2880 [[Broadway (Manhattan)|Broadway]]<br>[[Morningside Heights, Manhattan|Morningside Heights]], [[Manhattan]]\n| city              = [[New York City]]\n| county            =\n| state             = [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| postcode          =\n| country           =\n| coordinates       =\n| seating-capacity  =\n| reservations      =\n| other-locations   =\n| other-information =\n| website           = {{URL|tomsrestaurant.net|TomsRestaurant.net}}\n}}\n[[File:Tom's Restaurant (Manhattan, New York) P001.jpg|thumb|right|285 px|Tom's Restaurant interior]]\n'''Tom's Restaurant''' is a [[diner]] located at 2880 [[Broadway (Manhattan)|Broadway]] (on the corner of West [[112th Street]]) in the [[Morningside Heights, Manhattan|Morningside Heights]] neighborhood of [[Manhattan]] in [[New York City]],<ref name=\"nytimes\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/restaurants/1002207994638/toms-restaurant/details.html|title=Tom's Restaurant|work=New York Times|accessdate=4 April 2013}}</ref> and on the ground floor of [[Columbia University]]'s Armstrong Hall, home to the [[Goddard Institute for Space Studies]]. Frequented by Columbia students and faculty, it has been owned and operated by the [[Greek American|Greek-American]] family of Minas Zoulis since the 1940s.<ref name=\"vines\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=newsarchive&sid=aQX.iN_G21k8&refer=home |title=Real 'Seinfeld' Restaurant Is New York Staple |last=Vines |first=Richard |date=2008-03-13 |publisher=Bloomberg |accessdate=4 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nTom's Restaurant was the locale that inspired [[Suzanne Vega]]'s 1987 [[song]] \"[[Tom's Diner]].\"<ref name=\"vines\" /> Later, its exterior was used as a stand-in for the fictional [[Monk's Caf\u00e9]] in the [[television]] [[Situation comedy|sitcom]] ''[[Seinfeld]]'', where [[comedian]] [[Jerry Seinfeld]]'s [[Jerry Seinfeld (character)|eponymous character]] and his friends regularly gathered to eat.<ref name=\"nytimes\" /><ref name=\"vines\" /> The interior shown on the television show, however, looked very little like the real \"Tom's\", as indoor scenes were filmed on a set in [[Los Angeles]].<ref name=\"vines\" />\n\nEarly ''Seinfeld'' episodes showed the entire neon sign; later, the \"Tom's\" portion was cropped out, showing only the \"RESTAURANT\" wraparound. Even though the interior and exterior have undergone minor remodeling since the show, the distinctive sign has remained the same. Tom's is featured in \"Kramer's Reality Tour\" conducted by [[Kenny Kramer]].\n\n[[US Senator|Senator]] [[John McCain]] often ate at Tom's when he visited his daughter [[Meghan McCain|Meghan]] when she was a student at Columbia.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://allday.today.com/_news/2008/09/09/4377908-11-questions-for-meghan-mccain |title=11 questions for Meghan McCain |date=2008-09-09 |work=Allday.Today.com |accessdate=4 April 2013}}</ref> Likewise, [[Barack Obama]] frequented the restaurant as a student at Columbia.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/01/20/recollections-of-obamas-ex-roommate/|title=Recollections of Obama's Ex-Roommate |date=2009-01-20 |work=New York Times |accessdate=11 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nPrior to ''Seinfeld'', Tom's exterior had been seen on television in the 1978 ''[[The Bionic Woman]]'' episode \"Long Live the King\" at around the 27 minute mark of the DVD release.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of restaurants in New York City]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* [http://www.tomsrestaurant.net Tom's Restaurant Official Homepage]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nLedFWpF9EA Video shows Suzanne Vega talking about the Tom's Restaurant]\n* [http://www.morningside-heights.net/toms.htm Morningside Heights: Tom's Restaurant]\n* [http://www.virtualnyc.info/panopages/west/toms-rest.htm  VirtualNYC panoramic image of Tom's Restaurant]\n* [https://maps.google.com/?ie=UTF8&ll=40.80537,-73.965561&spn=0,359.998273&t=h&z=19&layer=c&cbll=40.805411,-73.965661&panoid=7ioLPjtm9kB26kw7TyKEAA&cbp=12,84.67786569807919,,0,5.9511790126069215 Google Street View: 112th Street and Broadway]\n\n{{Coord|40|48|20|N|73|57|56|W|region:US-NY_type:landmark_source:dewiki|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Coffee houses of the United States]]\n[[Category:Morningside Heights, Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Restaurants in Manhattan]]\n", "name_user": "Epicgenius", "label": "safe", "comment": "add template", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tom%27s_Restaurant"}
